<TD ROWSPAN=8>
<H3><a name="top">News Releases</a></h3>
<h1>Program News</H1>
<HR>
<H3><B>Wisconsin Sea Grant</B></H3>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<CENTER>

<H3>Communications</H3>



<H1>Earthwatch Helps Public Tune In On Environment</H1>

</CENTER>

After 22 years, 5,700 radio programs, three published collections of scripts, and 10 major awards from environmental and educational organizations, Wisconsin Sea Grant's Earthwatch Public Service Radio Program continues to provide a huge and growing national radio audience with sharp, concise programs about the environment and science, particularly about the Great 

<P>

<H2>Lakes and the oceans</H2>



Earthwatch is a weekly series of five, two-minute programs produced by the Sea Grant Institute and the Institute for Environmental Studies at the University of Wisconsin-Madison.  Every two weeks, institute staff and student writers prepare and record 10 Earthwatch programs and distribute them on cassette tape free of charge to more than 150 radio stations throughout the Great Lakes region and beyond. The program's appeal is reflected in the fact that a third of these stations have carried the program for more than five years. 

<P>

Earthwatch's high quality has won it numerous awards, and in 1992 the United Nations Environment Programme added Earth-watch's name to its "Global 500 Roll of Honour" at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro.

<P>

<H2>22:1 Return on Investment </H2>



Although commercial radio is a fiercely competitive market, Earthwatch is currently given free airtime by 84 commercial radio stations throughout the country. 

<P>

This is particularly remarkable given that commercial stations no longer are required to provide public service programming and could otherwise sell that airtime to advertisers. The fact that so many commercial stations broadcast Earthwatch at their own expense provides further  evidence of the program's mass audience appeal.     

<P>

Market surveys indicate that the value of commercial radio airtime donated to Earthwatch in 1993 was $527,000 -- a 10:1 benefit: cost return on the annual investment of $52,000 federal Sea Grant dollars. The figure is even more impressive when noncommercial airtime is factored in. More than 80 noncommercial outlets -- including 75 radio stations and seven reading services for the blind -- also broadcast the program.  

<P>

In 1993, the estimated value of noncommercial airtime, based on the average price of two minutes of commercial airtime, totalled more than $588,000. Together, commercial and noncommercial airtime donated to Earthwatch totalled nearly $1.12 million for a benefit:cost return on the federal investment of more than 22:1.

<P>

<H2>Promotes Science Literacy</H2>



While Earthwatch is designed to promote public environmental literacy through the mass media, program scripts with lasting informational value have been recycled into books, and electronic copies are now available online as well. Three collections of Earth-watch scripts have been published under the title Earthwatching,  the most recent of which, Earthwatch-ing III, featured a teacher's guide. 

<P>

Earthwatch scripts produced since January 1990 are available to the estimated 20 million users of the Internet global computer network via the UW-Madison "gopher" information server. UW-Madison computer records show that nearly a thousand Internet users access this collection of scripts every month.

<P>















<P>

<B>For more information, contact:<BR>
Steve Wittman, Communications Leader, Wisconsin Sea Grant<br> 
Phone: (608) 263-5371, FAX: (608) 263-2063<br> 
Email: <a href="mailto:sherman@umbi.umd.edu, 
  swittman@seagrant.wisc.edu">swittman@seagrant.wisc.edu
</a><br>
or<BR>
Ben Sherman<br>
