<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(3)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
March 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 3
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Reducing Bycatch to Help Build Sustainable Fisheries</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>Reducing Bycatch to Help Build Sustainable Fisheries<H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>
Bycatch is the portion of a commercial catch that is not targeted and is either economically undesirable or is governmentally regulated and, therefore, cannot be landed. Bycatch is discarded at sea and often results in nearly 100 percent mortality. While the impact of bycatch-induced mortality on stock recruitment is unknown, the unhealthy condition of many of the world's fisheries is focusing attention on factors contributing to the decline of desirable stocks. Thus, the economically tenuous commercial fishing industry is becoming proactive in promoting methods to reduce bycatch both as a conservation measure and as a means to avoid even more restrictive regulations.
<P>
Closely coupled Sea Grant research and technology transfer is making progress in bycatch reduction. This effort is particularly important because bycatch caps are set for certain species. When the caps are met, the fisheries are closed even if the target species quota has not been landed. In the North Pacific, closures resulting from the cap placed on halibut bycatch cost approximately $100 million in lost fish and opportunity in 1991 alone. Therefore, Washington Sea Grant is conducting research to increase the precision of halibut bycatch mortality data and to develop methods to help halibut bycatch survive through better onboard handing.
<P>
The size of fish caught as bycatch in trawl fisheries is directly related to the shape and size of the mesh used for the targeted species. In the North Pacific, a project supported by Washington Sea Grant, industry, and the Alaska Fisheries Development Foundation recently demonstrated that undersize walleye pollock (bycatch) can escape larger mesh trawls even when a single load weighs 200,000 pounds. On the East Coast, net characteristics also influence bycatch in the mixed groundfish fishery. All species respond differently to stimuli created by the net and provide challenges to scientific understanding, but further work on species and general fish size selection should result in predictive models for specific fishery applications.
<P>
Sea Grant research on selective gear has already cause changes in fishing practices. Work by Maine-New Hampshire and Rhode Island Sea Grant programs has contributed to the development of a shrimp separator trawl used in North Atlantic waters that reduces bycatch of small groundfish. As a result, many New England states have passed shrimping regulations requiring separator trawls to be used in state waters. In addition, based on Virginia Sea Grant research to reduce bycatch of undersize scallops, the New England Fishery Management Council has amended its Sea Scallop Fishery Management Plan to incorporate use of dredge rings of a larger size.
<P>
In the Southeast and Gulf of Mexico shrimp fishery, trawls with small mesh are used to retain shrimp, causing as many as 10 pounds of undersize finfish bycatch to be taken for each pound of shrimp. To help reduce this disproportionate amount of bycatch, Georgia, Louisiana, MIT, Mississippi-Alabama, North Carolina, and Texas Sea Grant programs have conducted tow tank experiments, diver observations, remote video observations, and experimental trawling to develop bycatch reduction devices (BRDs).
<P>
The simplest type of BRD is the fish-eye, a metal support sewn into the codend of a net to hold open a hole that allows finfish to escape. Bycatch of some species such as redfish and croaker can be reduced over 50 percent when BRDs are used, but their performance is highly variable. The loss of shrimp when using BRDs is of continuing concern to shrimpers. In replicated fishing experiments with NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service and concerned shrimpers, Georgia Sea Grant has identified some causes of shrimp loss in BRDs that can be corrected.
<P>
The bycatch of marine mammals in various set net fisheries is an extremely volatile issue. Maine-New Hampshire and Alaska Sea Grant specialists are experimenting with subtle underwater sound to warn mammals about the presence of fishing nets. Preliminary results are encouraging. In Alaska, documentation of marine mammal interactions with specific fisheries has helped managers and industry focus limited resources on the most important bycatch issues so that changes in fishing practices will have the greatest impact.
<P>
A national conference convened by Alaska and Oregon Sea Grant in 1992 resulted in fishing industry leaders agreeing to work together on bycatch. In the future, Sea Grant will continue its work with NMFS and fishermen to reduce bycatch in the more intractable fisheries such as mixed groundfish and shrimp. In addition, Sea Grant is providing leadership through a Rhode Island Sea Grant scientist who is serving on an international working group to address the problems of bycatch. All of this work is important to NOAA's goal of building a sustainable U.S. fishery. (For details, Bud Griswold, 301/713-2431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

