<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 1(4)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
December 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 4
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Biotechnology: Combatting Marine Pathogens</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Biotechnology: Combatting Marine Pathogens</H2>
</CENTER>

Many viruses and bacteria in marine and coastal waters contaminate aquatic animals and cause illness in humans. Other pathogens cause disease in fish and shellfish and are responsible for large-scale mortality of animals in natural fisheries and aquacultural operations. While some of these pathogens are indigenous to aquatic environments, others are present because of pollution. Sea Grant scientists are taking several paths to solving problems associated with marine pathogens. 
<P>
In Alabama, Louisiana and North Carolina, Sea Grant researchers are working on rapid and unequivocal assays for pathogens in seafood. Using DNA technology, they are developing practical methods to detect Hepatitis A Virus and "Vibrio" and "Salmonella" bacteria that oysters and clams can filter from polluted waters. Taking a different approach, Rhode Island Sea Grant researchers are using antibody technology to develop biosensors that directly detect pathogens in seafood. 
<P>
At California Sea Grant, scientists are developing methods to precisely delineate polluted coastal waters so that bans on fishing and recreation can be restricted to the smallest possible areas. They are attempting to use gene probes to provide characteristic profiles of the bacterial and viral populations in unpolluted areas. These will be compared to profiles of waters that can be polluted by sewage effluents, storm water runoff, and harbor discharges. 
<P>
To prevent spread of disease and ensure that healthy stocks are used in aquaculture, Sea Grant scientists in Maine, Minnesota, New York, and Oregon are developing diagnostic tests for several diseases. These include an enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay to diagnose bacterial kidney disease (BKD); a test, providing a reading within minutes, for infectious necrosis virus in finfish tissue samples; an antibody test for a rickettsial disease; and a procedure for detecting infectious pancreatic necrosis virus (IPNV) in hatchery facilities. Oregon researchers already have developed an effective vaccine for IPNV and are attempting to clone interleukins of rainbow trout so that they can be evaluated as general immunostimulants to combat many salmonid diseases. 
<P>
Other Sea Grant programs are also working on vaccines to combat fish diseases. BKD affects Atlantic and Pacific salmon worldwide. Because antibiotics currently approved for use in aquaculture do not inhibit BKD, researchers in Washington are developing a vaccine for the disease. In Maine, researchers are creating a single finfish vaccine against two diseases that spread rapidly in high density aquaculture. By using genetically engineered bacteria, the researchers plan to develop methods to produce, on a practical scale, a bivalent vaccine against a lethal "Vibrio" bacterium and the virus that causes pancreatic necrosis. 
<P>
Hawaii Sea Grant scientists have developed techniques to culture the virus that causes runt-deformity syndrome and is responsible for enormous losses in crustacean aquaculture. Building on this research, Arizona scientists developed a DNA probe for diagnosing the disease. The test is used to certify health of crustacean brood stocks and juveniles headed for grow-out facilities. It will help protect natural fishery stocks by preventing inadvertent introduction of the disease to new areas. 
<P>
Sea Grant also is conducting research to counteract pathogens in natural fisheries. Dermo and MSX are parasitic diseases that have almost destroyed the oyster fishery in Chesapeake Bay. To control a parasitic disease, its natural history and its cellular interaction with hosts must first be determined. Recently, Maryland Sea Grant scientists and researchers at two other centers independently took a major step in this direction by developing a technique to culture pure, reproductive strains of the dermo parasite in the laboratory. The new culture technique is expected to be a key to defining dermo's infective processes and to devising a strategy for protecting oysters from it. Other researchers in Maryland and Virginia are working on practical methods to introduce MSX-resistant oysters to the Bay. 
<P>
In developing new technologies for ensuring public safety, Sea Grant scientists will advance the molecular sciences and apply state-of-the-art technology to solving problems that inhibit development of aquaculture and use of fishery resources. This area of research will continue to receive attention as $3.2 million in new NOAA Sea Grant funding is awarded in 1994 for projects in marine biotechnology (For details, David Attaway, 301/713-2451 or <A HREF="mailto:dattaway@rdc.noaa.gov">dattaway@rdc.noaa.gov</A>) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

