<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 4(4)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
October 1996<BR>
Volume 4, Number 4
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Coastal Erosion Study Results in Action
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Research and Education Program Developed to Save Greenwich Bay
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Coastal Erosion Study Results in Action
</H2>
</CENTER>
Along certain areas of the Texas coast, erosion is a severe problem.  It was so severe at Sargent Beach in Matagorda County that only 600 feet of land separated the Gulf and the Gulf Intercoastal Waterway (GIWW).  As the erosion continued, the county¹s <A HREF="http://texas-sea-grant.tamu.edu/">Texas Sea Grant</A> outreach specialist became increasingly concerned as block after block of homes disappeared into the Gulf.  He also worried that one large hurricane could easily breech this land strip, cutting off waterborne commerce on the GIWW and destroying thousands of acres of valuable wetlands as well as the bay system ecology.
<P>
Major industries such as mining, chemical manufacturing, and petroleum refining depend on water transportation.  Because of the GIWW, these industries, along with their respective payrolls and tax payments, have located along the Texas coast.
<P>
To acquaint the public, industry, business, and government of the consequences of ignoring this erosion problem, the Texas Sea Grant outreach specialist organized meetings and workshops.  He also raised money to have an economic study conducted.  The study showed that, in Texas, the GIWW directly contributes more than $3 billion annually to the state¹s economy. In addition, the study indicated that closing of the waterway would cost the local economy $20 million a day and jeopardize about 150,000 jobs.
<P>
Information from this study caused the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to speed up its normal construction schedule for shore protection.  The Corps is now building a seven-mile-long seawall to protect Sargent Beach and to retard erosion before the Gulf breaks through. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Research and Education Program Developed to Save Greenwich Bay
</H2>
</CENTER>
Greenwich Bay, a 15-square mile estuary in Rhode Island, faces critical problems such as deteriorating water quality, closed fisheries, and increased conflict over use of limited space. Although local and state governments were prepared to take action to stop the bay¹s pollution and sustain its fishery, little was known about the bay as an ecosystem.  In addition, many of the citizens serving on the local volunteer boards and commissions lacked the knowledge necessary to make well-integrated local land use and waterfront decisions.  
<P>
To provide these volunteers with the information they needed to set priorities and guide decisions, <A HREF="http://seagrant.gso.uri.edu/riseagrant">Rhode Island Sea Grant</A> has launched a multi-faceted program combining research and education. The research component of this program focuses on the fate and transport of pollutants in Greenwich Bay and on translating this knowledge to improve management of the bay and its resources.  The focus of the education component has been on translating this knowledge to improve management of the bay and its resources. 
<P>
Before beginning the educational facet of the program, local and state officials in the watershed were contacted to assess their training needs. An eight-week Sea Grant educational course was then developed and conducted by a project coordinator from the University of Rhode Island¹s Coastal Resources Center.  Central to this course was a training manual that covered information pertinent to the issues affecting the bay. 
<P>
Twenty-eight members of three Rhode Island town boards and commissions in Warwick, East Greenwich, and North Kingstown recently completed this eight-week course.  These officials are now better equipped to deal with the sophisticated technical issues involved in making wise decisions on the future of Greenwich Bay. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">William Graham</A>, 301-713-2448)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

