<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
November 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 6
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Research Provides New Tool for Alaska Fishery Managers</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Former Students Fill Top Spots in Academia, Government, and Industry</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research Provides New Tool for Alaska Fishery Managers
</H2>
</CENTER>
Hatchery pink and chum salmon returning to Juneau area waters last summer had a unique new bar code imprinted on their inner ear bone. These codes were imprinted through a method adapted by <A HREF="http://www.uaf.alaska.edu/seagrant/">Alaska Sea Grant</A> that takes advantage of a natural process in the fish.
<P>
Newborn salmon add a new layer to the otolith (inner ear bone) each day. These layers, some light and some dark, resemble a bar code when viewed through a microscope. Scientists at Cornell University and Uppsala University in Sweden discovered that by raising and lowering the water temperature as little as two degrees they could artificially put more easily recognizable layers on the otolith. 
<P>
Five years ago, Alaska Sea Grant researchers, in partnership with the Douglas Island Pink and Chum Hatchery (DIPAC), adapted the bar coding process for large-scale use in Alaska hatcheries. Since then, millions of young salmon released at the DIPAC hatchery have been imprinted. 
<P>
State fishery managers use the code to distinguish wild and hatchery salmon stocks. Now that all members of a cohort group can be identified, more data can be collected to aid managers in making decisions. In addition, hatchery managers use the code for problems such as determining how their stocks are affecting local fisheries. 
<P>
Currently, the bar coding process is being used by other Southeast Alaska hatcheries. In the future, this new technology will also be used in Prince William Sound where the Prince William Sound Aquaculture Corporation will code hundreds of millions of its juvenile salmon to learn how wild and hatchery salmon can be better managed there. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:leon.cammen@rdc.noaa.gov">Leon Cammen</A>, 301/713-2435).
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Former Students Fill Top Spots in Academia, Government, and Industry
</H2>
</CENTER>
For the past 25 years, Sea Grant education has been making a difference. That is what a recently completed survey of former <A HREF="http://h2o.seagrant.wisc.edu/home.html">Wisconsin Sea Grant</A>-supported graduate students shows. 
<P>
The survey revealed the following:
<BR><UL>
<LI>In the last 25 years, these former students have received 396 graduate degrees (152 Ph.D.s and 244 Master¹s). 
<LI>These graduates work in 46 of the 50 United States as well as in 31 foreign countries. 
<LI>Forty-two percent of survey respondents currently work in the private sector, 35 percent in the academic sector,  and 21 percent in the public sector.
</UL><P>
Judging by their vitae, the Wisconsin Sea Grant-trained graduates have become national assets. They have joined the executive suites of major corporations, become senior scientists in government laboratories, started their own businesses, become professors and been elected to public office.
<P>
Positions held by these former students range from a laboratory director for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency to an eighth-grade science teacher to a director of environmental health and laboratories for a Midwestern city of 200,000.
<P>
And the benefits multiply. A former Wisconsin Sea Grant student, now a professor of marine geochemistry at the University of Michigan, estimates that to date he has taught oceanography to more than 3,000 undergraduates and instructed 500 more in his summer geology field research course. In addition, he has taught marine geochemistry to 100 graduate students and served as major professor for eight Ph.D. students and 15 Master¹s students, some of whom have received support from Michigan Sea Grant during their studies. 
<P>
The guiding philosophy of the Wisconsin Sea Grant education subprogram continues to be that education--especially graduate education--is a risk-free investment with an excellent rate of return. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">William Graham</A>, 301/713-2448).

<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

