<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(1)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Coral Reef Ecosystems - Protected Through Volunteer Program
</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Drilling for Oil Improved
</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]"> Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2> Coral Reef Ecosystems<BR>
Protected Through Volunteer Program
</H2>
</CENTER>
Honolulu's world-renowned Hanauma Bay attracts as many as 10,000 visitors a day. Over the years, such heavy use has taken its toll on the bay. Ninety percent of the nearshore coral reef has been killed, and fish populations have changed radically because of constant hand feeding. Realizing the need to reverse the damage to the marine life of the island's second most popular tourist attraction, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.hawaii.edu:70/1/seagrant">Hawaii Sea Grant</A> along with state and local government agencies and an environmental group created the Hanauma Bay Educational Program (HBEP).
<P>
HBEP is a volunteer-driven effort to increase public knowledge about island reef ecosystems and to promote the stewardship of Hanauma Bay and other coral reefs of Hawaii through public education. To accomplish this goal, specialists from Sea Grant and other organizations trained volunteers in conducting free natural history interpretive walks for visitors. Visitors are now taught the importance of minimizing their impact on the environment by not trampling on or collecting the delicate corals.
<P>
The program also includes a beach-side information desk and cleanup patrols. In addition, HBEP volunteers visit the islands' public schools to educate students about the fragility of coral reefs and to encourage stewardship of the entire marine ecosystem.
<P>
The combined undertakings in the schools and at the bay itself have proven surprisingly successful. The volunteers' cleanup patrols and educational efforts have helped to reduce pollution of the bay and stem the degradation of the nearshore reef. More visitors, for example, are now using waterproof sunscreen products whose chemical ingredients do not leach into the water and onto the living reefs. Also, most visitors have stopped feeding the fish inappropriate foods. The word has gotten out that bread, peas, and corn are not acceptable food for the fish. Visitors who bring these foods to the bay can now change them for a packet of "fish friendly" foods at the information desk staffed by HBEP volunteers.
<P>
Recently, HBEP was recognized for developing creative and practical environmental solutions to restore the reef at Hanauma Bay. It was awarded a 1993 Chevron Conservation Award from the nation's oldest privately-sponsored program for recognizing environmental role models. (For details, Bud Griswold, 301/713-2431)

<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2> Drilling for Oil Improved
</CENTER>
</H2>
Drilling is a substantial part of offshore petroleum production costs. Lost time caused by the failure of drill strings (long pipes with a drill at the end) in offshore areas can exceed $1 million per drill hole. Therefore, in 1986, an <A HREF="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/s/seagrant/www/mitsg.htm">MIT Sea Grant</A> researcher was asked by industry to apply knowledge gained from his Sea Grant-sponsored work on the vibration of marine cables and risers to problems associated with the dynamics of drill strings.
<P>
Building upon the results of previous Sea Grant supported research, one year's additional MIT Sea Grant funding served as seed which enabled an industry consortium-sponsored project to be initiated to solve the costly drill string failure problem. Afterwards, industry assumed full support of the project and, by the sixth year, the consortium had reached its peak membership of 14 companies in the United States, Europe, and Asia.
<P>
Greatly exceeding original expectations, the project not only resulted in reduced lost time, but also stimulated the establishment of a new surface-vibration measurement industry which monitors drilling performance by measurement of drill-string vibration. In addition, the project resulted in the identification of a destructive drill-bit vibration mechanism. This finding led engineers at AMOCO and Eastman-Christianson to invent a vibration-resistant bit which is now commercially available.
<P>
Along with these industrial developments, the MIT Sea Grant project also was instrumental in the graduate education of nine students, three of whom earned a Ph.D., five a masters degree, and one a postdoctoral. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/7l3-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

