<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(11)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
November 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 11
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Helping Coastal Managers Deal With Nutrient Overenrichment</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Helping Coastal Managers Deal With Nutrient Overenrichment</H2>
</CENTER>
Increasing coastal development has led to a reduction in water quality along much of the coast of the United States. Although toxic pollutants are problems in many areas, the Environmental Protection Agency has identified excess nutrients (eutrophication) as the major water quality problem in U. S. estuaries. Sea Grant has a long history of research and outreach activities addressing the eutrophication issue and, as a result, understanding of the behavior of nutrients in coastal environments has advanced significantly. However, many aspects of the problem still need to be better understood.
<P>
Sea Grant researchers in Rhode Island and North Carolina are addressing the effects of nutrients on shallow embayments, paying particular attention to the responses of seagrasses. In North Carolina, investigators are questioning whether the contrasting response of three seagrass species to increased levels of nutrients may lead to changes in composition of the seagrass communities. Rhode Island investigators have developed elaborate mesocosms, where an entire shallow-water ecosystem can be simulated, including sediment, plants, animals, and water. They are testing various scenarios of nutrient input and flushing rates to predict the impacts on coastal ponds of increased population density and changes in land use patterns.
<P>
Knowledge of nutrient cycling in the water column of estuaries and coastal waters has improved substantially, but gaps remain. For example, it is known that much of the nutrient inputs to coastal estuaries comes in the form of inorganic compounds, but scientists are just beginning to understand the significance of organic nutrient inputs. New Jersey Sea Grant researchers are assessing the impact of the large fraction of nitrogen that enters coastal estuaries in the form of dissolved organic matter. The results of this and similar studies may lead to a reevaluation of the strategy of concentrating nutrient reduction efforts on inorganic inputs.
<P>
North Carolina Sea Grant researchers are investigating the interplay of light and nutrients in controlling phytoplankton productivity. They are trying to predict the outcome of scenarios, such as an increase in agricultural runoff, where the increase in sediment input would result in more available nutrients but less available light. Other North Carolina investigators are assessing the impact of chronic, long-term increases in nutrients on estuarine and coastal ecosystems versus acute, short-term nutrient pulses such as those resulting from storm events.
<P>
Most eutrophication research has taken place in temperate estuaries, but tropical environments, such as coral reef ecosystems, are equally susceptible. In Florida, Sea Grant researchers are attempting to distinguish the effects of anthropogenic nutrient inputs on coral reef ecosystems from those due to natural inputs of nutrients from offshore waters. They are looking both at the reef systems as they exist now and at the historical response of the reefs as captured in the coral skeletons laid down during many years of growth. At Hawaii Sea Grant, the mechanism through which the corals take up nutrients from the waters that pass over the reefs is the subject of an investigation that will lead to better models for predicting the impact of nutrient increases.
<P>
Much of the information critical to developing and evaluating management responses to the nutrient problem comes from long-term monitoring programs. Although Sea Grant does not support environmental monitoring per se, there has always been interest in investigating novel approaches that would improve the efficiency or sensitivity of monitoring programs.
<P>
Currently, a Delaware Sea Grant researcher is developing techniques to use molecular probes on phytoplankton to measure the concentration of cellular proteins that respond to nutrient limitation. This assay would be extremely sensitive and could be carried out without the long incubations that are now necessary. Maryland Sea Grant investigators have developed indices for monitoring eutrophication that use oxygen measurements to follow whole ecosystem metabolism. Presently, they are modifying these indices for use in Chesapeake Bay to better account for the importance of the Bay's shallow-water regions.
<P>
The coastal management community needs more information and better tools with which to deal with the problem of nutrient overenrichment, and the Sea Grant network is responding to the challenge (For details, Leon Cammen, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:lcammen@rdc.noaa.gov">lcammen@rdc.noaa.gov</A)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

