<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(6)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
June 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 6
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">New Technology Promises Boost to Marine Aquaculture</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Technology Promises Boost to Marine Aquaculture</H2>
</CENTER>
Aquaculture is one of the fastest growing primary production sectors in the U.S. However, this country lags behind others in developing aquaculture's full economic potential, and it is only a modest competitor in the world marketplace. A major factor contributing to this limited development is the inability to dependably and cost-effectively culture the microscopic, single- celled marine algae needed to feed the larval stages of both marine shrimp and fish and all life stages of mollusks.
<P>
Traditionally, algal feed for aquaculture is grown in batches which requires using many culture tanks to ensure continuous production. This method is labor intensive and conducive to culture collapse since most facilities grow the algae outdoors where contamination occurs. In some marine hatcheries, the costs of producing the algae alone is as high as 50 percent of operating expenses.
<P>
Researchers at the Delaware and Texas Sea Grant programs had some success growing algae on a larger scale using the batch culture method but, because of cost and contamination problems, new methods of culturing algae were needed.
<P>
Therefore, during a project on ocean thermal energy conversion in the Virgin Islands, Sea Grant researchers investigated the possibility of continuous algal culture using nutrient-rich, deep ocean water. Their work showed that algae could be harvested continuously without resorting to batch culture techniques.
<P>
Then, with the help of computers and process control, Louisiana Sea Grant engineers developed a laboratory scale, computer-automated system, called a turbidostat, for continuously culturing algae. This system provides precise control of the process, increases algal production tenfold over the beach culture method, and reduces problems of contamination.
<P>
However, on a commercial scale, high energy needs for artificial lighting and temperature control made the continuous culture of algae indoors uneconomical. To reduce production costs through energy savings by using natural light, researchers at Georgia and Louisiana Sea Grant, in a pilot-scale project, are currently investigating use of the computer-automated turbidostat under greenhouse conditions.
<P>
In addition, the Louisiana Sea Grant researchers are combining the positive attributes of both the indoor continuous culture and the outdoor pond culture technologies into a computer-automated, hydraulically- integrated, serial turbidostat algal reactor (HISTAR).
<P>
To reduce algal production costs, HISTAR combines the precise control and high production capabilities of the computer-automated turbidostat with large outdoor tanks. The system physically consists of an indoor turbidostat unit connected to a series of outdoor continuous-flow, stirred tank reactors (CFSTRs). The turbidostat produces a high quality, dense algal suspension that is continuously injected into the first of the large tanks.
<P>
As algae flows from one CFSTR to the next, the standing crop is increased until the desired concentration is reached by the final tank. This method permits precise control of the algae at the front end, while taking advantage of large outdoor tanks and natural lighting to produce the mass quantities of algae required for most commercial operations. Of equal importance is that contaminants can be "washed out" of the system by manipulation of the hydraulic retention time.
<P>
HISTAR is in the early stages of prototype testing. Following demonstrations on the Louisiana State University campus, it will be tested in a commercial setting.
<P>
The goal of this Sea Grant research is to develop a centralized marine algal production ability with regional distribution facilities that would supply algae and secondary feed products to commercial aquaculture businesses. This arrangement would remove from the individual businesses the burden of growing algae, which would reduce their production costs and facilitate expansion of their growout activities. It would also keep algal culturing technology near to research experts, enabling technological advances to be easily implemented and transferred to the aquaculture industry. (For details, James McVey, 301/7l3-2451 or <A HREF="mailto:jmcvey@rdc.noaa.gov">jmcvey@rdc.noaa.gov</A)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

