<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(12)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
December 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 12
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Partnerships Formed to Meet Educational Challenges</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Partnerships Formed to Meet Educational Challenges</H2>
</CENTER>
Precollege education is changing. The need to achieve national and international excellence in the future workforce requires a concerted, multi-agency effort focused on education. Sea Grant is responding to that challenge by providing leadership through partnerships.
<P>
What happens in today's classrooms is not what happened 20 years ago. Text books are no longer the only curriculum guide, cookbook-type directions are no longer the prototype for science experiments, and teachers are no longer the ultimate source of knowledge. Partnerships, cooperative learning, electronic communication, interdisciplinary courses, contextual learning and scientific literacy are additions to the educator's vocabulary.
<P>
To respond to needs for educational reform, Sea Grant programs are providing leadership in training teachers and producing relevant curriculum materials, and they are also participating in partnerships to reach out to a much larger audience in the education community. Two national programs now in progress exemplify the successful integration of multi- agency resources to support common education goals.
<P>
"Operation Pathfinder: Oceanography and Coastal Processes for Elementary and Middle School Teachers" is a national course in marine science education offered through a partnership that includes Sea Grant programs with other NOAA components including the Office of Coastal Resource Management, the Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research, and the National Environmental, Satellite and Data Information Service. The Oceanographer of the Navy and the Office of Naval Research are funding partners and provide technical resources. So that Operation Pathfinder can reach the Pacific Island area, the Department of Interior is providing funding and logistical assistance.
<P>
Operation Pathfinder is offered in six regions: Northeast Coast; Mid-Atlantic Coast; South Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico; Great Lakes; West Coast; and Hawaii and Pacific Island. Within most regions, sites rotate among different Sea Grant programs.
<P>
Though the regional courses have a national format, each takes the flavor of its location. Regardless of the site, all Pathfinder teachers study six major themes: physical parameters (tides, currents, coastline processes): marine and aquatic habitats; marine and aquatic biology; marine and estuarine pollution; plate tectonics; and deep ocean technologies. Teachers are required to develop activities and units for inclusion in their home classrooms, conduct staff development sessions, and participate in a long-term evaluation effort. Participants in the three-credit graduate course are selected in regional competitions from applicants who teach predominately minority students and also meet additional course criteria.
<P>
Designed to be a five-year program, plans for Operation Pathfinder 1995 are underway for sites in Delaware, Hawaii, Mississippi, New Hampshire, Washington, and Wisconsin. Future plans are to reach teachers in all 50 states, provide a network to facilitate sharing, and produce classroom materials using the latest oceanographic and coastal research findings.
<P>
"The Global Change Education Workshop for Nonformal Educators" is a training program for non-classroom educators such as 4-H agents, extension agents, and Sea Grant and Space Grant educators. This three-year effort is a partnership among Sea Grant programs, Project Earthlink, and NOAA's Office of Global Programs. It began with regional planning sessions in 1993 that resulted in a national three day videoconference on global change in November 1994.
<P>
The simultaneous broadcast reached educators who gathered in Hawaii, Mississippi, Nebraska, New Hampshire, Virginia, Washington and Wisconsin. Each site downlinked four broadcasts during which national experts discussed their research on global change issues. While all the sites listened and watched, members from the seven audiences phoned in their questions. To take back to the classroom, each participant received the Global Change Education Resource Guide which provides background articles and activities on the major global change themes: natural climate variability, greenhouse effect, sea-level rise, ozone depiction ecosystem response, and decisionmaking under scientific uncertainty.
<P>
Currently, the global change education effort is moving from national coordination to individual state efforts. After a year of these local efforts, a second national videoconference is planned to train additional educators.
<P>
Partnerships help meet the challenge for education reform. Programs such as Operation Pathfinder and the Global Change Workshop service the education community drawing upon the rich diversity of resources from the partners. The results are economically effective, high quality opportunities that improve the quality of teaching in the United States (For details, Lundie Spence or Shirley Fiske, 301/713-2431 or <A HREF="mailto:sfiske@rdc.noaa.gov">sfiske@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

