<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(4)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
July 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 4
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Developing Environmentally Friendly Products</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Increasing the Margin of Safety with Seafood Canning</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2> Developing Environmentally Friendly Products
</H2>
</CENTER>
By studying how the Eastern oyster builds its shell South Carolina Sea Grant researchers have laid the groundwork for developing new materials that could be valuable alternatives to the non-biodegradable substances now used by industry and consumers. They found that as the oyster grows its shell some oyster molecules promote crystal growth while others regulate or terminate it.
<P>
Synthetic mimics of these molecules which are based on natural amino acids have various commercial applications. For example many industries use nonbiodegradable chemicals to reduce crystal growth in pipes, heat exchanges, and boilers. The new materials not only reduce this growth but also are largely biodegradable. Another use for these materials would be as a detergent additive. The most effective detergents include dispersants which keep soil and minerals off glassware and clothes but which for the most part are nonbiodegradable. The new material when added to such detergent formulations would make them decompose naturally.
<P>
In the course of their research the investigators also discovered a class of oyster molecules with super-absorption properties. They are now trying to develop a synthetic mimic of these molecules which could lead to the replacement of non-biodegradable chemicals now used in disposable diapers adult health care products and medical and hospital supplies.
<P>
The South Carolina scientists have filed several patents for their discoveries that have been transferred from laboratories to businesses. The Donlar Corporation a venture company based in Bedford Park Illinois is currently setting up a pilot facility to develop methods for producing these new environmentally friendly materials on a large scale. Major chemical corporations have also shown an interest in the concept. In addition another start-up company Biotechtronix located in Pendleton, South Carolina, has been formed based on the special instruments that were developed for analysis used in the research. (For details, A HREF="mailto:dave.attaway@noaa.gov">David Attaway</A><)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Increasing the Margin of Safety with Seafood Canning
</CENTER>
</H2>
For over two decades home canners of seafood have been advised to use the same processing time for both raw and smoked fish. When concerns about the adequacy of this canning process surfaced, <A HREF="http://seagrant.orst.edu">Oregon Sea Grant</A> researchers were prompted to re-examine seafood home canning information. Using computerized sensors they discovered that to destroy bacteria home canneries should increase smoked fish processing time for pint jars by approximately 9 percent an additional l0 minutes.
<P>
To get the word out the researchers published their findings in a respected food safety journal. As a result the U.S. Department of Agriculture will soon include this processing information in its nationally distributed manual <I>Complete Guide to Home Canning </I>(Ag. Information Bulletin no. 539). The Sea Grant researchers also distributed nationally and internationally their own publication containing the new guidelines. In addition they helped create a 15-minute video on home canning of smoked fish. This video was broadcast during a national satellite conference to approximately 200 sites in 31 states and viewed by hundreds of volunteer food safety instructors and outreach staff.
<P>
The Oregon Sea Grant research helps not only individual consumers but also marine business. Seaport Fisheries, a Native American company in Kirkland Washington, was marketing smoked fish in pint glass jars when the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, concerned about the potential for botulism, asked the small company to document its processing procedures. Oregon Sea Grant's existing guidelines backed up the fledgling company's processing methods and saved the company from a possible disaster. In an effort to expand Seaport Fisheries is currently negotiating with a large California distributor to market its smoked salmon. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A> at 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

