<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 5
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Research Improves Prediction of Wave Conditions</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  New Life Given to Aging Waterfronts</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research Improves Prediction of Wave Conditions</H2>
</CENTER>
In January 1988, an unexpected storm striking California generated the largest waves ever recorded in the Southern California Bight. Damage was particularly heavy in the Redondo Beach - King Harbor area where waves crashed through a breakwater and destroyed an estimated $16 million worth of coastal structures.
<P>
This storm forced California coastal planners to revise their estimates of extreme wave conditions. To make these estimates, planners turn to computer models. Unfortunately, the Southern California Bight is a challenging region for modelling waves, because the Channel Islands partially shelter the coast from storm waves arriving from the North and South Pacific. In addition, the islands, submarine canyons, and shallow banks of the Bight create very complex wave patterns.
<P>
Although wave data had been collected at a number of locations, usually for specific needs, the complexity of conditions within the Bight made it difficult to relate such data to other locations where there are no wave instruments.
<P>
Therefore, with support from the California Department of Boating and Waterways, California Sea Grant researchers adapted two computer models to allow scientists to use an existing wave-monitoring network to estimate swell conditions at all coastal locations in Southern California, even those without instruments. This adaptation is important because instrumenting and processing data from a single site can cost tens of thousands of dollars annually.
<P>
The models developed in this project are presently being used as part of the "Orange County Storm and Tidal Wave Study." This study will provide for better planning of future coastal structures through improved prediction of coastal erosion.
<P>
The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the California Department of Boating and Waterways are also using the research results to plan future expansion of the Coastal Data Information Program, which maintains a network of gauges for monitoring wave conditions primarily on the West Coast and Hawaii. Daily swell predictions from this model for Southern California are now available on the World Wide Web for use by harbormasters, mariners, surfers, and others who need "quasi-real time" information (WWW location: splashuesd.edu). (For details, <A HREF="mailto:dave.attaway@noaa.gov">David Attaway</A>, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Life Given to Aging Waterfronts</H2>
</CENTER>
The South Fork and the Willapa Rivers were once the economic heart of the small town of Raymond, Washing ton. The riverbanks were lined with mills, log booms and shipyards. Much of that industry, along with the jobs it generated, has vanished. During the 1980s alone, timber related employment dropped by 40 percent. As industry declined, so did the waterfront. Riverside buildings collapsed, and the riverbanks filled with trash.
<P>
Then, two years ago, a group of Raymond's citizens began to look at the rivers in a new way, as the basis for a different kind of economic development. Thanks in part to a plan developed with the assistance of <A HREF="http://www.wsg.washington.edu/">Washington</A> and <A HREF="http://seagrant.orst.edu">Oregon</A> Sea Grant specialists and the National Coastal Resources Research and Development Institute, Raymond is reclaiming its waterfront. 
<P>
The city has obtained $1.3 million in state and federal funding to demolish abandoned buildings, construct a waterfront park, and transform an abandoned rail corridor into a foot and bike path. That path may eventually link Raymond with South Bend, located five miles down- stream, where the Willapa River empties into Willapa Bay. Raymond's new downtown park and public dock will be the permanent home of the tall ship <I>Krestine</I>, now temporarily moored at the port of Willapa Harbor.
<P>
During the same two-year period, outreach specialists at Sea Grant programs in Washington and Oregon also helped the city of Warrentown, Oregon, develop its waterfront plan. Situated at the mouth of the Columbia River, Warrentown has received a grant to develop a waterfront park on the Skipanon River near the city's center. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:fritz.schuler@noaa.gov">Francis Schuler</A>, 301/713-2445).
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

