<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 4(1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1996<BR>
Volume 4, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Test Developed to Detect Scrubbed Lobsters
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Partnership Results in Successful Harvest of Scallops
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Test Developed to Detect Scrubbed Lobsters
</H2>
</CENTER>
A sustainable lobster fishery is vital to the socioeconomic well-being of many rural coastal communities in Maine. Therefore, laws have been passed making it illegal to harvest egg-bearing lobsters. In the past, it has been difficult for officials to enforce this law because a widely used technique for removing eggs of berried females leaves no obvious external signs. This technique--dipping berried females in chlorine bleach--is used by short-sighted individuals who then sell the non-berried females. Now, thanks to recent work by <A HREF="http://unhinfo.unh.edu:70/unh/acad/special/seagrant/index.html">Maine Sea Grant researchers</A>, enforcement officials have a simple method of detecting these scrubbed lobsters.
<P>
Using a conventional light microscope, the researchers examined the swimmerets both on untreated lobster tails and on tails treated with a chlorine bleach solution. They found that on untreated swimmerets, pairs of fine, uniformly arranged hairs extended from a central shaft (seta) creating a characteristic feather-like pattern. However, the setal hairs of swimmerets of lobsters dipped in bleach were not in the typical feather pattern. Instead, the hairs were highly disorganized and bent and some were even missing. It was also observed that differences in swimmeret hairs were not specific to chlorine bleach, but were indicators that the lobster had been exposed to a chemical irritant.
<P>
To verify these findings, the researchers, working with NOAA¹s National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) in Portland, conducted the same tests using a scanning electron microscope and got the same results. NMFS officials have worked with the researchers from the beginning of this project and are responsible for enforcing the law against harvesting egg-bearing lobsters. 
<P>
These findings by the Maine Sea Grant researchers are included in a manual to be published by the Lobster Institute, a research and educational organization that represents lobster interests from Newfoundland to New York. The manual, which describes how to detect lobsters that have been dipped in bleach or other irritating solutions, also includes chemical-color reaction tests developed, in part, by Woods Hole Sea Grant researchers. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:shirley.fiske@noaa.gov">Shirley Fiske</A>, 301/713-2431) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Partnership Results in Successful Harvest of Scallops
</H2>
</CENTER>
For the past 20 years, the Long Island Sound has been depleted of bivalves because of pollution and excessive commercial harvesting. Last fall, aquaculture students were able to harvest scallops from the Sound that were grown using a proven aquaculture method.  This harvest was made possible by a partnership that was formed to start a demonstration bay scallop farm in the Sound. 
<P>
Partners in this project were the Bridgeport Regional Vocational Aquaculture School and an advisor from the Peoples Republic of China, a marine biologist visiting as part of the NOAA Bilateral Agreement with China. In addition, the project had support from <A HREF="http://www.ucc.uconn.edu/~wwwsgo/">Connecticut Sea Grant</A> and NOAA¹s National Marine Fisheries Service Milford Laboratory.
<P>
To launch this project, the Aquaculture School students first conditioned the parent scallops to spawn in tanks at the school. They next placed the seeds or embryonic scallops in Chinese-lantern-style mesh bags.  These bags were then tied to moorings in the Sound and suspended in the water by buoys to protect the scallops from crabs and other seafloor predators.  After tending to the bags in all types of weather, the students successfully harvested approximately 12,000 bay scallops.
<P>
To celebrate, the students invited guests to come taste their first harvest. Educators and marine experts from as far away as Shanghai attended the reception.
<P>
The Aquaculture School is a regional magnet facility designed to give students not headed for college job skills in the marine industry. In the future, the school¹s scallop farm will continue to operate and be an integral part of the curriculum.  In addition, the techniques and procedures learned during the scallop project will be adapted to other aquaculture crops that students at the school are planning to culture. (For details, Tim Tisch, 301/713-2431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

