<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 3(2)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
March 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Fishermen Recycle 22 Tons of Gear</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Breakthrough Made in Underwater Wet Welding</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Fishermen Recycle 22 Tons of Gear
</H2>
</CENTER>
North Carolina's commercial fishermen recycled nearly 22 tons of crab pots and nets in February, attacking a solid waste disposal problem and setting a good environmental example to boot. The material was collected in nine coastal counties where, for two weeks, the crabbers, shrimpers and other watermen toted their worn-out net webbing and old crab pots to 17 locations.
<P>
Local waste haulers pitched in to collect the refuse, which was trucked to the East Carolina Vocational Center in Greenville for baling.
<P>
<A HREF="../NCSG/index.html>North Carolina Sea Grant</A> and the North Carolina Office of Waste Reduction coordinated the effort. It was funded through NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service, which has also supported commercial gear recycling programs in other coastal areas. In addition, the program had support from local fishermen and the North Carolina Crabbers League of Aware Watermen.
<P>
Weighing in at 20 tons, crab pots- about 4,600 of them- accounted for the bulk of the material. All the metal pots went into a pile for meltdown and reuse by local scrap dealers.
<P>
As expected, nets made up only a fraction of the collection by weight. In the Southeast trawl fisheries, nets are usually patched and repaired rather than discarded. Only 3,500 pounds of trawl and gill net material were collected. It was baled and shipped overseas where the recycled fibers may appear in jackets, sneaker bottoms and bicycle seats.
<P>
This pilot program is just a beginning in the effort to address the problem of marine debris and solid waste from the fishing industry. It is estimated that a quarter of a million crab pots are disposed of by North Carolina crabbers annually. Many end up in landfills but some are tossed along riverbanks and into tidal creeks. (For details, Lundie Spence, 301/713-2432)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Breakthrough Made in Underwater Wet Welding
</H2>
</CENTER>
The ability to create reliable, permanent welds underwater could save industry and the military time and money in repairing ships, off-shore rigs and underwater infrastructure. Currently, large hyperbaric chambers are used to keep water from the work area during underwater welding. Operating these chambers is very expensive.
<P>
In a breakthrough in underwater wet welding technology for use in commercial applications, <A HREF="http://www-ohio.osc.edu/seagrant.html">Ohio Sea Grant</A> researchers have developed a welding electrode nicknamed "Black Beauty" for the appearance of its waterproof coating. Testing, during a project sponsored by NOAA's National Coastal Resources Research & Development Institute, documented that Black Beauty can withstand the two major hazards of underwater welding: porosity and hydrogen cracking.
<P>
To help commercialize this technological breakthrough, Ohio Sea Grant has established the Underwater Welding Center. Based at The Ohio State University, the center disseminates new underwater welding information to industrial users and provides databases, training, and research and development services.
<P>
To handle the potential national and international demand, a new company, Applied Welding Technologies, Inc., has been formed to manufacture and market the new electrode. It is predicted that a potential annual sales volume of 150,000 pieces, about 40 percent of the total domestic market, is a reasonable estimate for the market in this country alone. The related welding equipment sales could be $1.5 million annually.
<P>
However, the potential for the international market is considered to be even greater. Because of the superb performance of the new electrode during pressure vessel testing in Harbin, China, the Harbin Research Institute of Welding has expressed interest in promoting the electrode in the huge Chinese market.
<P>
Interest in the new electrode has also been shown by the U.S. Navy. It is funding the Ohio Sea Grant researchers to evaluate the electrode's applicability for wet welding repairs underwater in lieu of costly and time-consuming dry-docking. (For details, Dick Kolf, 301/7 13-2445)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

