<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 3(3)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
May 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 3
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Shipwreck Parks Boost Small Town Economies</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Research Aids Abalone Industry</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Shipwreck Parks Boost Small Town Economies</H2>
</CENTER>
The cold, fresh water of the Great Lakes preserves the remnants of several thousand shipwrecks that hold clues to the maritime history of the region. Thanks to 15 years of work by Michigan Sea Grant, these shipwrecks attract thousands of recreational divers each year, as well as many archaeologists.
<P>
In the early 1970s, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.great-lakes.net:2200/11/partners/SeaGrant/Mich">Michigan Sea Grant</A> researchers showed the benefits of establishing preserves to protect these Great Lakes shipwrecks and to stimulate scuba diving and associated tourist spending in coastal communities. These findings culminated in state legislation authorizing the designation of state bottomland preserves.
<P>
As a result, Michigan Sea Grant outreach specialists helped establish nine bottomland preserves and arc working on a proposed tenth one. They then helped communities secure financial resources for important projects in the reserves such as buoying shipwrecks so they can be easily found and protected from dive boats inadvertently dropping anchor on them.
<P>
Work by Sea Grant also aided communication among he widely scattered preserve communities along Michigan's coastline and along Lakes Superior, Huron, and Erie and resulted in the formation of the Michigan Underwater Preserves Council. The Council markets diving opportunities in the preserves and encourages appropriate state policy for managing the resources.
<P>
In addition, Sea Grant-sponsored diving safety research has provided vital guidance to communities near preserves in developing management plans for dive accidents. Michigan Sea Grant diving specialists also train dive rescue personnel and emergency medical technicians.
<P>
The development of these underwater preserves has significantly boosted the economy of a wide range of businesses in Michigan's coastal communities. A recent Michigan Sea Grant study suggests that diving activity provided an economic stimulus of at least $1.5 million 'over a two-year period for the small towns near the preserves. Forty percent of these expenditures are for dive services; the other 60 percent are for other services, such as lodging and food. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:dave.attaway@noaa.gov">David Attaway</A>, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research Aids Abalone Industry</H2>
</CENTER>
The first two private companies in the world to achieve profitable abalone production are located in California, and the industry there is growing rapidly. Last year, California sales of products from abalone aquaculture hit $3 million. A large percentage of the meat was exported to Asia.
<P>
Much of this success can be attributed to California Sea Grant researchers who, in cooperation with industry, identified the major bottlenecks in abalone production:  control of spawning, control of larval metamorphosis, and acceleration of growth. The researchers first focused on learning the natural environmental triggers that control  these processes.
<P>
For example, they found that a hormone called prostaglandin is a natural trigger that induces spawning. A simple and inexpensive application of this finding was then developed, in which hydrogen peroxide is used to stimulate the animal to produce prostaglandin. This convenient and reliable method is now widely used by the industry.
<P>
The researchers then tackled problems associated with the metamorphosis of abalone larvae into their juvenile form, It was found that this process can be conveniently induced in hatcheries by using an inexpensive chemical, GABA. Currently, this method is also being used by an increasing number of California producers.
<P>
The California Sea Grant research group is now taking aim at the problem of abalone growth, which is often slow. They have discovered that growth can be significantly accelerated by adding to the water very low concentrations of hormones normally produced by the animal. Present research efforts are aimed at developing a simple method for stimulating the abalone itself to produce these growth-accelerating hormones.
<P>
The California aquaculture industry is very active in assisting this effort Producers have provided technical assistance, abalone, and stocks of feed algae. Other active collaborators are in Japan, the Netherlands, and Taiwan. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:leon.cammen@noaa.gov">Leon Cammen</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

