<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 1(1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Research On Harmful Algal Blooms</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2> Research On Harmful Algal Blooms</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
Although "red tides" and other unusual plankton blooms have occurred for centuries world-wide, algal blooms harmful to human health appear to be occurring more frequently in the coastal zone and estuaries of the United States. Spreading both regionally and globally, these blooms increase the risk of health problems for seafood consumers and coastal residents. 
<P>
When toxic blooms do appear, the need to protect human health by closing fisheries results in severe economic losses to the shellfish, aquaculture, and finfish industries. Compounding these losses are those incurred when other bloom-forming species, harmless to humans, cause fish and invertebrates to die. Food webs leading to higher levels may be altered, thus affecting the normal functioning of an entire ecosystem and reducing the yield of harvestable marine resources. 
<P>
The Sea Grant network is tackling this problem through a comprehensive, interdisciplinary research program. Investigators are looking at topics ranging from the causes of the blooms and new methods for detecting them before they affect seafood to an assessment of the total economic impact of the problem. 
<P>
Sea Grant investigators in Alaska, Hawaii, Maine, Massachusetts, New York, Rhode Island, and Texas are trying to understand why harmful algal blooms are becoming much more common. Among the factors being considered are: changes in oceanographic conditions; alterations in nutrient inputs due to coastal development; and increases in the amount of ultraviolet radiation that the algae receive because of atmospheric ozone reduction. In addition, researchers are looking at why some algae are becoming increasingly toxic and at the effects of marine viruses as potential agents to control algal abundance. 
<P>
In California, North Carolina and Rhode Island, Sea Grant researchers are developing more rapid and sensitive methods to detect the presence of harmful algal species before they endanger seafood consumers. Methods being investigated range from those that hone in on the genetic make-up or optical properties of single cells to airplane sensors that measure light absorbance of entire plankton communities. 
<P>
Of greatest concern to the public, of course, is the potential presence of toxins in seafood. Sea Grant researchers from California, New York, and Texas are working with marine animals to see how they take up algal toxins through feeding and other means. The researchers are trying to predict how long it takes the animals to get rid of ingested toxins and become safe for human consumption. They have learned that marine animals respond very differently once the toxic algal blooms disappear; some become safe for consumption in a few days, while others may remain toxic for months. 
<P>
Although scattered estimates exist of severe economic losses from closure of fisheries due to algal toxins, the figures have never been compiled systematically for the entire U.S. coastline. Sea Grant investigators Massachusetts and Rhode Island have begun to gather estimates of the true cost of this problem to the national economy. 
<P>
Eliminating harmful algal blooms from the environment is not expected to happen soon. In fact, as the understanding of marine ecosystems increases, it may be found that these blooms play important roles in the functioning of natural ecosystems. 
<P>
In responding to this important coastal resource problem, Sea Grant has developed an innovative and comprehensive research program drawing upon not only the biological and physical sciences but also social sciences and economics. The ultimate goal is to better understand harmful algal blooms so as to reduce their impact on seafood consumers, coastal economies, and U.S. fisheries. (For details, Leon Cammen, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:lcammen@rdc.noaa.gov">lcammen@rdc.noaa.gov</A>). 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

