<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(9)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 9
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">New Technology to Strengthen<BR>
U.S. Recreational Boat Industry</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Technology to Strengthen<BR>
U.S. Recreational Boat Industry</H2>
</CENTER>
In the United Stales, recreational boating is a multi- billion dollar industry. The State of Michigan, for example, with the nation's longest continental coastline Of 3,200 miles, has recreational boat registrations approaching one million. Very similar numbers are registered by California, Florida, and Texas and many other states are not far behind.
<P>
As in almost all other areas of engineering technology, the U.S. has been the leader in the design and production of the world's recreational boats, both in numbers and in quality. Consistent with recent trends, however, its leadership is being lost to international challenges. This is particularly true in the outboard engine and propulsion system market, but the threat in the market for boat hulls and hull components is imminent.
<P>
Sea Grant has invested in applying U.S. superiority in basic engineering research to secure and maintain the leadership that the nation has always enjoyed in this very important coastal industry.
<P>
The challenge of modem recreational boat design is fourfold: functionality, occupant safely, safely for people and animals in the water, and minimal environmental impact. In the past, the dominant focus of the U.S. recreational boat industry has been on functionality. Other boat design challenges have only recently been brought to the forefront and considered equally important. The design issues have clearly become complex enough to warrant a more systematic and rigorous engineering approach to recreational boats for the next generation.
<P>
Sea Grant's research effort in recreational boat engineering and design is centered at the University of Michigan. Over the past five years, Michigan Sea Grant researchers have addressed the dynamics of recreational planing boats. They have worked to extend basic hydrodynamics theories of vessel planing to more accurately predict the fluid flow, and resultant fluid pressures and forces, on general boat hull forms when planing in calm water or through waves. These fluid forces dictate boat performance, such as the power required to achieve a desired speed and the boat's motion and pounding characteristics in waves at a given speed.
<P>
In support of the Sea Grant work, Hydrodyne Ski Boat Company of Fort Wayne, Indiana, has provided a boat constructed and outfitted especially for checking and verifying the new computational methods developed by the Michigan research team. Measurements of hull surface pressure distributions and propeller shaft thrust and torque as well as observation of propeller blade cavitation (rapid formation and collapse of low-pressure water vapor bubbles around a spinning propeller) are being conducted this summer and fall.
<P>
In August, University of Michigan marine engineering students competed in the first annual Solar-Electric Boat Races held in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. The races were sponsored by Johnson Controls, Inc., and hosted by Marquette University. The Michigan entry, Vee-n-Verse, a unique carbon-fiber inverted-V hull form with a surface piercing propeller, was designed, engineered, and built using the new Sea Grant technology. The construction and hardware costs were supported by an array of industrial sponsors, including NUCON Marine Systems, Ford Motor Company, and Trinity Marine Group. On the boat's first time out against well-established Japanese competition, it took third place in the sprint races and was awarded the prize for technological achievement.
<P>
With new predictive engineering tools having reached a useful state of development and with the guidance and support of several key companies in the recreational boat industry, Sea Grant now plans to target its research effort in recreational boats toward specific applications of the new technology. The first application, to be conducted at the University of Michigan, is a multi-year effort to establish concepts for safer, more efficient, and ecologically-sound recreational boat propulsion, and to assist the U.S. industry with implementation from concept to practical design. Based on the long-standing leadership of the University of Michigan in the field of naval architecture, Michigan Sea Grant is quickly becoming a center of excellence for recreational boat design. (For details, Richard Kolf, 301/713-2445 or <A HREF="mailto:dkolf@rdc.noaa.gov">dkolf@rdc.noaa.gov</A)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

