<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 1(2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  New Oil Recycling Market Developed</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Research on History of Fish Populations Aids Resource Managers
</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]"> Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Oil Recycling Market Developed</H2>
</CENTER>
A <A HREF="http://www.wsg.washington.edu/">Washington Sea Grant</A> demonstration project has opened a new market for the oil recycling industry. The project, which benefits both business and the environment, addresses the problem of used oil filters discarded at marinas. Without adequate disposal sites, commercial and recreational boat operators put these filters in dumpsters or leave them on the dock or in other areas where they might ultimately pollute the water. Therefore, Sea Grant brought together a marina director and the recycling industry - which already was collecting and recycling oil and oil filters from land activities - to participate in a pilot project.
<P>
The project established a used marine oil filter collection, crushing, and recycling demonstration in Everett at one of the state's largest marinas. Among the benefits realized from the project was that up to a quart of oil that normally would remain in an individual filter was reclaimed and recycled rather than allowed to enter the environment. Moreover, the entire oil filter was recycled and removed from the waste stream since both the metal and rubber were recovered after treatment at a recycling center.
<P>
This pilot project was so successful that the Port of Everett plans to continue it without Sea Grant assistance. A similar Washington Sea Grant-sponsored project was started at the Port of Seattle Fishermen's Terminal, the largest commercial fishing moorage facility in the state. Another Washington marina at Oak Harbor is working with industry to install an oil filter crusher, and the Alaska Ferry System is considering a similar effort in Bellingham. (For details: <A HREF="mailto:fritz.schuler@noaa.gov">Francis Schuler</A>, 301-713-2445 x160)

<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2> Research on History of Fish Populations<BR>
Aids Resource Managers
</CENTER>
</H2>
Although the Pacific sardine and the northern anchovy have supported major fisheries off California during the 20th century, volatility in these stocks has made them notoriously difficult to manage. Their boom-and-bust history has been attributed, in varying degrees, to overintensive fishing, biological interactions among species, and environmental influences associated with large-scale climatic change.
<P>
A recently published study by California Sea Grant researchers provides information critical to unraveling the sources of variability in these fish stocks. By analyzing fish scale deposits found in sediments in the Santa Barbara Basin off southern California, the researchers discovered that during the past 1,700 years, sardine and anchovy populations have varied over periods lasting about 60 years. Further sediment analyses showed nine major sardine population recoveries and subsequent collapses during the 1,700-year period, with the average recovery time being 30 years.
<P>
Of particular interest is the conclusion that the timing of the collapse of the sardine population in the early 1950s was consistent with the natural population cycle, though the magnitude of the collapse may have been related to fishing pressures. The researchers also reported that the present recovery of sardines is not unlike those of the past in its rate or size. Research on the relationships between population cycles, fishing pressure, and change in ocean climate is continuing. Fisheries managers from the United States and Mexico are presently using the information to develop management strategies for the sardine fishery that will not interfere with the present recovery. (For details: <A HREF="mailto:leon.cammen@noaa.gov">Leon Cammen</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

