<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 3(1)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Providing Information to Better Manage Fisheries</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Providing Information to Better Manage Fisheries</H2>
</CENTER>
Today, most of the effort expended on understanding what controls fishery populations focuses on the effects of fishing. Most population models used in fisheries management account for natural mortality but fishing mortality is the only variable that can be accurately estimated and controlled. Thus, while management focuses almost exclusively on controlling fishing effort, the success of any management scheme is dependent on understanding factors other than fishing that influence or regulate population abundance. For example, in the past, volatility in the Pacific sardine and the northern anchovy fisheries made them difficult to manage. Recently, a California Sea Grant study provided critical information showing that, over the past 1,700 years, sardine and anchovy populations expanded and collapsed in approximately 60-year cycles. Now, U.S. and Mexico fisheries managers can develop appropriate management strategies for these fisheries.
<P>
Understanding the underlying biological and physical factors that regulate fish populations and account for natural variability is an ongoing research priority of the National Sea Grant College Program. New York Sea Grant studies on bluefish in the Middle Atlantic Bight and estuarine areas of New York show that summer-spawned fish remain in continental shelf waters until early juvenile stages. Then they are transported to the estuaries. Juveniles of spring-spawned fish are significantly larger than those of the summer spawn when they enter the estuaries. Under "typical" conditions, the larger spring-spawned fish have higher survival rates. During those years when northern transport in continental shelf waters is weak, the summer-spawned fish make up a larger portion of the year-class. Results to date suggest that both spawning populations contribute significantly to each year-class.
<P>
Great Lakes Sea Grant researchers in New York and Wisconsin are focusing on the predator/prey interactions between stocked salmonids and their food species. Studies are underway to estimate whole lake biomass of planktivorous fishes (prey species) in Lakes Ontario and Michigan. Information from these studies will be used in the development and testing of trophodynamic models designed to predict the consequences of species interactions.
<P>
Virginia Sea Grant has supported research on blue crab for more than 12 years, much of which deals with identifying the factors controlling population abundance. Early studies showed that adults spawn at estuary mouths. Larval stages are spent in surface waters over the continental shelf, and the last larval stage (megalopa) enters estuaries where it settles and metamorphoses into a juvenile. Sea Grant programs in Delaware, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi-Alabama, New York and South Carolina along with Virginia are focusing research on identifying the mechanisms that help reentry into estuaries and the factors influencing survival of juvenile crabs.
<P>
Washington Sea Grant research on Dungeness crab suggests the life cycle of this crustacean is similar to the blue crab's. Adults spawn in nearshore waters, larval stages inhabit offshore surface waters, and megalopa are transported to nearshore waters and Settle in shallow benthic environments along the coast or in estuaries. The relative importance of these nursery areas to the fishable population is undetermined. However, studies on other crustaceans such as spiny lobster by Florida Sea Grant and on American lobster by Sea Grant programs in Maine-New Hampshire and Rhode Island have shown that the availability of juvenile habitat plays a significant role in regulating population abundance of these species.
<P>
Because of Sea Grant's leadership, understanding factors that influence or decide population abundance has blossomed into one of the most dynamic areas of fisheries investigations. The NOAA Coastal Ocean Program's effort in fisheries ecosystems and the NOAA/National Science Foundation Global Ecosystem Dynamics Program (GLOBEC) can trace their roots to Sea Grant's pioneering work in this area. In fact, many researchers involved in these major ecosystem investigations began as Sea Grant researchers or students.
<P>
Sea Grant will continue to support fundamental research in this new and exciting area of fisheries research. In addition, Sea Grant will take the next step and begin to develop ecosystem-based management models and strategies. Such models will incorporate mechanisms of population control, natural- and human-induced environmental fluctuations, and multi- species interactions. Also, to provide effective mechanisms for building and rebuilding sustainable fisheries, Sea Grant will provide fisheries managers, industries, and coastal communities with information needed to understand the social, economic, and legal impacts resulting from new management strategies. (For details, Gene Fritz, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

