<DOCNO>WT19-B05-25</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA095-001025-B012-287</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://mdsg.umd.edu:80/NSGO/SeaGrantFuture/V2N01.html 129.2.110.45 19970215002813 text/html 8139
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 00:28:26 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Research on Nearshore Waves</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research on Nearshore Waves</H2>
</CENTER>
During severe storms and hurricanes, waves are responsible for millions of dollars worth of property damage every year and sometimes take their toll in human lives. By moving sediment along the shore or in onshore/offshore directions, waves can also cause damage by creating new erosion patterns which alter the shoreline's natural features, and affect coastal and offshore structure. Because of this, nearshore and shallow water waves--those occurring in depths of about 10 meters or less--are extremely important considerations when coastal structures are designed. Predicting the impacts of waves becomes even more important as population, coastal development, and water levels increase along U.S. shores. Current Sea Grant research into nearshore waves is framed by a number of complicated factors including complex underwater topography, offshore islands, wave/ sediment interaction, and shallow and confined bodies of water. 
<P>
Two areas where wave conditions are extremely difficult to forecast are the Gulf of Maine and the Southern California Bight. In these areas, complex underwater topography and irregular shorelines combine with islands and offshore banks to create complicated interactions of shoaling, refraction, and diffraction. These interactions cause nearshore wave conditions to vary greatly even in short distances along the coast. Maine-New Hampshire and California Sea Grant researchers are addressing problems of predicting wave conditions in these difficult nearshore locations. Their findings will aid coastal planners in efforts to limit wave-induced damage to shoreline structures from severe storms and erosion of beaches. 
<P>
Discovering the interactions of shallow water waves with sediments on the bottom is another complex problem for researchers to solve. Waves generate currents that move the sediment, which in turn modifies the waves passing over it. This feedback mechanism causes a "Catch 22" situation for researchers struggling to understand and quantify the phenomenon. MIT Sea Grant has supported a two-pronged approach to solve this dilemma by using both carefully designed laboratory studies and advanced theoretical work. This approach has yielded the most advanced theories on the energy losses of waves propagating over sand beds and on the resulting sand movement and bed modification. 
<P>
At tidal inlets, wave conditions are important because of their influence on movement of sediments along the shore. The U.S. ocean coastline is dominated by sandy barrier islands separated by tidal inlets. Waves, currents, and sediment interact in unusually complex manners at inlets and affect the coastline for great distances. To design effective strategies to protect harbors and beaches from erosion, Delaware Sea Grant researchers are currently conducting theoretical research on this problem and soon will be initiating related laboratory work. Their efforts will complement theoretical and laboratory studies of tidal inlets being conducted at the South Carolina and Florida Sea Grant programs. 
<P>
Wave generation and propagation in shallow and confined bodies of water are particularly hard to predict. As part of a general effort to predict the physical status of the Great Lakes under the Great Lakes Forecasting System, Ohio Sea Grant is supporting wave prediction research. Maryland Sea Grant is initiating advanced research on wave prediction for Chesapeake Bay. In addition, Florida Sea Grant is developing an inexpensive PC-based wave forecasting system for the state's coastal waters. These efforts have general aspects which will be useful to other coastal areas of the country. 
<P>
Along parts of the Pacific Northwest coast, wave conditions can be so severe that typical seabed pressure wave gauges are damaged or destroyed during the very storm events that they should be documenting. Oregon Sea Grant researchers are avoiding this problem by measuring waves off the Newport coast with a microseismometer installed at The Hatfield Marine Center a mile-and-a-half from the coast. This unique method of measuring waves has proved to be quite effective in documenting their intensity during severe winter storms. 
<P>
Discovering the physical processes governing waves will ultimately enhance the ability to protect both life and property from their impacts. Results from Sea Grant's wave research will be used by coastal planners, the Federal Emergency Management Agency, and the Army Corps of Engineers to lessen the damage caused by waves through erosion or during storms. (For details, John Ahrens, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:jahrens@rdc.noaa.gov">jahrens@rdc.noaa.gov</A>) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

