<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sea Grant Challenges 4(1)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
March 1996<BR>
Volume 4, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Effective Coastal Management Developed Through Research
</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Effective Coastal Management Developed Through Research
</H2>
</CENTER>

Effective coastal management depends on laws, policies, and institutions that work. Sea Grant specialists evaluate these management tools, examine how to make better decisions, and propose new ways to tackle coastal problems.
<P>
Several states, including North Carolina, have moved to strengthen legal management of their ocean resources. To support this legal effort, scholars from North Carolina Sea Grant evaluated laws that govern the area from mean high tide to the limit of the 200 mile Exclusive Economic Zone. Their review included state and federal laws and jurisdictional issues that affect activities such as seafloor mining, oil and gas development, fisheries management, and pollution discharge. Based on this review, the report submitted to the state¹s Ocean Resources Task Force made specific recommendations for action where the current management regime is unclear or deficient. 
<P>
In Hawaii, the lack of coordination among government agencies hindered ocean resources management. To explore possible solutions, policy analysts from Hawaii Sea Grant studied Australia¹s Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority. They determined that the Authority offered a useful model. For a Hawaii version to work, however, an Authority would have to be established by law and given responsibility for managing the living and non-living resources as a single ecological unit within the exclusive economic zone of the Hawaiian archipelago.
<P>
Estuaries, like archipelagoes, present daunting management challenges. Specialists in public policy, planning, and administration from Rhode Island Sea Grant analyzed the evolution of the 16-year effort to understand and manage the Chesapeake Bay resources. Their intent was to determine the extent to which learning, adaptation, and flexibility (adaptive management) were features of the governance system.  The specialists found that, as new information became available, both Bay research programs and institutional arrangements changed significantly. This flexible, adaptive approach made it possible for the management program to evolve from a rather simple one to today¹s complex program. This capacity to learn and adapt has resulted in a sophisticated set of baywide indicators of ecosystem health and of institutions that coordinate federal, state, and local management. The Chesapeake experience suggests that managers can address estuarine restoration and protection most effectively through an adaptive process, one that is exploratory, evolutionary, and based on close ties between science and management.
<P>
Ocean governance at the national level is no less complex. Although the United States has an extensive body of ocean law and policy in place, it has yet to develop a national ocean governance strategy to achieve sustainable development of the nation¹s marine resources. Because these laws focus on individual resources, they are typically unable to address interrelationships and conflicts. Political scientists from Delaware Sea Grant are addressing the challenge of ocean governance in the United States. Based on an analysis of these laws and policies, they have defined the necessary features of a National Ocean Governance Strategy. These features would include a long-term vision, a stewardship ethic, and specific goals for sustainable development. In addition, the scientists have spelled out the analytical studies required to implement such a strategy and suggested several possible approaches to getting the process started.
<P>
Public participation can play an important role in coastal management decisions. Researchers from the New York Sea Grant Institute assessed the importance of local context in a community-based water resources program aimed at the cleanup of the 42 most polluted locations on the Great Lakes Basin. Survey data enabled the researchers to pinpoint conditions that significantly affect the design and conduct of public involvement programs. Among these conditions are level of community awareness, state of the local economy, and strength of local leadership.
<P>
Rigorous evaluation is critical for ensuring the effectiveness of coastal management. An interdisciplinary team from Oregon, Rhode Island, and Washington Sea Grant programs has begun the first comprehensive assessment of the national Coastal Zone Management Program in its 24-year history. The project, conducted with support from NOAA¹s Office of Ocean and Coastal Resource Management, will evaluate the effectiveness of the 29 federally-approved state and territory  CZM programs. The project focuses on the extent to which these programs have addressed the core objectives of the 1972 Coastal Zone Management Act, specifically, protection of natural resources, provision of public access to the coast, assistance in the development of coastal dependent uses, and simplification of procedures for coastal management decision-making. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:sfiske@rdc.noaa.gov">Shirley Fiske</A>, 301/713-2431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

