<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
February 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Changing Demographics and Marine Science Education</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>Changing Demographics and Marine Science Education<H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>
In the future, decisions affecting U.S. coastal resources will be in different demographic hands. According to census projections, minority groups will make up nearly 50 percent of the population by 2050. However, these groups are traditionally underrepresented in the marine sciences and in resource management.
<P>
To change this trend, Sea Grant programs nationwide are providing minorities help at all levels of the educational pipeline. They are developing marine science projects that directly involve middle and secondary students, train teachers, and create educational materials. To bring under- graduate and graduate students into the enterprise of science, Sea Grant is providing support for scholarships, research assistantships, and fellowships.
<P>
Minnesota Sea Grant has developed a summer institute focused on training teachers how to make marine science more relevant to Native American middle and high school students. Teachers will be trained to teach the environmental history of the Lake Superior region in a cultural context. The goal of this project is to increase the number of Native American students pursuing elective science and environmental courses. For undergraduates, Minnesota Sea Grant has developed the American Indians in Marine Science (AIMS) project. It provides a 3-year, university research- based program with financial, academic, and mentoring support for students. Three reservations in Minnesota have comprehensive natural resource management agencies. Two of these agencies are now headed by AIMS graduates.
<P>
In other work with Native Americans, Mississippi-Alabama Sea Grant directly involves students of the Poarch Creek Band Reservation in camps which, in response to tribal requests, focus on environmental education. So far, 120 elementary to high school students have participated in these camps.
<P>
To reach inner-city students, Mississippi-Alabama Sea Grant is cooperating with Mobile County Public Schools as part of the system's inner-city education enhancement plan. Sea Grant is providing in-service teacher training to incorporate marine sciences into the system's fourth-grade curriculum. The consortium is also providing African- American middle school students an opportunity to attend a sea camp in Mississippi as part of an enrichment program.
<P>
In Texas, the Rio Grande Valley (RGV) has a large and rapidly increasing population of Hispanic students and teachers. To enhance these teachers' skills to teach marine sciences, Texas Sea Grant is offering three different workshops. One will cover barrier island ecology, another features interdisciplinary classroom activities using marine resources, and a third utilizes an atmospheric curriculum. About 90 teachers will participate in the workshops overall.
<P>
Working with the state's education department, Hawaii Sea Grant is contributing to an interactive TV curriculum for use throughout all island schools. Intended for at-risk youth in fourth and fifth grades, the curriculum will be based on Hawaiian culture, and a television series will be developed as a component of the state's distance learning program. University scientists will serve as living textbooks and role models for participants.
<P>
Puerto Rico Sea Grant, working with the Commonwealth's education department, has significantly increased the level of marine science activities throughout the island's high schools. This has been accomplished through a dovetailed effort of extensive teacher training, and the development and introduction of marine curricular activities such as guided educational field trips for students and teachers.
<P>
At the national level, NOAA Sea Grant has developed an initiative to offer regional workshops through six Sea Grant programs-Hawaii, Mississippi-Alabama, New Jersey, New York, Southern California, and Wisconsin. An estimated 120 elementary and middle school minority teachers or teachers who instruct predominately minority students will attend the summer 1994 regional workshops where they will be taught new techniques to teach marine sciences. The workshops will be supported by the Oceanographer of the Navy, the Office of Naval Research, and the Naval Oceanography Command; the Department of Interior, and NOAA's National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service and its Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research.
<P>
Sea Grant alone cannot change the demographics of marine science education. In all cases, Sea Grant educators will continue to work with state education departments and national and state teacher associations, and will continue to leverage Sea Grant dollars with funds from other sources. (For details, Shirley Fiske, 301/713-2431 or <A HREF="mailto:sfiske@rdc.noaa.gov">sfiske@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

