<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(8)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
August 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 8
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Sea Grant and Partners Will Provide<BR>
Training to Assure Safe Seafood Products
</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Sea Grant and Partners Will Provide<BR>
Training to Assure Safe Seafood Products</H2>
</CENTER>
Proposed U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) regulations will require workers to be trained in proper handling of seafood. In addition, to ensure product safety, seafood processing plants will be required to have an approved plan for monitoring their production lines by hazard analysis and critical control point (HACCP) procedures. These procedures will consist of four steps: identifying hazards that can potentially affect a product; identifying critical points in processing where failure could create a hazard; establishing a plan to systematically monitor processing and keep records of such monitoring; and taking and documenting corrective actions.
<P>
The new regulations, which will apply to approximately 5,000 U. S. seafood plants and factory ships as well as to foreign processors, are supposed to take effect in 1996. Expected to eliminate most causes of microbial contamination in seafood, the regulations will allow the seafood industry to police its own quality control at crucial stages of production. However, implementing the regulations will require that tens of thousands of seafood workers, inspectors, and regulators become familiar with HACCP procedures for a variety of fishery species and associated products.
<P>
To aid the seafood industry in complying with the FDA regulations, the National Sea Grant College Program spearheaded the formation of an alliance of industry, government regulators, and the nation's Sea Grant universities. Called the "Seafood HACCP Alliance," it will initiate an educational program in seafood safety procedures.
<P>
The alliance includes the Sea Grant network, the FDA, the Association of Food and Drug Officials, and the Interstate Shellfish Sanitation Conference. Other partners in the alliance are NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service, the U. S. Department of Agriculture, the National Fisheries Institute, and the National Food Processors Association.
<P>
This alliance will bring regulars and industry together to increase the safety and quality of processed seafood and to restore consumer confidence in the nation's seafood. It will focus on training and education and will use educational programs designed to complement voluntary quality control measures already in place at many U.S. seafood plants. Alaska, California, Florida, Louisiana, North Carolina and Virginia Sea Grant programs will play lead roles in this educational effort.
<P>

<P>
  Goals of the alliance include:
<P>
  Developing and implementing a HACCP   training curriculum for seafood workers,   inspectors, and instructors.
<P>
  Designing a method to evaluate and certify   training.
<P>
  Training a cadre of "Seafood HACCP   Instructors" and establishing criteria for   acceptable content of training programs and   for instructor qualifications.
<P>
  Preparing and distributing educational   materials that promote proper seafood   handling.
<P>
  Developing a compendium of safe seafood   processing methods.
<P>
  Exploring use of pilot-testing to introduce   HACCP procedures.
<P>
  Helping design monitoring plans.
<P>
The foundation of the Seafood HACCP Alliance is built in significant part on state regulatory programs and related activities in the Sea Grant and Cooperative Extension Service networks around the nation. In the future, Sea Grant anticipates the alliance will become a self-sustaining program (For details, David Attaway, 301/713-2451 or <A HREF="mailto:dattaway@rdc.noaa.gov">dattaway@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

<!-- MORE for SeaGrantFuture -->
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="MORE"></A>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>
<TD NOWRAP COLSPAN=2 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
Find out more about Sea Grant, please visit:
<BR>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD NOWRAP ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
