<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 3(4)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
July 1994<BR>
Volume 3, Number 4
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Sewage Outfall Studies Save Taxpayers Money</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Christmas Trees Help Protect Vital Dunes</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Sewage Outfall Studies Save Taxpayers Money</H2>
</CENTER>
Ocean sewage outfalls are major sources of contaminants to coastal ocean ecosystems. Although this method of disposal has advantages in terms of economy and relative societal impact, it raises important concerns about seafood safety, public health, and ecosystem health and preservation.
<P>
The ocean offers relatively rapid dilution of many harmful substances, but it can also carry particulates bearing trace metals, bacteria, viruses, DDT and other harmful substances. To discover the potential impacts of these substances on urban populations and coastal ocean ecosystems, the University of Southern California (USC) Sea Grant Program sponsored studies of the White's Point sewage outfall. It is the largest outfall in the U.S., discharging an average of 330 million gallons per day onto the Palos Verdes shelf adjacent to Santa Monica Bay. 
<P>
These studies have produced a wealth of information about the behavior of effluents in the marine environment. Such information increases the ability of sanitation authorities to develop environmentally sound policies for managing urban waste. 
<P>
For example, the White's Point research aided modeling efforts at the Orange County Sanitation District sewage outfall, which enabled managers to assess the effect of sewage effluents on nearby coastal ecosystems. As a result, Orange County water officials give credit to USC Sea Grant for providing the effluent information that has helped them receive secondary treatment waivers under EPA's stringent water quality requirements. Thus, over a 30-year period, taxpayers are saving as much as $50 million a year that would have been spent on additional treatment facilities.
<P>
As demonstrated by Orange County sanitation authorities, USC Sea Grant research at the White Point's outfall has greatly improved the information base from which to make decisions about treating wastewater in Southern California. In addition, lessons learned here can be applied to other large sewage treatment plants around the nation. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Christmas Trees Help Protect Vital Dunes</H2>
</CENTER>
What can be done with that old Christmas tree after the holiday season?  Several years ago, a Texas Sea Grant advisory agent in Brazoria County and a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service agent collaborated on an idea to prevent erosion of the county's shoreline by recycling those trees.
<P>
Begun as a demonstration project, Dunes Day has evolved into a special event in which volunteers stake down Christmas trees to help in the development of dunes. By trapping wind-blown sand, the trees help establish a strong frontal dune line to protect the shoreline from erosion and high tides. In addition, during storms such as hurricanes, the dunes protect the hinterland where there are more valuable properties such as homes, industries, and businesses. 
<P>
Texas Sea Grant was one of the many sponsors of this year's annual event, which took place in January. It drew more than 300 volunteers who staked down an estimated 14,000 trees. 
<P>
However, the tons of sand trapped and miles of dunes constructed are not the only testimony to the volunteers' victories over erosion and subsidence. The volunteers also mentor local school groups and science clubs. This training done in the classroom is followed by hands-on experiences. One result is that people who have built the dunes are not inclined to trash them. The project also keeps discarded trees from landfills, saving space for future needs, and the new dunes provide a home to many plants and animals. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

