<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 1(1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
July 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 1<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Device Improves Oyster Growth Rate and Quality</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Disease-Causing Parasite Cultured in Scientific Breakthrough</A><P>
<A HREF="#3"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Noisemakers Keep Porpoises From Drowning in Nets</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Device Improves Oyster Growth Rate and Quality</H2>
</CENTER>
To address the problem of smaller oyster harvests along the East Coast, a <A HREF="/NCSG/">North Carolina Sea Grant</A> researcher has developed a system that uses floating bags called chubs. The tubular mesh bags each have floats to keep them suspended in the water and contain about three dozen seed oysters. The chubs protect the oysters from predators and lift the shellfish off the muddy estuary bottom into the top of the water column where currents are stronger and there is more oxygen and food. Thus the oysters grow more rapidly with less opportunity for succumbing to diseases.
<P>
Compared to oysters grown in the wild, the chub-produced oysters reach market size in half the time (12 to 18 months) with proportionately less shell and more meat. The new system, which simplifies the maintenance and harvest of oysters, has the potential to move shellfishing away from labor-intensive operations toward more efficient agribusiness. Further tests are needed to determine whether the chub growout system is practical on a large-scale commercial basis. (For details: <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">William Graham</A>, 301/713-2435 x144)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Disease-Causing Parasite Cultured in Scientific Breakthrough</H2>
</CENTER>
Dermo (<I>Perkinsus marinus</I>) has been causing mass mortalities of the Chesapeake Bay oyster since the mid-1980s. Now, a <A HREF="/MDSG/">Maryland Sea Grant</A> researcher has developed a method for culturing that protozoan parasite in the laboratory. The laboratory breakthrough is the critical first step in finding a cure for the disease caused by the parasite. The next step is to learn the strategies the parasite has evolved to avoid the oyster's natural defense mechanisms and how it causes the disease that kills the oyster.
<P>
The Chesapeake Bay once supplied more than half the oysters eaten in this country, but the bay harvest now only accounts for approximately 10 percent. This dramatic decline of bay oysters and its commercial fishery is coupled with the increasing recognition that the loss of oysters could help account for deteriorating water quality. Scientists have estimated that the bivalves, which filter-feed on algae clouding the bay, once filtered the volume of the bay every week. (For details: <A HREF="mailto:fritz.schuler@noaa.gov">Francis Schuler</A>, 301-713-2445 x160)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="3"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Noisemakers Keep Porpoises From Drowning in Nets</H2>
</CENTER>
To solve the growing problem of harbor porpoises drowning after becoming entangled in gillnets, a <A HREF=" http://unhinfo.unh.edu:70/unh/acad/special/seagrant/index.html">New Hampshire Sea Grant</A> outreach specialist has been testing an adaptation of a device which has proven successful in keeping whales away from fishing gear. The device has small spherical metal balls with battery-operated noisemakers inside that make the fishing gear more "visible" to marine mammals.
<P>
The specialist, using statistically designed experiments with both control and "acoustically armed" nets, outfitted four gillnetters with the device to test it with harbor porpoises. <A HREF="http://kingfish.ssp.nmfs.gov:80/home-page.html">NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service</A> cooperated in the research by providing 60 days of observer coverage.
<P>
The acoustically armed nets did not have a single incidence of porpoise entanglement while the control nets had 10. To validate the initial findings, a larger more statistically significant project will be carried out later this year. In the meantime, Rhode Island Sea Grant is planning to modify the noisemaking device for use by the swordfish driftnet fishery to avoid marine mammal entanglement problems. (For details: <A HREF="mailto:shirley.fiske@noaa.gov">Shirley Fiske</A>, 301-713-2431 x148)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

<!-- MORE for SeaGrantResults -->

