<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
March 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Navigational Safety Improved</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Shrimp Growers Better Able to Compete in World Markets</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]"> Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Navigational Safety Improved
</H2>
</CENTER>
<A HREF="http://unhinfo.unh.edu:70/unh/acad/special/seagrant/index.html">New Hampshire Sea Grant</A> researchers have designed a device which not only will improve navigational safety but also should save taxpayers millions of dollars. The device, a collision tolerant pile structure (CTPS), will be used to support the markers or lights known as aids to navigation (ATONs). The ATONs are used in shallow waterways to mark safe passage routes for all types of marine craft.
<P>
The rigid wood pile structures now used by the U.S. Coast Guard to support ATONs are easily damaged when struck by commercial vessels. These collisions can sometimes destroy the wood structure as well as the ATON, leaving the channel unmarked and the pile position unknown; damage can also result to the vessel. This situation poses a safety hazard as well as an environmental hazard since many cargoes contain petroleum products that could be spilled.
<P>
Hundreds of these structures are lost annually, and the replacement cost of each is $5,000 to $10,000. By replacing the wood piles with the new CTPS, costs can be tremendously reduced and navigation safety greatly enhanced.
<P>
The CTPS designed by New Hampshire Sea Grant consists of an ATON mounted on a single pile which has a foam core. It is hinged just above the mudline and contains compression springs that return it to an upright position after a collision.
<P>
To test the device, three prototypes were designed by Sea Grant researchers and built for the U.S. Coast Guard. The CTPS had to be able to survive five collisions a year to fully meet the design goals set by the Coast Guard. Two were deployed in the Houston Ship Channel in 1990 and have withstood repeated collisions-m ore than 20 each-and are still operating as designed. A third was installed off the New Hampshire coast to check responses to severe environmental forces. It too has operated as anticipated.
<P>
The results have so pleased the Coast Guard that it has ordered 30 more CTPS to be built at a cost of about $20,000 each. They will be deployed in critical navigation areas around the country. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:shirleyfiske@noaa.gov">Shirley Fiske</A>, 301/7132431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Shrimp Growers Better Able to Compete in World Markets
</CENTER>
</H2>
Because of high labor costs, U.S. shrimp growers have turned to capital intensive, highly automated aquaculture systems to complete in world markets. Now, thanks to Arizona researchers supported by <A HREF="../index.html">NOAA Sea Grant</A>, growers will be able to use a simple, diagnostic gene probe in kit form to screen aquacultured shrimp for infectious hypodermal hematopoietic necrosis virus (IHHNV).
<P>
IHHNV causes runt deformity syndrome in while shrimp, the major species grown in the U.S. It is linked to significantly lower shrimp growth and harvest rates which translate into lower market values and reduced profits for growers.
<P>
While working on characterization of IHHNV, the researchers found a method to clone its genome, an event which marked the first such accomplishment for a marine invertebrate virus. This step led to the development of gene probes for IHHNV.
<P>
After issuing a patent disclosure for the diagnostic probe, the researchers worked with DiagXotics Inc., a company in Wilton, Connecticut, which specializes in manufacturing test kits for aquaculture applications. The collaboration resulted in a simple, ready-to-use kit which gives results within 12 to 24 hours. Growers can use it to analyze tissue samples from shrimp of unknown health to test if IHHNV is present or to assess the prevalence of IHHNV infection by testing a selected number of individuals from a shrimp population. Test results can be used to develop management strategies such as using a different hatchery supplier for the next crop to avoid further contamination. In addition, the kit can be used as a means to certify the health status of postlarvae or juveniles headed for grow-out facilities, or as a nonlelthal method for certification of broodstock. 
<P>
Besides the IHHNV gene probe, three other probes are under development by Arizona researchers and DiagXotics for use with three different shrimp viruses. These probes will provide essential tools to the U.S. shrimp aquaculture industry so that it is not as prone to the catastrophic disease losses that have recently affected shrimp aquaculture interests overseas. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:jim.mcvey@noaa.gov">Jim McVey</A>, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

<!-- MORE for SeaGrantResults -->

<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="MORE"></A>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>
<TD NOWRAP COLSPAN=2 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
Find out more about Sea Grant, please visit:
<BR>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD NOWRAP ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
