<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(5)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
May 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 5
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Remote Sensing for Science, Commerce, and Public Safety</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Remote Sensing for Science, Commerce, and Public Safety</H2>
</CENTER>
The ability to monitor the Earth's environment via satellites increases understanding of environmental processes and contributes to both economic efficiency and public safety. With rapid development of remote sensing technology, scientists and managers can now obtain data on spatial and time scales previously impossible or unaffordable. Sea Grant, in cooperation with other NOAA elements, actively supports the technological development of new capabilities in remote sensing applications for the ocean, coastal, and Great Lakes environments.
<P>
One of the first applications of satellite sensing has been to measure radiances from the sea surface at wave lengths representative of phytoplankton-like pigments. These radiances, converted to bio-optical parameters such as ocean color and plant pigment concentrations, are widely used in global change studies, by fisheries managers, and by commercial fisheries to optimize catch. However, the water-leaving radiances are a small portion of the total signal received by the satellite and, before valid data can be obtained, corrections must be made for atmospheric interferences.
<P>
Utilizing imagery from the Coastal Zone Color Scanner (CZCS), California Sea Grant scientists are developing new procedures for handling the atmospheric radiance terms. This will result in more accurate estimates of pigment concentrations from the CZCS and, thus, of ocean productivity and color. In addition, the pigment extraction algorithms developed will be applicable to the Sea-viewing Wide Field-of-view Sensor (SeaWIFS), the ocean color sensor to be launched in 1994.
<P>
Data on bay-wide productivity will be essential to evaluating the success of the nutrient reduction program in Chesapeake Bay. To meet this need, the new SeaWIFS satellite will provide synoptic data through time. Since coastal and estuarine waters are much more turbid than ocean waters, special algorithms are needed to convert radiances into pigment concentrations. Maryland Sea Grant researchers, working closely with the NASA SeaWIFS Office, are developing the algorithms necessary to measure bay productivity over time.
<P>
The COASTWATCH program, developed by NOAA's Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service with support from NOAA's Coastal Ocean Program (COP), makes Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer (AVHRR) weather satellite images available in near-real-time to the marine community. Ohio Sea Grant and NOAA's Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory (GLERL), with COP support, have developed the Lake Erie Forecast System (LEFS) as a pilot for a Great Lakes Forecast System. Using NOAA models run on the Ohio State supercomputer, the LEFS utilizes lake-surface temperature derived from the AVHRR provided by the COASTWATCH center at GLERL, along with data from NOAA's Weather Service and the U.S. Geological Survey. Forecasts include three-dimensional currents and temperature distributions, water levels, and wave heights. To improve LEFS forecasts, current Ohio Sea Grant research is focused on developing improved predictive functions for surface heat flux from AVHRR data.
<P>
Readily available COASTWATCH near-real-time AVHRR images are spurring new applications research. Woods Hole Sea Grant researchers have found that sea-surface temperatures (SST) derived from these images help to study bloom dynamics of the dinoflagellate causing outbreaks of paralytic shellfish poisoning (PSP) in the Gulf of Maine. A warm coastal current, believed to carry the dinoflagellate to the south, was easily resolved by SST imagery, demonstrating its great promise to provide early warning of conditions conducive for bloom development and movement.
<P>
In addition, Wisconsin Sea Grant scientists have combined SST COASTWATCH data for Green Bay with bathymetric and substrate data from the National Geophysical Data Center to identify bay areas at high risk for zebra mussel colonization. This information, combined with census data identifying areas where colonization would have a major impact, enables industry and governments to direct resources to the most critical locations.
<P>
Michigan Sea Grant scientists are using COASTWATCH images to develop black-and-white temperature contour maps of Lake Michigan. Intended to help recreational fishermen locate fish, the maps can be faxed to ports and marinas. A demonstration project is currently underway and, if successful, this technology will be transferred to the private sector.
<P>
Currently, the U.S. fishing fleet uses antiquated remote sensing technology that significantly diminishes AVHRR imagery information. In contrast, some foreign fishery fleets and managers are moving to a high resolution picture transmission system coupled with a geographic information system (GIS). California Sea Grant scientists are developing software for a remote sensing/GIS system that would integrate remotely sensed data, environmental observations, bathymetry, fish catch statistics, and weather conditions into a real-time information resource tool to be used by both fishermen and stock assessment managers. Working closely with NOAA's Marine Fisheries Service and the West Coast commercial and sports fisheries, fishing and stock assessment management groups will be field testing the system this year. (For details, William Graham, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:bgraham@rdc.noaa.gov">bgraham@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

