<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(4)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
April 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 4
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Exploring the Oceans with Unmanned Vehicles</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Exploring the Oceans with Unmanned Vehicles</H2>
</CENTER>
Exploring the oceans has depended on sampling from surface vessels or on using manned submersible vehicles. In both cases, the process is slow, and the coverage in time and space is necessarily very limited. Operation of both manned submersibles and sophisticated unmanned tethered submersibles called remotely operated vehicles (ROVs) requires very costly support from large surface vessels. The hazards, the unknowns, and the expense of exploring for research and for resources increase dramatically with depth. Therefore, the deep oceans remain a mysterious and a largely unexplored frontier. Scientists are quick to point out that more is known about the surfaces of other planets than about the ocean depths on Earth.
<P>
In recent years, it has become clear that special purpose, unmanned submersible vehicles can augment or replace manned submersibles. Indeed, the ROV is already considered "state of the art" for many survey, inspection, and simple work tasks. The ROV, however, suffers from serious limitations due to the "tether" that connects it to a surface ship for power and communication purposes. The tether is easily entangled on obstacles, and produces serious hydrodynamic drag on the vehicle when it is operating at greater depths. Clearly, the goal of providing an affordable means for exploring unmapped environments otherwise unreachable by humans can only be met by a truly free-swimming or Autonomous Underwater Vehicle (AUV).
<P>
AUV research by Sea Grant has been concentrated at the Florida, Hawaii, MIT, New Hampshire, Texas, and Washington programs. Cooperation and joint sponsorship of various projects have been received from NOAA's National Undersea Research Program, the Office of Naval Research (ONR), National Science Foundation, Advanced Research Projects Agency, Naval Surface Weapons Center, Naval Explosive Ordnance Disposal Technology Center, and also from many industrial supporters. Work to date has largely been directed at the key technical issues such as navigation and control systems, optical and other sensors, power systems, and communication among vehicles and with surface ships.
<P>
Recent research successes have created the prototype of a new class of AUV capable of vastly increasing human presence in the ocean. Although there are still major engineering issues to be addressed, technology has progressed to the point where small, long-range AUVs can economically execute missions that are impossible to perform with tethered vehicles (such as in under-ice operations) or are expensive with conventional methods (such as in deep ocean surveys).
<P>
Sea Grant AUV research is now focused at MIT. The MIT prototype vehicle, Odyssey 11, was built from components costing less than $75,000. It weighs 360 pounds, can travel 170 miles at depths up to 3.7 miles, and is the first deep diving AUV to carry a sonar system and two acoustic navigation systems.
<P>
During March 1994, Odyssey 11 undertook its first major scientific mission. With ONR support, the vehicle was launched from a hole cut through five-foot thick ice at a camp approximately 170 miles offshore of Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's northern coast. It made several runs beneath the ice, conducting preliminary tests of under-ice mapping and obtaining data on conductivity, temperature, and depth before piloting itself back into a capture net at its point of entry.
<P>
In upcoming missions, plans call for Odyssey 11 to study hydrothermal vent systems on the Juan de Fuca Ridge off the Washington coast in August and on the East Pacific Rise west of Central America in October. The ultimate goal of Sea Grant's work on AUVs is to develop a network in which many low-cost AUVs operating interactively from remote sites will collect oceanographic data over greater areas and for longer periods. This scope of scientific data collection has not been possible before. It should open a new era in understanding the oceans and their resources. (For details, Richard Kolf, 301/713-2445 or <A HREF="mailto:dkolf@rdc.noaa.gov">dkolf@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

