<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(10)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
October 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 10
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Helping Coastal Businesses Deal with Change</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Helping Coastal Businesses Deal with Change</H2>
</CENTER>
Businesses in coastal regions are experiencing rapid changes in their business environment. For example, enterprises engaged in the seafood industry, coastal tourism and recreation, and marine trades face greater burdens than in the past because of factors such as scarce natural resources, environmental and public safety regulations, waterfront displacement, and increased competition.
<P>
To grow and sustain themselves, these businesses must be able to respond quickly to changing markets, adjust to changes in regulatory requirements, adapt new technology or processes as they become available, and evaluate economic options. Assisting both small and large coastal businesses is a major, ongoing challenge for the Sea Grant network. Through scores of daily contacts, Sea Grant helps coastal businesses deal with change.
<P>
Because New England groundfish stocks are at an all-time low, New Hampshire Sea Grant is working to develop a sustainable East Coast hagfish fishery. Collaborating with Washington Sea Grant, which had experience working with Pacific hagfish, and with additional support from the New England Fisheries Development Association and NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service, Sea Grant outreach specialists are teaching New England fishermen the best methods to harvest hagfish. The hagfish are then sold to South Korean markets where they are processed and their skin is used to produce leather goods. Currently 10 vessels from Gloucester, Massachusetts, north to Stonington, Maine, are fishing for hagfish, providing income opportunities to some of New England's beleaguered groundfishermen. First-year landings are anticipated to be valued at $600,000.
<P>
Aquaculture is a highly competitive, dynamic industry subject to a great deal of risk and uncertainty. Remaining a viable producer requires a firm grasp of biological and production techniques as well as the ability to use financial information to make business decisions. To help potential investors assess the current financial status of an aquaculture business, Sea Grant business specialists nationwide have adapted fundamental tools for financial decisionmaking. One of these tools is Maryland Sea Grant's computer-based aquaculture financial simulator (AQUASIM). It is designed to evaluate the inherent risks associated with aquaculture businesses such as fluctuating market prices and uncertainty about fish survival during production. Since every aquaculture operator has different views about the performance of his enterprise, AQUASIM, using a semblance of artificial intelligence, helps quantify the expectations of production performance and is adaptable to almost any species being cultured. Distributed nationally, AQUASIM has been used to assess nearly 50 planned or existing culture operations in Maryland alone.
<P>
Coastal tourism development is very important to the economic base of coastal communities. Therefore, Ohio Sea Grant, with support from the National Coastal Resources Research and Development Institute, conducted Tourism Business Retention and Expansion Programs in counties bordering Ohio's Lake Erie Coast. The core component of these programs is a set of visits to tourism businesses to obtain information about their business issues. Visitors are also surveyed to obtain information about their activities and expenditures. This information is then used to help communities develop marketing strategies for their recreational amenities and to help local economic development programs assist tourism businesses more effectively.
<P>
In the future, Sea Grant will continue to provide outreach services critical in helping businesses operate efficiently and increase productivity, adapt new technologies and processes, and train a workforce that will produce quality goods and services in return for good wages. (For details, Fritz Schuler, 301/7l3-2445 or <A HREF="mailto:fschuler@rdc.noaa.gov">fschuler@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

