<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 3(1)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 1
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Green Bay Study Offers National Model
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Crab Meat Recovery Increases Industry Yields</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Green Bay Study Offers National Model
</H2>
</CENTER>
The Green Bay PCB Mass Balance Study is the first complete input-output study ever conducted on what happens to a toxic chemical in an aquatic ecosystem. Because of this landmark national study, resource managers now have a much-needed mass balance model for assessing the sources, movements, and ultimate fates of toxic industrial and agricultural chemicals in U.S. waters.
<P>
This five-year study was funded by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) because of national concern about persistent toxic chemicals in the environment. The deciding factor in the EPA's choice of Green Bay as the site for this unprecedented national study was the wealth of available expertise and scientific data on Great Lakes contaminants developed by <A HREF="http://h2o.seagrant.wisc.edu/home.html">Wisconsin Sea Grant</A>-sponsored research over the past 25 years.
<P>
Though focused specifically on polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) in Green Bay, Lake Michigan, this model will also help decisionmakers identify the most cost-effective strategies for cleaning up lead, dieldrin, cadmium and similar toxic chemicals in the Great Lakes and coastal estuaries. Covering 1,640 square miles, Green Bay is the largest freshwater estuary in the world. In size and other physical characteristics, it is similar to the Delaware Bay estuary.
<P>
Launched in 1988, the Green Bay Mass Balance Study involved researchers from a dozen universities nationwide, six federal agencies, and the Wisconsin and Michigan departments of natural resources. Wisconsin Sea Grant scientists and former Sea Grant-supported students were among the study's Lead investigators.
<P>
The study showed that- except for cleaning up one highly contaminated stretch of the river- the most effective strategy for eliminating PCBs from Green Bay over the next 25 years was simply to let them become buried in bottom sediments.
<P>
Thanks in large part to the long-term Sea Grant investment in PCB and Green Bay research, Wisconsin will save hundreds of millions of dollars cleaning up the bay. In addition, the nation has a highly successful model for developing rational and cost-effective strategies for cleaning up its contaminated estuaries and bays, which ultimately may save the U.S. billions of dollars. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">William Graham</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Crab Meat Recovery Increases Industry Yields
</H2>
</CENTER>
Since steam-processed blue crabs yield only about 10 percent meat by weight when hand-picked, the blue crab industry generates about 180 million pounds of waste each year. In Georgia, the picking room scrap was either discarded in landfills or processed into low-value crab meal. For help in recovering meat from crab picking wastes, two of the state's largest processors contacted Georgia Sea Grant researchers.
<P>
This led to a three-year <A HREF="http://alpha.marsci.uga.edu/gaseagrant.html">Georgia Sea Grant</A> project during which annual minced meat recovery by the two processors increased from 20,000 pounds to more than 400,000 pounds. As a result, waste disposal costs lowered and profits increased from the sale of the recovered meat for human consumption as an extender in deviled crab, seafood stuffings, soups, and chowders and for pct food. Minced meat sales made the difference between net profit and net loss for one of the processors.
<P>
To achieve these results, Sea Grant researchers first conducted studies to evaluate the characteristics of byproducts separated into four groups-minced white meat, minced leg meat, minced claw meat, and mixed minced meal. Chemical, sensory, microbiological, and nutritional qualities were then determined for these meats.
<P>
Next, the seafood technologists developed processing recommendations for minced meat products. For example, they found that low temperature pasteurization reduced discoloration. In addition, they found that lactic acid dips or mild steaming of picking-room byproducts reduced bacterial levels and that blending surimi with minced crab meat improved the flavor, odor and texture characteristics of the recovered meat.
<P>
This project did more than cut costs and increase profits and employment in Georgia's blue crab industry. Consumers benefited from safe, new seafood products and extenders; stress on landfills was lightened; and science of safe seafood processing was advanced with the new data that was developed. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">William Graham</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

