<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(5)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 5
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  New Coho Breed Spurs Domestic and Foreign Markets </A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Menhaden Bycatch Study Helps Save Jobs</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Coho Breed Spurs<BR>
Domestic and Foreign Markets
</H2>
</CENTER>
Through selective breeding, <A HREF="http://www.wsg.washington.edu/">Washington Sea Grant</A> researchers and private aquaculturists have tripled the growth rates of native coho salmon. This new coho breed now helps support a $5 million domestic industry.
<P>
Since the supply and quality of coho eggs available from hatcheries varied greatly according to the size of wild returns, a salmon farming company, Domsea Farms, Inc. of Manchester, Washington, decided try to develop its own stock.
<P>
Therefore, research began in 1977 as a collaborative effort between Washington Sea Grant and Domsea. Domsea supplied the fish, manpower, and rearing facilities. Sea Grant provided the breeding expertise and a crucial intangible: commitment. Ten years of support was provided, enough to cover five breeding cycles.
<P>
The primary goal of the Washington Sea Grant/Domsea program was to create and maintain domesticated broodstock capable of rapid growth and good survival in intensive culture conditions. Results from the Sea Grant 10-year project exceeded expectations. A 1977-78 vintage yearling weighed no more than 300 grams, while mature fish averaged about 850 grams. By 1990, yearlings tipped the scales from 650 to 900 grams; mature two-year olds reached a whopping 3,000 grams.
<P>
Domsea, now called Domsea Broodstock, Inc., sells five to eight million domesticated coho eggs annually to aquaculturists in Chile, Europe, Japan, and the United States. The Washington-based company is the primary egg supplier for domestic coho farmers who brought approximately two million pounds of fish to market during 1993.
<P>
The significance of the Washington Sea Grant/Domsea breeding program extends beyond the development of a new variety of fish. Internationally, it is a prototype for marine breeding; locally, it serves as a model for the future of the West Coast aquaculture industry. (For details, Eugene Fritz, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Menhaden Bycatch Study Helps Save Jobs
</CENTER>
</H2>
Fishery managers, regulators, and the general public have become increasingly concerned about bycatch or the incidental harvesting of non-target species. Their major concern is that commercial fishers are wasting resources by harvesting both the important game fish .and the prey of major commercial and recreational species.
<P>
From Maine to North Carolina, recreational fishing and environmental groups have sought legislation to restrict menhaden fishing, particularly in coastal waters of the Mid-Atlantic Bight. So far, legislation prohibiting menhaden fishing in state waters has been passed by New Jersey and Delaware. And, in 1994, legislation was introduced to restrict it in Virginia, North Carolina, and Rhode Island.
<P>
This legislation has been introduced because of concerns that the menhaden fleet harvests excessive levels of bycatch. To address these concerns, the <A HREF="/VASG/index.html">Virginia Sea Grant Advisory Program</A> conducted a one year study on bycatch levels in the Mid-Atlantic menhaden fisher. Results of the study, funded by the Saltonstall-Kennedy Program of NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service (<A HREF = "http://kingfish.ssp.nmfs.gov:80/home-page.html">NMFS</A>), demonstrated that for every 2,440 menhaden harvested, approximately one fish or shellfish other than menhaden was caught, which was 0.041 percent of the total harvest.
<P>
The study results were published in <I>Bycatch and the Fishery for Atlantic Menhaden in the Mid-Atlantic Bight: An Assessment of the Nature and Extent of Bycatch</I>. This report was used by Virginia and North Carolina legislators and served as a partial basis for their decision not to restrict menhaden fishing in state waters.
<P>
As a consequence, what could have been a threatened industry continues to operate, employing more than 800  individuals. Those 800 jobs represent an approximate annual payroll of $18 million dollars. (For details, Bud Griswold, 301/713-2431) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

