<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 2(7)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
July 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 7
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Wetlands Research Yields Insights into Coastal Problems</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Wetlands Research Yields Insights into Coastal Problems</H2>
</CENTER>
Coastal wetlands in the U.S. are literally between a rock and a hard place. On one side there is rising sea level and, on the other side, there is frequently something that does not allow transgression such as a housing development, a shopping mall, or an interstate highway. By studying the physical processes responsible for forming wetlands, scientists can gain valuable insights into potential solutions for many related coastal problems.
<P>
The study of the processes that determine the form of tidal flats has suffered because there is a lack of understanding about the erodibility and transport of the fine-grained material that dominates a wetland. Physical properties of sediment deposits in wetlands tend to be nonhomogeneous. They also vary with salinity and are strongly influenced by the associated plant and animal life. Because of recent research advances in many scientific disciplines, Woods Hole Sea Grant scientists believe this is an advantageous time to study the physical processes that are important on tidal flats. Part of this study will be to design and field test instrumentation for measuring the bulk properties of fine sediments in situ. The researchers also plan to develop a theoretical and empirical framework for assessing fine-grain sediment erosion and transport in the context of tidal flats.
<P>
In an era of rising sea level, one important question about wetlands concerns the nature of their transgression into the hinterland. To answer this question, Delaware Sea Grant researchers are trying to determine the rates of marsh transgression into the state's uplands and river valleys. It appears that current wetlands are considerably narrower than those of 3,500 years ago. Further, in all probability, with sea level rising at an increasing rate, future wetlands will be narrower than those of today. In addition, there is clear evidence that tidal wetlands are being rapidly destroyed by shoreline erosion. These findings indicate that Delaware's tidal marshes are both dynamic and fragile.
<P>
To predict the future extent of Delaware's wetlands and the characteristics of their transgression into the uplands, the researchers are developing conceptual and numerical models. These models will be useful in helping coastal managers and planners make wetland policy decisions. They will also be used to provide reasonable answers to "what if" scenarios. Since much of both the East and Gulf coasts is morphologically similar to Delaware's coast, these models should have general application.
<P>
It is often assumed that there is a direct link between recent anthropogenic increases in greenhouse gases and global warming and that this, in turn, is leading to sea level rise. Connecticut Sea Grant researchers indicate this simple scenario is probably not correct. Detailed investigations of tidal marshes along Long Island Sound indicate that there was a pronounced increase in the rate of sea level rise about 1700 AD. However, modern global warming only became apparent about 1870 AD. Data collection is continuing, and it is being collated with related data from all over the world. It is expected that what currently appears to be an anomalous finding will be resolved to yield new insight into this complex problem of interaction among greenhouse gases, climate, and sea level rise.
<P>
Until recently, people living on the Oregon coast did not feel threatened by earthquakes. However, new understanding of plate tectonics suggests that strong subduction zone earthquakes can occur not only off Oregon's coast but also off the coasts of Washington, Northern California, and British Columbia. In addition to the threat of earthquakes to these coasts, there is also the threat of flooding due to tsunamis. Although, in modem times, earthquakes and locally-generated tsunamis have not been observed in these areas, there is a real need to determine how often such events might occur and how severe they might be. Therefore, Oregon Sea Grant scientists are examining the geological record of wetlands and flood- plains along the state's coast to identify past catastrophic events and to evaluate the potential for future devastating coastal subsidence, erosion, and flooding generated by earthquakes along the Juan de Fuca Ridge and North American plates off the Pacific Northwest coast.
<P>
As a result of these and other studies, scientists are beginning to be able to quantify the importance of wetlands, which moderate floods, maintain water quality, and provide critical habitat for many species of plants and animals. Louisiana Sea Grant has published a report to educate the public about these valuable natural resources. Called "The Fragile Fringe: Coastal Wetlands of the Continental United States," it is a comprehensive perspective on the status of U.S. wetlands. (For details, John Ahrens, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:jahrens@rdc.noaa.gov">jahrens@rdc.noaa.gov</A>)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

<!-- MORE for SeaGrantFuture -->
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="MORE"></A>
