<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(3)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
May 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 3
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Fishermen Prepared for Emergencies at Sea
</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  New Business Spurred by Pump Design</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]"> Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Navigational Safety Improved
</H2>
</CENTER>
Late last year, skills learned at ><A HREF="http://www.wsg.washington.edu/">Washington Sea Grant's</A> fishing vessel safety training classes paid big benefits to the captains and crews of two vessels caught in a winter storm. Both vessels, part of the Dungeness crab fleet, were making a run to the fishing grounds to drop pots, when the storm hit with winds of 55 to 60 miles per hour.
<P>
On one boat, a shifting load of crab pots apparently knocked a crew member overboard. He was pulled unconscious from the water by the crew and revived by the captain who used cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) learned at a Sea Grant first aid course. Meanwhile, a second boat was taking on water. When a Coast Guard helicopter arrived on the scene and lowered an emergency pump, the captain knew exactly what to do. It was the same type of pump he had readied and started in drills during a Sea Grant safety and survival class 10 days earlier. And, since Sea Grant coordinates its safety program with Coast Guard air and boat stations, the captain was also familiar with Coast Guard procedures. 
<P>
In addition to these two captains, Washington Sea Grant trained over 130 persons last year in fishing vessel safety classes conducted at ports around the state. The classes have very intensive "hands-on" training. This type of training, also offered on the Pacific Coast by the <A HREF="http://info.alaska.edu/UA/UA_Fairbanks/SeaGrant">Alaska</A> and <A HREF="http://seagrant.orst.edu">Oregon Sea Grant</A> programs, enables crews to avoid succumbing to panic when there is an emergency at sea. Sea Grant has found that having equipment demonstrated and used, having fishermen get into their survival suits and crawl into life rafts in both swimming pools and harbor areas, having proper training in first aid and the use of CPR, and having onboard drills are extremely important and critical in saving both lives and property. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:fritz.schuler@noaa.gov">Fritz Schuler</A>, 301/713-2445)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Business Spurred by Pump Design
</CENTER>
</H2>
Manufactured by the firm Composite High Pressure Technologies (CHPT), the DELPUMP is a direct descendant of the DELBUOY, a wave-driven desalination system developed under the sponsorship of <A HREF="/DELSG/">Delaware Sea Grant</A>. Although DELPUMP is presently more of a commercial success than its ancestor, it owes its existence in large part to the component engineering undertaken for the DELBUOY. While designing the wave-powered pump, much was Iearned about water-lubricated polymeric bearings and composite construction allowing for the complete redesign of conventional metallic pumps.
<P>
This knowledge gained about high performance engineering plastics and composite materials was used to design the DELPUMP from scratch as a reverse osmosis seawater desalination pump. This approach differs greatly from other pump companies that have taken oil-field type pumps and reworked them to operate in reverse osmosis service. Advantages inherent in the DELPUMP's design such as corrosion resistance, light weight, and no oil lubrication make it well suited not only for use in desalination but also for submersible, food/chemical processing, industrial, machine tool, and mining applications.
<P>
The student who collaborated in the design of the DELBUOY earned his doctoral degree in marine studies and subsequently became the president of CHPT, Inc., which he formed in 1991. DELPUMPS have been sold to all four branches of the U.S. military, the Canadian Army and Navy, several commercial reverse-osmosis system assemblers (domestic and international), and companies supplying filtration equipment to the chemical processing industry.
<P>
Although the ancestor, DELBUOY, is not quite ready to be offered for commercial sale, it has strong potential. The DELBUOY produces fresh water from sea water without using electricity, fuels or motors and, since the DELBUOY is wave-powered, it is ideal for island and coastal areas where drinking water is in short supply. The concept is sound and the pump has been demonstrated extensively in conjunction with Puerto Rico Sea Grant off its coast. When financing is available to carry it through the transition from limited to full production, DELBUOY could be even more of a commercial success than DELPUMP. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:victor.omelczenko@noaa.gov">Victor Omelczenko</A>, 301/7132431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

