<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 3(3)</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:jacobs@umbi.umd.edu">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
January 1995<BR>
Volume 3, Number 3
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Socioeconomic Research Supports Fisheries Management
</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Socioeconomic Research Supports Fisheries Management
</H2>
</CENTER>
The Sea Grant network sponsored a National Issues Forum--Can America Save its Fisheries?--recently at the National Press Club in Washington, DC. Speakers from industry, government, and the scientific community discussed the problems facing U.S. fisheries and possible solutions to those problems.
<P>
Although no single change in the management of the nation¹s fisheries will solve all their ills, controlling access is one mechanism that is receiving serious consideration. For example, Individual Transferable Quotas (ITQs), are beginning to be used as a method of allocating a share of the allowable harvest to individuals. In turn, these shares can be transferred or traded. The primary feature of ITQs is the assignment of exclusive property rights for the harvest of a commonproperty resource. While ITQs are not viewed as a total panacea (they are complex to implement, for example), they will help provide a rational approach to managing fisheries through economic incentives that lead to resource conservation. 
<P>
Sea Grant programs nationwide have conducted long-term, socioeconomic research on fisheries management, including consideration of market-like mechanisms for allocating access to fish stocks. California Sea Grant conducted some of the earliest work studying how the implementation of  ITQs in other countries could serve as a model for the U.S.  Sea Grant researchers in Delaware and New Jersey played a key role in designing an ITQ system for the Atlantic surf clam and ocean quahog fishery, the first application of ITQs in the U.S.  Since the ITQ management system was implemented in 1991, these fisheries have stabilized.  Delaware Sea Grant is now continuing research to understand how existing firms adapted and how  income was redistributed.
<P>
Recently, the state of North Carolina placed a two-year moratorium on the sale of new commercial fishing licenses. North Carolina Sea Grant was asked to administer for the state a study of future management options and to derive better data about the people who fish. As part of this effort, Sea Grant social science researchers will be working with the fishing industry to discuss what types of limited entry might work in North Carolina.
<P>
An economist and legal scholar at Maine-New Hampshire Sea Grant are jointly studying the new approaches to rights-based fisheries management that might be created to control fishing pressure. Each of the management strategies to be studied -- fractional shares, ITQ banks, and fishery trusts -- seeks to solve some of  the well-known problems with limited entry or ITQ schemes. 
<P>
Since very little is known about the cumulative impacts on other fisheries from limiting access to a target species, Oregon Sea Grant researchers are looking at the impact of access limitation on a system of linked fisheries--groundfish, Dungeness crab, and pink shrimp.   In Texas, the expected incorporation of limited entry into managing the shrimp fishery will constitute a major change in this industry.  Texas Sea Grant researchers are studying the economic impacts of a limited entry program by developing a general, bioeconomic-fisheries-simulation model for the Gulf of Mexico shrimp fishery.  And in Alaska, Sea Grant economists are developing a model to assess alternative access limitations programs for the groundfish and crab fisheries. 
<P>
Currently, Sea Grant has two new major efforts to study the socioeconomic impacts of innovative fishery management strategies. In Rhode Island, one part of a multidisciplinary Sea Grant effort will be to assess the full economic and social consequences of implementing the actions necessary to rebuild the New England groundfish stocks. In Oregon, a team of researchers and outreach specialists is developing the socioeconomic knowledge needed to assess the impacts on people from changes occurring in the Pacific Northwest fisheries. 
<P>
These Sea Grant  socioeconomic research and outreach efforts related to fisheries management are helping to provide the information base that will be needed to secure a stable future for the families, businesses, and communities that depend upon having a sustainable fishing industry. (For details, Fritz Schuler, 301/713-2445)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

