<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grnat Office: Sea Grant Results 4(2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
March 1996<BR>
Volume 4, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Oil Spill Receives Quick Response
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Program Promotes Environmentally-Friendly Lawn Care
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Oil Spill Receives Quick Response
</H2>
</CENTER>
The worst oil spill in Rhode Island's history occurred in January after stormy seas caused the tugboat Scandia and its barge to run aground on the state's south shore. Before salvage workers were able to stop the flow of oil, almost a million gallons leaked from the barge into Block Island Sound.  <A HREF="http://seagrant.gso.uri.edu/riseagrant">Rhode Island Sea Grant</A> researchers and outreach specialists were able to quickly respond to this accident not only because they were on site and supported by a small amount of  rapid response funds but also because of the long-term history of Sea Grant research and outreach activities in the area.
<P>
Within hours of the accident, a Rhode Island Sea Grant researcher was at work running an innovative hydrodynamic computer model he had previously developed for Narragansett Bay. He produced an animated model to predict the path of the leaked oil and, for several days, continued these predictions.  They were passed on to the Rhode Island Marine Safety Office and then to the U.S. Coast Guard to aid their containment and cleanup efforts.
<P>
Braving stormy seas, Sea Grant outreach specialists, accompanied by scientists from the Narragansett Laboratory of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), were first on the scene to assess the oil spill's damage to the environment.  Using a University of Rhode Island research vessel, they obtained samples of fish, surface and bottom water, and  bottom sediment for chemical analysis by the EPA.
<P>
Another Sea Grant researcher, who has been studying the area's lobster fishery for many years, accompanied fishermen to pull pots to evaluate the effects of the oil spill on lobster abundance.  Divers returned to the site later to gather additional estimates of abundance for comparison with Sea Grant baseline data.
<P>
Within days of the accident, the Sea Grant communications staff developed a WWW site (<A HREF="http://brooktrout.gso.uri.edu:80/riseagrant/oilspill.html">http://brooktrout.gso.uri.edu:80/riseagrant/oilspill.html</A>) that provided information about the spill to a concerned public and the media.  This information was also used by the Governor's Office as a source for scientific statements about the accident, particularly on how it related to seafood safety and tourism. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:leon.cammen@noaa.gov">Leon Cammen</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Program Promotes Environmentally-Friendly Lawn Care
</H2>
</CENTER>

Estimates show that homeowners use 10 times more chemicals per acre to grow attractive lawns than do farmers to grow crops. These fertilizers and pesticides, under some conditions, can contribute to nonpoint source pollution problems in coastal waters.  To educate homeowners how to care for lawns and landscapes using environmentally-friendly practices, <A HREF="http://www.cce.cornell.edu/seagrant/">New York Sea Grant outreach specialists</A>, supported by both NOAA and the USDA Cooperative Extension Service, initiated  the "Homescape for Water Quality" program. It is modeled after a program conducted by the Cooperative Extension Service in a Virginia county.
<P>
In the fall of 1994, a typical suburban development in western New York was targeted to participate in the first Homescape program. Homeowners from this development were teamed up with Master Gardener volunteers who had been recruited and trained by New York Sea Grant outreach specialists.  These volunteers worked closely with the homeowners, helping them to take and interpret soil tests to accurately predict fertilizer needs and to fill out pre-surveys of  past lawn and garden practices. In addition, the Master Gardeners recommended lawn and landscape care practices that were beneficial to the environment. 
<P>
Data collected from homeowner post-surveys indicate that important changes in lawn care behavior took  place. Use of slow-release fertilizers replaced those that allow nitrogen to run-off property in heavy rain, and the total amount of fertilizer applied was cut in half on some properties. People also found that environmentally-sound gardening techniques actually took less time than traditional approaches. Furthermore, one happy homeowner calculated he saved $250 using the new practices and his lawn has never looked better. 
<P>
Last fall, residents from another development in western New York signed up to participate in the Homescape program, and it is expanding to other regions of New York including Long Island and the Hudson River Valley. This spring, with the help of New York Sea Grant outreach specialists, these homeowners will be able to make decisions about lawn and landscape care that will save time, money, and the environment. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/713-2435)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

