<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 4(3)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
June 1996<BR>
Volume 4, Number 3
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Powerful Tool Aids Researchers and Resource Managers
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Marine Compounds Reap Big Profits
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Powerful Tool Aids Researchers and Resource Managers
</H2>
</CENTER>
A <A HREF="http://www.seagrant.wisc.edu/">Wisconsin Sea Grant</A> researcher and his students have provided scientists with a powerful tool, a computerized fish bioenergetics model. This model, which enables scientists to gather data about how fish collect and spend energy, is being used by researchers and fisheries managers throughout the nation and abroad as a research and management tool.
<P>
The original bioenergetics model was first successfully used to help sustain Lake Michigan¹s forage fish base, which supports a billion-dollar salmon and trout sport fishery. The model predicted that forage fish populations, particularly the alewife, would decline if fishery managers continued to increase salmonid stocking rates. The model¹s prediction proved correct when, four years later, Lake Michigan¹s once-abundant alewife population declined 86 percent. Forewarned, fishery managers reduced stocking pressures to avoid a complete collapse of the valuable fishery.  
<P>
As a result, the <A HREF="http://h2o.seagrant.wisc.edu/greatlakes/glnetwork/glnetwork.html">Great Lakes Sea Grant Network</A> and state and federal fisheries managers developed a coordinated two-year regional study of the diets of predator fish, providing the first simultaneously collected database for predator-prey systems in each of the Great Lakes. Since then, the state, federal, and provincial fishery agencies responsible for stocking policy in Lakes Michigan, Ontario, and Superior have employed bioenergetics models to help guide management policy. Today, the Wisconsin Sea Grant bioenergetics model forms the framework for Great Lakes stocking decisions.It also is heavily used by state and federal fisheries managers nationwide, from Lake Ontario to the Flaming Gorge Reservoir in Wyoming to the Northwest¹s Columbia River.
<P>
Wisconsin Sea Grant has helped sponsor more than two dozen workshops on the fish bioenergetics model and trained more than 350 scientists. In addition, Sea Grant has distributed nearly 1,000 copies of the model software and manual. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:bill.graham@noaa.gov">Bill Graham</A>, 301/713-2448)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Marine Compounds Reap Big Profits
</H2>
</CENTER>
Developed by <A HREF="http://www-csgc.ucsd.edu">California Sea Grant</A> researchers, a unique class of marine compounds generated $686,000 in royalties last year and over a million dollars to date, placing them among the university¹s top ten royalty-producing inventions. The compounds, a closely related group called pseudopterosins, are extracted from a creature called the Caribbean sea whip. They have been licensed to two companies for very different purposes.
<P>
For medical use as anti-inflammatory drugs, pseudopterosins have been licensed to a small pharmaceutical firm. The company has completed preclinical tests of one pseudopterosin, a potent topical anti-inflammatory compound, and filed an investigational new drug application with the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. It is expected that clinical trials on human subjects will focus on the drug¹s potential as therapy for irritant contact dermatitis.
<P>
For cosmetic application, use of the natural extract has been licensed to a speciality chemicals firm that supplies natural bulk ingredients to the cosmetics industry. At present, the natural extract is included in a boutique line of skin care products.
<P>
These represent the first of what will probably be a number of significant uses for derivatives of the pseudopterosins. Looking ahead to the next generation of pseudopterosin-derived drugs, the researchers will attempt to develop drugs for inflammatory diseases such as arthritis and asthma. 
<P>
For fiscal year 1994-1995, the University of California reported revenues of over $63 million in fees and royalties on over 400 inventions. Net income (income after expenses and distributions to joint holders, inventors, and the State of California) is available to support ongoing campus research and educational programs. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:dave.attaway@noaa.gov">David Attaway</A>, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

