<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 1(3)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
September 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 2
<P>
List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  New Uses for Fish Boost Economy</A><P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Research Assists Groundfish Plan Development
</A><P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]"> Find out more about Sea Grant</A><P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>New Uses for Fish Boost Economy</H2>
</CENTER>
Whiting, a fish found in abundance off Oregon's coast, was once shunned by commercial fishermen because its flesh deteriorated quickly after being caught, making it unprofitable for use by onshore processors. The fishing industry realized whiting's economic potential, however, after Sea Grant and other researchers showed U.S. processors how surimi products such as imitation crab and shrimp could be made from plentiful domestic species.
<P>
<A HREF="http://seagrant.orst.edu">Oregon Sea Grant</A> worked with industry to help develop new harvesting, onboard handling, and processing techniques to overcome the rapid breakdown of whiting flesh. As a result, whiling became a feasible seafood for use by onshore processors. In 1992, approximately 50,000 metric tons of whiting, more than double the previous year's production, were processed at Oregon shore-based plants. Estimates show a local economic impact of over $30 million.
<P>
With this increase in whiting processing came an increase in fish waste. To find a use for the leftover fish carcasses, Oregon Sea Grant contacted fertilizer, meal, and compost producers. One business, the family run Thorpe Valley Farms of Eugene, Oregon, expressed interest in using the fish waste for composting. With technical assistance from Sea Grant, Thorpe Valley was able to develop a nutrient-rich potting soil made from Ieftover Pacific whiting carcasses and sawdust mix. This year, the company made 10,000 cubic yards of compost by using about 2,500 tons of whiling waste. Gross sales for the firm should be about $750,000 in 1993 with hopes to double this sales figure next year. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:john.ahrens@noaa.gov">John Ahrens</A>, 301/7l3-2435)

<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research Assists Groundfish Plan Development
</H2>
</CENTER>
Responding to management and industry needs, <A HREF="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/s/seagrant/www/mitsg.htm">MIT Sea Grant</A>, in cooperation with the New England Fishery Management Council (NEFMC), took the lead on a preliminary assessment of the potential socioeconomic impacts of a proposed amendment to the New England Groundfish Multispecies Fishery Management Plan. Proposed Amendment S recommends rebuilding overfished stocks through a broad range of measures that include cutting in half the cod, haddock, and yellowtail flounder harvest rates. Such a reduction, even phased in gradually, will clearly have major impacts on fishermen and their communities.
<P>
Sea Grant researchers found that because of the extreme diversity in the New England groundfish industry, impacts of Amendment S are likely to vary across regions and communities, age and ethnic groups, and gear types and vessel sizes. The uncertainty about how each sector and each individual will be affected creates tension and anxiety among all involved in the fishing industry. Fishermen anticipate bankruptcy and the loss of their homes, which often provide collateral for their vessels.
<P>
Some ports with a disproportionate concentration of mid-sized vessels, in particular, face severe losses of individual ownership of vessels. Ports with mid-sized fleets may be at greater risk than ports characterized by fleets of larger vessels or smaller vessels that predominate in small, rural ports. In addition, the impacts could be deeper in communities where kinship is an important employment factor- where there is family involvement in all aspects of the industry from fishing to processing and marketing.
<P>
The findings of the technical report have been incorporated into the draft EIS by the NEFMC's plan development team, and the socioeconomic findings have been used to brief an interagency group convened to discuss potential effects and economic mitigation for the New England region. As a result of this initial MIT Sea Grant assessment pointing out the diverse distribution effects and the lack of information about them, NMFS is developing requirements for further social impact studies, with additional projects likely to be conducted by universities and colleges. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:shirley.fiske@noaa.gov">Shirley Fiske</A>, 301/713-2431)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

