<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Results 2(6)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantResults -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Results</H1>
<H2><I>Making A Difference</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
November 1994<BR>
Volume 2, Number 6
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<A HREF="#1"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT=[*]">  Plants Protect Threatened Shorelines </A>
<P>
<A HREF="#2"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Filtering Systems Used Nationwide </A>
<P>
<A HREF="#MORE"><IMG SRC="../../GIFs/bluecube.gif" ALT="[*]">  Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Plants Protect Threatened Shorelines
</H2>
</CENTER>
From New Jersey to Texas, in Mexico and throughout the Caribbean, plants from Horticultural Systems, Inc. (HSI) are helping restore damaged coastal ecosystems and protecting fragile beach environments from natural and human threats. The company's many clients include government agencies at the federal, state and local levels, and private firms involved in coastal engineering.
<P>
Much of HSl's success can be attributed to <A HREF="http://gnv.ifas.ufl.edu/~seaweb/homepage/fsg.htm">Florida Sea Grant</A>. By providing research and the support and advice of outreach specialists, Sea Grant has enabled the company to grow from a backyard, two-person hobby into a 15-acre nursery with 50 full-time employees who produce four million plants each year.
<P>
Of particular importance to HSI was Sea Grant research exploring the use of micropropagation techniques to create "offspring" from a superior plant in the laboratory. This enabled growers to "custom design" vegetation that survives better than similar plants growing in the wild, which is a valuable attribute for the harsh growing conditions found in coastal and beach environments.
<P>
Also of vital importance to HSI was Sea Grant research showing that sea oat seedlings inoculated with a fungi had a greater survival rate when transplanted at the beach than did untreated seedlings. In addition, the root systems of the treated oats were better able to hold sand in place.
<P>
In return for Sea Grant's support, HSI has served as a valuable test ground and experiment station for Sea Grant researchers who are working to protect America's increasingly threatened shorelines. Together HSI and Sea Grant have shown what can be accomplished through a partnership approach among industry, universities, governments, and people. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:jjim.mcvey@noaa.gov">James McVey</A>, 301/713-2451)
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="2"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Filtering Systems Used Nationwide
</CENTER>
</H2>
Unlike life-supporting water in the natural environment, water used in aquaculture systems requires intense and special treatment. The high density of animals and the feeding levels used in commercial aquaculture systems require efficient nitrification ability, maintenance or adequate dissolved oxygen and acid Levels, and solids removal.
<P>
Using a new approach, Louisiana Sea Grant researchers have developed and patented bead filters for use in aquaculture systems. These new filters accomplish both nitrification and solids removal in a single, efficient unit that requires far less space than alternative filters.
<P>
The filtering systems have proved reliable, are easily maintained and well-adapted to automation-qualities believed by many in the aquaculture industry to be the key to success in large-scale recirculating aquaculture technology. The advantages of this new approach include excellent water conservation, reduced environmental impacts from wastewater discharge, and better control Or the animals' feeding, health and habitat requirements.
<P>
These versatile units are being manufactured by companies in Louisiana and Texas and are available in various sizes. They not only have improved The efficiency of aquaculture enterprises nationwide but also have provided the technology needed to produce a wider variety of species in high density systems.
<P>
For example, a tropical fish producer with facilities in California, Florida and Pennsylvania purchased 10 of the large bead filters for his systems. Louisiana's first tilapia producer operates a multiple 40,000-gallon lank system with eight of The bead filters. A bead filter was installed to cleanse crawfish for market by a Louisiana firm. Two ornamental fish retailers in Baton Rouge purchased several hundred bead filters for in-store use. The bead filters are also being used by a Louisiana alligator producer; university researchers in Florida, Georgia, Hawaii, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, and Texas to culture shrimp, hybrid striped bass, rangia clams, red drum, catfish, and lobsters; a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service fish hatchery in Montana; and a Florida firm for a fish exhibit prepared for the Walt Disney Epcot Center. (For details, <A HREF="mailto:leon.cammen@noaa.gov">Leon Cammen</A>, 301/713-2435) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

