<HEAD>
<TITLE>National Sea Grant Office: Sea Grant Challenges 1(2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="GIFs/background.gif">
<A NAME="TOP"></A>
<!-- Masthead for SeaGrantFuture -->

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/NSGO/GIFs/NSGOlogo.gif"ALT="[NSGO  logo]">
<H1>Sea Grant Challenges</H1>
<H2><I>Looking To The Future</I></H2>
</H2>
</CENTER>


<H3>
October 1993<BR>
Volume 1, Number 2
<P>

List of Contents:<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT=[*]">  <A HREF="#1">Research On Toxic Pollutants</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/cyanball.gif" ALT="[*]">  <A HREF="#MORE">Find out more about Sea Grant</A>
<P>
</H3>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<CENTER>
<H2>Research On Toxic Pollutants</H2>
</CENTER>

Public concern regarding toxic pollutants in the environment has been heightened by the many well- documented cases of serious impacts on human health from both manufacturing and construction industry pollutants. Similarly, many cases have been reported of the acute effects that oil and pesticide spills have on aquatic life and ecosystems. 
<P>
However, it is difficult to learn how long-term exposures to low levels of toxic pollutants affect marine ecosystem functions and populations. Therefore, a major area of Sea Grant research on toxic pollutants focuses on their transport, transformations, and fates in the marine and Great Lakes environments. These processes control an organism's level and duration of toxic exposure. 
<P>
Researchers are particularly interested in the release of toxic metals from contaminated sediments and the metals' subsequent uptake by marine organisms. Many Sea Grant field and laboratory studies are identifying the environmental conditions that control the release of metals. Metal speciation measurements, using new electrochemical analytical technology, are permitting researchers to accurately measure the biologically active forms in sediments, waters and marine organisms, and to determine true rates of uptake. 
<P>
Sea Grant research into the environmental behavior of toxic organic compounds has shifted from studies which identify and quantify sources. Projects now focus on understanding the processes controlling the transport and fate of these compounds. For example, concentrations of many toxic organic compounds such as PCBs and DDT accumulate in plankton and are biomagnified as they pass up the food chain. Understanding and quantifying the routes taken by these compounds in complex food webs is critical to developing models for predicting toxicant behavior in the environment. 
<P>
The behavior of toxics when they interact with colloids is also being explored by Sea Grant researchers. Colloids are particles existing naturally in lake and ocean waters, but they are too small to be seen with a light microscope. Recently, technology was developed to separate colloids from truly dissolved material and larger particles. This ability to measure colloids has expanded research on their interaction with pollutants. The high surface area per unit volume of colloids enables them to readily adsorb many pollutants. Understanding this interaction will lead to better models of the transport of pollutants in coastal and Great Lake waters. 
<P>
Another major area of Sea Grant research concerns the effects that toxic pollutants have on aquatic ecosystems and their plant and animal components. At the cellular level, research is directed toward developing indicators of exposure, stress, and genetic damage. At the organism level, research is focused on how toxic pollutants affect the reproduction and growth processes critical to determining populations. For example, research by Wisconsin Sea Grant has shown that even very low levels of PCBs and dioxins, while not lethal to adult lake and rainbow trout, can cause significant mortality to eggs and fry. These results are important to understanding the reproductive failure of stocked lake trout in the Great Lakes. 
<P>
In regional, multi-agency approaches to solving environmental problems, Sea Grant scientists are investigating how toxic pollutants affect estuaries. A team of Texas Sea Grant scientists is participating in the Environmental Protection Agency's Galveston Bay Program. Their research will help to identify and better understand the sources and transformations of toxic metals in the bay. 
<P>
Supported by both NOAA and EPA, Maryland and Virginia Sea Grant scientists are participating in the comprehensive Chesapeake Bay Toxics Research Program. The program is focused on the transport and fate of toxic substances and on how these substances affect both ecological processes and bay organisms. 
<P>
Learning the real effects of low-level toxic pollutants on aquatic ecosystems and their inhabitants is an especially difficult research challenge. The answers will not come quickly and will require the attention of the best researchers in the field. Addressing this challenge, in cooperation with other NOAA elements and federal agencies, is a major Sea Grant undertaking. (For details: William Graham, 301/713-2435 or <A HREF="mailto:bgraham@rdc.noaa.gov">bgraham@rdc.noaa.gov</A>) 
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="#TOP">top</A> of the document.

