<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/blueball.gif" ALT="[*]">  
<A HREF="#R/ODR-06">Molecular detectors for Dermo disease</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="../../GIFs/blueball.gif" ALT="[*]">  
<A HREF="#R/ODR-07">Seeking the cellular basis of oyster vulnerability to disease</A><BR>

</TR></TABLE>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]"><P>
<A NAME="R/ODR-01"></A>
<H2>Continued Studies of Juvenile Oyster Disease (JOD) in the Northeastern United States (R/ODR-01)</H2>
Many oyster aquaculture operations in the northeastern United States, from Maine to Long Island Sound, saw production plummet 50 to 90 percent, beginning in 1990 because of juvenile oyster disease (JOD). Researchers are continuing work with a grower in Long Island Sound to breed JOD-resistant oysters; evaluations of oysters bred in 1994 showed mortalities in selectively-spawned strains were greatly reduced; at present they are testing the susceptibility of two other oyster species to JOD. 
<P>
Stephen Jordan, C. Austin Farley and Earl J. Lewis, Jr.<BR>
NOAA, Cooperative Oxford Laboratory<BR>
Maryland Department of Natural Resources
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-04"></A>
<H2>Continued Studies on the Identity of Juvenile Oyster Disease (JOD) Causative Organism in Northeastern United States Oysters (R/ODR-04)</H2>
In trying to determine the identity of the juvenile oyster disease (JOD), researchers have largely eliminated a dinoflagellate or a bacterium as the primary disease agent. Suspecting the infective organism to be a ciliated protist, which is known to parasitize oysters and other invertebrates by first invading the mantle epithelium, Eugene Small is working to culture and identify the protist, and to test its infectivity in oysters. 
<P>
Eugene B. Small<BR>
Department of Zoology<BR>
University of Maryland, College Park
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-02"></A>
<H2>Production of disease-free oysters for use in oyster recovery area research (R/ODR-02)</H2>
A key feature of the Maryland Oyster Roundtable Action to restore oyster stocks to the Chesapeake Bay is the setting aside of oyster recovery areas, low salinity regions for planting disease-free oysters -- one way to provide such oysters is to rear them in hatcheries under controlled conditions. This project represents a first step in determining whether disease-free seed can survive and grow in natural habitats; the researchers will produce sufficient numbers of young oysters for planting on 3 to 5 acres annually, will monitor the survival, growth, disease onset and mortality over a three-year period, and then quantify changes in the bottom communities associated with oyster reefs. 
<P>
Donald Meritt<BR>
CEES Horn Point Environmental Laboratory<BR>
University of Maryland System
<P>
Kennedy T. Paynter, Jr.<BR>
Department of Zoology<BR>
University of Maryland, College Park
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-08"></A>
<H2>Cooperative Regional Oyster Selective Breeding (CROSBreed) Project (R/ODR-08)</H2>
For nearly 25 years, scientists at Rutgers have been breeding oyster survivors of MSX attacks to produce lines with high resistance to MSX.  Unfortunately MSX-resistant oysters have not proven resistant to Dermo.  In an ambitious project, scientists in the mid-Atlantic have embarked on a regional program to breed MSX-resistant oysters for resistance to Dermo as well. These oysters will be spawned at the Haskin Research Lab at Rutgers and grown out in three different sites in Delaware and Chesapeake bays.  The goal is to demonstrate the utility of such resistant lines across different environments and, ultimately, to make these strains of oysters available for aquaculture and repletion programs.
<P>
Standish K. Allen, Jr., Ximing Guo, Susan E. Ford  and Greg DeBrosse<BR>
Haskin Shellfish Research Laboratory<BR>
Rutgers University
<P>
Patrick M. Gaffney<BR>
College of Marine Studies<BR>
University of Delaware
<P>
Mark Luckenbach and Eugene Burreson<BR>
Virginia Institute of Marine Science
<P>
Donald Meritt<BR>
CEES Horn Point Environmental Laboratory<BR>
University of Maryland System
<P>
Kennedy T. Paynter, Jr.<BR>
Department of Zoology<BR>
University of Maryland, College Park
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-05"></A>
<H2>Crassostrea viginica Pathogens in Chesapeake Bay Oyster Populations: A Dual Disease Simulation  Model of Parasite-Host Interactions over a Large Spatial Scale (R/ODR-05)</H2>
A rational basis for assessing strategies to manage seed areas or brood stocks will need to predict the potential consequences of alternative restoration strategies. This project will model  oyster populations subject to the influences of the environment (e.g., water temperature, salinity, circulation) and two lethal parasites, Dermo and MSX. In the long run, managers and scientists will be able to apply this model to address "what-if" questions that could better steer management towards the most promising tactics for restoration.
<P>
Stephen Jordan<BR>
NOAA Cooperative Oxford Laboratory<BR>
Maryland Department of Natural Resources
<P>
Eileen Hofmann and John Klinck<BR>
Old Dominion University<BR>
Center for Coastal Physical Oceanography
<P>
Eric N. Powell<BR>
Haskin Shellfish Research Laboratory<BR>
Rutgers University
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-03"></A>
<H2>Evaluation of American Oyster Stocks for Resource Rehabilitation: Disease Resistance and Genetics (R/ODR-03)</H2>
MSX and Dermo appear less virulent in regions outside the Chesapeake Bay, which suggests that oysters from those areas may possess traits which enable them to better survive infection. Do these traits have a genetic basis? The researchers will collect oysters from regions throughout the Atlantic range of the eastern oyster to evaluate their genetic relatedness. Offspring of these broodstocks will be deployed in representative sites in Maryland and Virginia. Survival, growth and condition of offspring will be monitored throughout the project. Promising genotypes will be selected and maintained for future selective breeding of disease-resistant strains. 
<P>
Kennedy T. Paynter, Jr.<BR>
Department of Zoology, UMCP
<P>
Donald Meritt<BR>
CEES Horn Point Environmental Laboratory<BR>
University of Maryland System
<P>
Patrick Gaffney<BR>
College of Marine Studies<BR>
University of Delaware
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-06"></A>
<H2>Assessing the Presence and Virulence of "Dermo" Disease in the Environment Using a PCR-Based Diagnostic Assay for the Extrachromosomal Plastid Genome of Perkinsus marinus (R/ODR-06)</H2>
One vital need to protect against transferring infected oysters into uninfected areas is the ability to detect the presence of disease in broodstock, spat and adult oysters, even at very low levels, as well as in the environment into which oysters might be planted.  Research by Vasta and Marsh is continuing the development of molecular probes for Perkinsus marinus. Specifically, polymerase chain reaction (PCR) of a unique DNA molecule found only in Perkinsus is used as the basis of a test which can detect the parasite at levels several orders of magnitude below that of current techniques.  
<P>
Gerardo Vasta and Adam G. Marsh<BR>
Center of Marine Biotechnology<BR>
University of Maryland Biotechnology Institute
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../GIFs/MDSG_bar.gif" ALT="[MDSG bar]">
<A NAME="R/ODR-07"></A>
<H2>The Molecular Basis for the Etiology of the Oyster "Dermo" Disease: Gene Regulation Events Susceptible to Chemical Inhibition (R/ODR-07)</H2>
How is Perkinsus marinus able to invade its oyster host, evade detection and thus subsequent attack by cellular defense mechanisms, and why is Crassostrea virginica more susceptible to Dermo than closely related species? Answers to such questions may make it possible to inhibit infection, bolster host immunity or identify genes which confer improved resistance to the parasite. Researchers in this project are working to identify nutritional and other factors in the oyster¹s cells and tissues which regulate the ability of P. marinus to reproduce within its host and to determine the adaptations which allow the parasite to evade destruction by the oyster¹s hemocytes. The ultimate goal is to develop chemical strategies to block the ability of the parasite to detect, enter or proliferate within the body of the oyster. The activity of the parasite in the eastern oyster will also be compared with that in the more resistant Pacific oyster.
<P>
Gerardo Vasta and Adam G. Marsh<BR>
Center of Marine Biotechnology<BR>
University of Maryland Biotechnology Institute
<P>
Select <A HREF="#TOP">return</A> to go back to the beginning of the document.
<P>
<ADDRESS>Last modified 1 October 1996</ADDRESS>
<P>

