<HEAD>

<TITLE>Virginia Mason - Volunteer</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#0000ff">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1"VALIGN="TOP">
<IMG SRC="logo2.gif"><IMG SRC="logoc.gif">

                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1"  ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="497" VALIGN="TOP">
<font size=5 color="#2222c2">The beauty of volunteering isn't only what it gives to others, but what it brings to you.</font>
<p>
<IMG align=right SRC="vol.jpg" border=2>
All of us can think of someone who helped or encouraged us along the way with a simple act of kindness, never to be forgotten.
<p>
Have you ever stopped to think, you weren't the only one who benefited?  The person who gave so willingly also received a very special reward.  It was your gratitude, and often that is enough.  For that is the essence of volunteering.
<p>
<font size=5 color="#2222c2">What you gain is immeasurable.</font>
<p>
Few people ever get the chance to be a Rhodes scholar, perform at Carnegie Hall or play in the World Series. But for a few hours a week, you can be part of a world class team -- regardless of your age or education.
<p>
Virginia Mason has earned a national and international reputation for advances in medical treatment and research. Virginia Mason scientists were the first to discover the primary genetic marker for diabetes. With over 400 physicians and providers, a hospital, research center and regional clinics, Virginia Mason is the most comprehensive, unified medical facility in the Northwest.
<p>
Throughout its 75 year history, volunteers have been an important part of Virginia Mason. They come for many reasons, from all walks of life, but they all have something in common. By helping others, they gain something in return.
<p>
As a volunteer at Virginia Mason you can learn while you serve, with a chance to expand your horizons and grow as a person, while working with some of the best and brightest medical professionals in the country.
<p>
But most of all, you'll have the opportunity to make a difference. To reach out and touch the lives of others. To find beauty in acts of kindness.
<p>
<font size=5 color="#2222c2">Never stop learning - volunteer.</font>
<p>
It is often said that helping others is its own reward. While that is true, there are also many additional benefits and opportunities for volunteers of all ages. Here are just a few:
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Make new friends and participate in educational and  social activities throughout the year.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Work alongside healthcare professionals as important  members of the Virginia Mason team.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Gain a greater perspective on life and enhance your  sense of well-being.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Earn service credits for school, build a resume, and  get a head start on your future.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Learn about different healthcare positions and  employment opportunities.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Develop new skills, broaden your talents and gain  real-life experience.
<p>
<IMG SRC="drop.gif" border=0>Make the most of your time by giving something back  to the community.
<p>
<font size=5 color="#2222c2">Put your talents to work in areas that interest you.</font>
<p>
Each volunteer receives a general hospital orientation and at least 15 hours of supervised training. After receiving training most volunteers make a six month commitment of at least four hours one day a week, with flexible schedules tailored to your availability.
<p>
We try to place volunteers in areas consistent with their skills and interests. There are many opportunities to choose from, including:
<p>
<b>Patient services</b> -- enhancing patient stays on the nursing units by delivering mail or flowers, reading or writing letters, running errands or fluffing a pillow. Whatever it takes to bring a smile to someone's face and brighten their day.
<p>
<b>Clerical services</b> -- putting your office and organizational skills to work in the administrative and clinical offices. Opportunities may include use of business machines and computers, calling patients with appointment reminders, mailing announcements, entering data and other clerical tasks.
<p>
<b>Family and guest services</b> -- working with the public at the Information Desk or as a Concierge, providing comfort, support and information to patients and guests.
<p>
<b>Satellite services</b> -- assisting in clinics throughout the region and providing support for a variety of departments. Opportunities include physical therapy departments, information desks and clerical work in other specific areas.
<p>
<b>Special projects</b> -- helping with fund raisers, running errands, delivering gifts and supplies to departments, shopping for patients or escorting them to the bank or local shops. Utilize your creative skills to help others in imaginative ways.
<p>
<font size=5 color="#2222c2">Heres how to get started.</font>
<p>
To become a Virginia Mason volunteer, simply complete this form to request an application packet. Or call (206) 583-6507 for more information.
</TD>
        </TR>
 <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
         </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2"  ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="490">
<hr>
		</TD>
        </TR>
</TABLE>

