<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<table cellspacing="2" cellpadding="2" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center"><img align="center" src="chap.jpg"></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><img align=bottom src="clined.jpg"></center><br>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<center><table width=85%>
<tr><td><font size=2>

Clinical Pastoral Education (CPE) allows theological students, parish clergy, and lay people to enhance their pastoral care skills through real life experience.  CPE is based on an action/reflection model of learning.  Chaplain interns provide pastoral care, evaluate their experience with their colleagues and supervisor, and integrate their insights and learning into the next ministry experience.  <br><br>
<br>
Those in the program establish learning goals around personal and professional growth.  The curriculum integrates personal and professional experience/history, psychology, sociology, theology, and spiritual development.</font></td></tr></table></center>
<br>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<br>
<center><h2><i>CPE at Virginia Mason Medical Center</h2></i></center>

<center><table width=85%>
<tr><td><font size=2>
Virginia Mason Medical Center is a regional referral and primary care center for the Pacific Northwest.  The medical center includes Virginia Mason Hospital, Virginia Mason Clinic, 22 Neighborhood Clinics, and the Virginia Mason Research Center.
<br><br>
The hospital serves as the primary clinical site for students, and has approximately 300 acute care beds.  Interns may also have opportunity to work with out-patients through the clinic and AIDS patients through the Bailey Boushay House, a 35 bed facility for those living with AIDS. 
<br>
Chaplain interns work as a part of the health care team to provide pastoral care to patients, their families, and to staff.  Those involved in the CPE program may expect:
<br></font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><table width=75%>
      <tr><td width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><font size=2><i>Daily                                 pastoral visits with patients and family members.</i></font></td></tr>
      <tr><td><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2><i>Night and weekend on-call                                 responsibility for the medical center.</i></font></td></tr>
      <tr><td><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2><i> Involvement with a                                 multidisciplinary health care team.</i></font></td></tr>
      <tr><td><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2><i>Opportunity for personal and                                 ministerial reflection and evaluation.</i></font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<center><h2><i>The objective of Clinical Pastoral Education</i></h2></center>

<center><table width=85%>
    <tr><td><font size=2>
CPE includes the goals of Pastoral Reflection, Pastoral Formation, and Pastoral Competence.  In addition Pastoral Specialization and Consultation may be offered when appropriate.  Each intern is expected to make use of the action/reflection model to identify ministry skills that enhance Reflection, Formation, and Competence in the care for and ministry with others.
</font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><h2><i>Components of the Program</i></h2></center>

<center><table width=85%>
    <tr><td colspan=2><font size=2><b><i>Feedback and evaluation are provided through various group and individual sessions:</i></b></font></td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Didactic Seminars  --  <i>Presentations from health care professionals and ministry specialists regarding different aspects of ministry and pastoral care.</i></font></td></tr>
 
<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Theological Reflection Seminars  -- <i>Presentations made by chaplain interns regarding how ones theology and spiritual awareness is shaped by the ministry provided in this setting.</i></font></td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Case Presentations  --  <i>Review of verbatims of pastoral visits shared in the peer group and with CPE supervisor for feedback.</i></font></td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Worship Seminars  --<i>  Opportunity to conduct weekly chapel service and devotions with other colleagues.</i></font></td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Group Process  -- <i> Sessions providing an environment where relationships between colleagues and supervisor can be worked out and shared in a safe and supportive fashion.</i></font></td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Nursing unit rounds  -- <i> Participation as a member of the team with a multidisciplinary group, i.e. nursing, medicine, social services, ancillary services, etc., to evaluate and create treatment plan for patients.</i></font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>

<center><h2><i>Programs Available</i></h2></center>

<center><table width=85%>
<tr><td><font size=3><font size=2><b><i>Virginia Mason offers CPE in two formats: </b></i></font></td></tr>

<tr><td><font size=2><b>1.)</b>  Full-time, 40 hours per week for 11 weeks with additional on-call responsibility.  This unit begins approximately every 12 weeks, for a total of 400 hours of supervision.</font></td></tr>

<tr><td><font size=2> <b> 2.)</b>  Extended or Part-time CPE, two full days per week for 25 weeks.  This unit usually is offered from September through March each year, for a total of 400 hours of supervision.</font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>


<center><h2><i>Accreditation</i></h2></center>
<center><table width=85%>
<tr><td><font size=2>Virginia Mason Medical Center is accredited by the Association for Clinical Pastoral Education, Inc. (ACPE) to offer programs of Clinical Pastoral Education.</font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<center><h2><i>Chapliancy Staff</i></h2></center>

<center><table width=85%>
<tr><td><font size=2>Rev. David Wendleton is the ACPE certified supervisor and directs the program.  He has served as the chaplain at Virginia Mason since 1984.  He is an active member of the Pacific Region ACPE, having served as chair of the Research and Accreditation Committees.  He is an ordained United Methodist minister and member of the Pacific Northwest Conference of the United Methodist Church.</font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>

<center><h2><i>To Apply:</i></h2></center>
<center><table width=75%>
<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Complete an ACPE application</font></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Send screening interview from ACPE supervisor</font></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top><img src="blueball.gif"></td><td><font size=2>Arrange a personal interview at Virginia Mason</font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><table>
<tr><td align=center><font size =2><b>For more information please contact:</b><br><br>

Chaplain David H. Wendleton<br>
Chaplaincy Services -- H5-CHP<br>
Virginia Mason Medical Center <br>
925 Seneca<br>
Seattle, WA  98111<br>
(206) 624-1144<br>
<a href="mailto:chpdhw@vmmc.org">chpdhw@vmmc.org</a>
</font></td></tr></table></center>
