<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Message from the Department Chief
Virginia Mason Medical Center</TITLE></HEAD>
<! Updated by Kent Hargrave, Virginia Mason Medical Center, Anesthesia Program>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><font size="6">Department of Anesthesiology</font><br>
<hr>

<Table>
<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>


<br>
<center>
<img src="welcome.jpg">
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>

	<b>Welcome to the Department of Anesthesiology at Virginia Mason Medical Center in Seattle, Washington.</b>  We are a unique department which offers a distinctly different training opportunity (from the large university model) for medical graduates (and fellows) pursuing a career in the specialty of Anesthesiology.  We are known nationally and internationally for our practice and expertise in regional anesthesia.  Sixty-five percent of our cases involve a regional anesthetic as a component or as the sole source of anesthesia.  This tradition prepares our graduates to offer unique skills and expertise in regional anesthesia and post-operative pain management.  This coupled with the growing awareness, interest and outcome data demonstrating regional anesthesia and post-operative analgesia's contribution to lower morbidity and mortality rates, reduced length-of-stay and hospital costs has resulted in a high demand and competitive edge for our residents and fellowship-trained graduates in pursuing other opportunities (both private and academic) as they leave Virginia Mason.  
<p>
	At Virginia Mason, we are committed to the training of consultants and leaders in the field of Anesthesiology.  Thus, Virginia Mason training promotes the following skills in our graduates:  expertise, creativity, individualization in analysis and management of complex and changing situations (adaptability), teamwork, as well as clarity of expression.
<p>
	Other characteristics of our department which recommend it for your careful consideration include:
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li> a nationally recognized core faculty with diverse interest and expertise that supplement the expertise in regional anesthesia and round out the training so that it is complete in all aspects of anesthesiology

<li> a small class and faculty size that permits close supervision and guidance as the resident progresses through his/her training

<li> a value-driven department that strives to teach cost-effective care, as well as practice management in a real-world setting

<li> a history of securing outstanding residents (e.g. in 1995 we filled our residency program through the NIRMP match--one of only 19 out of 139 programs to do so)

<li> a track record of outstanding performance on the written and oral board exams

<li> a long-standing high rating from the Residency Review Committee for Anesthesiology

<li> opportunity to participate in relevant clinical research

<li> a close and friendly relationship with the University of Washington's Department of Anesthesiology (though, we are free-standing)

<li> located in a highly desirable city---Seattle
</ul>

<h4>We appreciate your interest and look forward to the chance to discuss this training opportunity with you.</h4>
<blockquote>
<p>
Sincerely, 
<p>
Stephen M. Rupp, M.D.<br>
Chief, Department of Anesthesiology<br>
<p>
phone: (206) 223-6859<br>
fax: (206) 223-6982<br>
E-mail:  <a href="mailto:anesmr@vmmc.org">anesmr@vmmc.org</a>
</blockquote>

<center>
<h4><a href="index.htm">Return to the VMMC Department of Anesthesiology Home Page</a></h4>
</center>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

