<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMMC Anesthesia Residency Program</TITLE></HEAD>
<! Updated by Kent Hargrave, Virginia Mason Medical Center, Anesthesia Program>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><font size="6">Department of Anesthesiology</font><br>
<hr>

<Table>
<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>

<center>
<br><img src="residen3.jpg" alt="VMMC Anesthesia Residency">
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
The Virginia Mason Medical Center offers a complete Anesthesia Residency Program approved by a commission of the American Board of Anesthesiology (ABA) and the Council on Medical Education of the American Medical Association.  The Medical Center has a 233 bed hospital with 11,902 admissions annually and 17,292 emergency room visits.  There are also residencies in Internal Medicine, Surgery, and Radiology.
</blockquote>
<h4>Clinical Base Year</h4>
<blockquote>
The base clinical year requirement of the ABA can be fulfilled by either the "Complete Anesthesiology" First Postgraduate Year or a "Transitional" year at the Virginia Mason Hospital.  The positions designated as "Complete Anesthesiology," along with the transitional positions, are filled through the National Resident Matching Program.  Students may also match at the CA1 (R-2) level through the <a href="mrnp96.htm">NRMP</a> (known as the "Advanced Anesthesia" Program).  We currently fill four positions as "Complete Anesthesia" and two others from the "Advanced Anesthesia" match, for a total of six residents per year.  All six positions were filled in 1995and 1996.
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>For further information on <a href="trans8.htm">VMMC Transitional Program</a>
</ul>

<h4>Clinical Anesthesia Training</h4>
<blockquote>

The Clinical Anesthesia Training Program consists of three years (CA-1, 2, and 3) after the base year.  Although Virginia Mason is well-known for its regional anesthesia emphasis, all of the subspecialty tracks are well represented in the CA1 and 2 years, including obstetrics, neuroanesthesia, cardiothoracic anesthesia, recovery room management, and outpatient anesthesia.  Training includes a 3-month pediatric anesthesia rotation at Children's Hospital, a month on a diagnostic/therapeutic pain-block service, and a two-month rotation in Critical Care at the Harborview (County) Medical Center.  All residents case experiences exceed the minimum requirements in all areas specified in the recently revised standards of the Anesthesiology Residency Review Commission.
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>See <a href="caseloa1.htm">table of case loads</a>
<li>See <a href="caseloa2.htm">Graph of case loads</a>
</ul>
<blockquote>
Advanced anesthesia training (CA-3) is available in all the tracks required by the ABA:
</blockquote>
<ol><ol>  
	 <li>Advanced Clinical,  
	 <li>Subspecialty Clinical,  
	 <li>Clinical Scientist.
</ol></ol>
<blockquote>
The only requirement at the CA-3 level is a 2 month rotation at Harborview Medical Center, the regional Trauma and Burn Center.  Otherwise, the CA-3 rotations are flexible.  Most residents choose the Advanced Clinical Tract, which emphasizes advanced challenge and responsibility including management of major vascular and other complex cases.
</blockquote>
<h4>Fellowships</h4>

Advanced Fellowship training is available in 
<ul>
<li> <a href="region5.htm">Regional Anesthesia</a>,
<li> <a href="pain4.htm">Pain Management</a>, and
<li> <a href="cardanes.htm">Cardiac Anesthesia</a>
</ul>
See additional pages for further information in these specialty areas.

<h4>Training Experience</h4>
<blockquote>
All residents participate equally in the operative caseload by rotating through all operating rooms.  Training of residents is based on exposure to a large, balanced volume of surgical cases averaging 450 per resident annually.  Regional anesthesia is a part of the anesthetic plan in over 60% of these procedures, which makes the Virginia Mason anesthesia experience unique.  Virginia Mason is a well established HMO organization, as well as a referral center for the Northwest and is currently expanding its patient base by affiliation with the local Group Health Cooperative.  As a result, residents see a large variety of routine surgical cases as well as complicated neurological, cardiac, vascular, orthopedic and other procedures.  A first call resident stays in the hospital each night and is usually relieved for a "library day" the next morning, normally providing two or three study days monthly.
<p>
Practical experience is enhanced by a structured didactic program which includes weekly basic science lectures, "critical incident" conferences, and a general medical conference.  There is an active monthly Journal Club and regularly scheduled visiting professors.  Attendance is encouraged at the quarterly Washington State Society of Anesthesiologists meetings as well as the ASA Annual Meeting.  All residents are required to take the ABA in-service training exam each July and are expected to achieve certification by the American Board of Anesthesiology at the completion of their clinical training.  For the thirteen classes 1982 -95, the average score of the graduating class was in the 95th percentile on the written exam.
</blockquote>
<h4>Faculty</h4>
<blockquote>
The keystone of resident education is daily contact with one of the staff anesthesiologists in the operating room.  The eighteen operating locations are covered by seventeen staff.  Each staff covers no more than two residents, and coverage is one-on-one during the first month of residency.  The staff provide a varied background with extensive involvement in research and national society activity.  Three of the staff are junior associates.  The 12 senior staff all trained elsewhere, and average ten years of participation in the training program.
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>See<a href="faculty6.htm"> Faculty description</a>
</ul>
<h4>Research Activity</h4>
<blockquote>
Though the department's primary interest lies in comprehensive clinical training of residents, there are ongoing clinical research projects and resident involvement is encouraged.  The Department has a Research Nurse to assist with these projects.  For each of the last ten years, a Virginia Mason resident has presented an abstract at the annual ASA meeting.  Residents and Fellows have participated in multiple publications in the last several years.
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li><a href="pub14.htm">Resident/Fellow Publications</a>
</ul>
<h4>Application Procedure</h4>
<ul>
<li>Click <a href="res-app.htm">here</a> to print an application from Netscape 1.1+ for the residency training programs. 
<li>Click <a href="res-app.doc">here</a> to download a Microsoft Word 6.0 version.
</ul>
<blockquote>
For a detailed brochure describing housestaff benefits and other VMMC training programs, send your address to House Staff Affairs Office, <a href="mailto:resmlb@vmmc.org">resmlb@vmmc.org</a>.  A Washington State medical license is required for all physicians performing direct patient care.  Please return the completed application to Ms. Maureen Beaulieu in the Office of Housestaff Affairs.  Interviews for applicants will be scheduled in November, December, January, and February after completion of the application.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<center>
<b>If you have further questions, please do not hesitate to contact me at<br> (206) 583-6079, or <a href="mailto:anemfm@vmmc.org">anemfm@vmmc.org</a>.<b></center>
<p>
Michael F. Mulroy, M.D.<br>
Teaching Coordinator
<br><br>
<center>
<a href="index.htm">Return to the VMMC Department of Anesthesiology Home Page</a>
</center>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br><br>

