<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Fellowship Opportunities in Pain Management</TITLE></HEAD>
<! Updated by Kent Hargrave, Virginia Mason Medical Center, Anesthesia Program>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><font size="6">Department of Anesthesiology</font><br>
<hr>

<Table>
<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>



<br>
<center>
<img src="pain.jpg" alt="FELLOWSHIP OPPORTUNITIES IN PAIN MANAGEMENT">

</center>
<br>
<br>
<ul>

<li>Thank you for inquiring about the Pain Management Fellowship at Virginia Mason Medical Center.  We offer a 12 month experience in pain management which is organized through the department of anesthesia, and certified by the American Board of Anesthesiology.  One or two pain fellows are selected each year, depending upon the demand within our CA-3 class for a subspecialty pain tract.  We have two openings for the positions starting in July of 1997.  We are committed to providing a top quality experience for the fellow, with a balanced exposure to acute and postoperative pain management, chronic benign pain management, and cancer pain management.   Each fellowship is further taylored with outside rotations, OR experience and clinical pain research to meet individual objectives.

<h3>Acute and Postoperative Pain Management</h3>
<li>Virginia Mason is a tertiary referral center for the Pacific Northwest.  Anesthetics are administered for many complicated surgical cases, and regional anesthetic techniques are utilized in the majority of these cases.  As a result, we have a busy postoperative pain service.  Opportunity for research in the area of perioperative pain management is vast, and the fellows are encouraged to participate.
<li>Virginia Mason is not a major trauma center, so the proportion of accident victims is very low.  The acute pain service does not provide routine intravenous PCA management.  We have a highly regarded anesthesiology training program, with twenty residents.  In addition, we have an average of five CA-4 fellows obtaining additional training in regional anesthesia.  Overall, this makes for a congenial, and stimulating academic environment.
<h3>Chronic Benign Pain Management</h3>
<li>Chronic benign pain is optimally managed via a multidisciplinary approach.  The Anesthesiology Pain Service at VMMC sees a large number of these patients referred for diagnostic or therapeutic nerve blocks.  The vast array of psychological, social, and occupational issues that these patients present with dictates a level of staffing and commitment which is beyond the scope of the Anesthesiology Pain Service alone.  However, within our multispecialty clinic, we have a highly developed and very busy group of physicians who see these patients on a daily basis.  Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation operates both inpatient and outpatient facilities for pain management at Virginia Mason.  The Anesthesiology Pain Service works in conjunction with physical medicine and rehabilitation, when appropriate, in the management of chronic benign pain.  Most importantly, the Anesthesiology Pain Management Fellow rotates for a month with this group, learning the practice and business of chronic pain management from a perspective not typically available in anesthesiology training programs.
<h3>Cancer Pain Management</h3>
<li>Virginia Mason operates a Cancer Center, and our liaison with the medical and radiation oncologists provides a steady flow of patients with advanced cancer pain.  Most of these patients are candidates for neurolytic blocks, or implanted devices to deliver neuraxial pain medication.  Our Cancer Center continues to expand, and in conjunction with the Anesthesiology Pain Service, is developing an organized and comprehensive approach to pain management in all their patients.
<h3>Outside rotations and OR experience</h3>
<li>In addition to pain management at VM, several rotations to local institutions may be available, depending upon the fellow's individual interests.  These inlcude pediatric pain management at Children's Hospital, and private practice experience with a well known practitioner at Swedish Hospital.  One month of dedicated research time is planned for each fellow.  Other excellent local rotations are also possible.
<li>Many CA-4 fellows are interested in keeping their OR skills tuned up.  Indeed, we find that it is important to have the fellow rotate into the OR at the beginning of the fellowship year.  This allows them to get to know the anesthesia department and residents, as well as to gain experience in providing regional anesthesia the "VM way."  Typically, the Pain Fellow has no other OR duties for the remainder of the year; however, if he or she wants to provide some anesthetics so as not to get rusty, this can be easily arranged.
<h3>Stipend and Benefits</h3>
<li>Per annum salary in 1996 is approximately $38,500. Washington State training license, health and dental insurance, and parking are provided. Twenty days are allocated for vacation and professional time.
</ul>
<hr>	

