<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMMC Anesthesia Faculty and Resident Accomplishments</TITLE></HEAD>
<! Updated by Kent Hargrave, Virginia Mason Medical Center, Anesthesia Program>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><font size="6">Department of Anesthesiology</font>
<br>
<hr>

<Table>
<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>


<center><b>"Everything is what it is and is not another thing"</b><br>
Bishop Joseph Butler</center>

<p>The Department of Anesthesiology at Virginia Mason Medical Center is what it
 is--a unique blend of private and academic practice for which there is no stereotype. Its primary 
mission is the education of anesthesiology residents and fellows. We have trained over 300 
private anesthesiologists and university faculty members. Celebrating our 50th anniversary in 
1998, the Department maintains an international reputation for excellence in regional anesthesia. 
And while The Mason Clinic has been providing tertiary care in
 the Pacific Northwest for over 75 years, our community-based practice demands efficiency and value for today's 
reality of managed care.

<p>There may be some misperceptions regarding this thing called the Virginia Mason 
Department of Anesthesiology. One is that teaching and research are not consistent with efficient 
anesthesia care and cost containment. In reality, our economic past and future is rooted in 
efficient practice. Another misperception is that a non-university faculty cannot be academically 
productive, yet our scholarly output easily competes with the top ten university programs. 
We are especially proud that our residents and fellows participate in and contribute to both our 
efficient practice and our scholarly pursuits. Whereas participation in research and administration 
is not a requisite of our program, residents frequently avail themselves of these opportunities. 
Let us share with you some of their accomplishments.
<br><br>

<b>FROM JANUARY 1995 THROUGH JULY 1996...</b><br><br>

<b>Publications:</b><br>
Our residents and fellows have authored or co-authored--
<ul>
<li>Fifteen peer-reviewed journal articles<br>
<li>Four articles in anesthesia society newsletters<br>
<li>Eighteen scientific abstracts<br>
<li>And have another three manuscripts submitted for publication
</ul><br><br>

<b>Scientific Presentations:</b><br>
They have presented scientific posters and abstracts at various meetings, including--
<ul>
<li>Five presentations to the American Society of Anesthesiologists<br>
<li>Thirteen presentations to the American Society of Regional Anesthesia<br>
<li>Two papers at the International Anesthesia Research Society<br>
<li>And five presentations at the Western Anesthesia Resident's Conference<br>
</ul><br>

<b>Major Offices Held:</b><br>
Our residents gain invaluable experience serving in various political offices, including--
<ul>
<li>Virginia Mason Housestaff President<br>
<li>Chair and Vice-Chair of the Washington Society of Anesthesiologists, Resident Component<br>
<li>Resident Section Board Member, American Society of Regional Anesthesia<br>
<li>WSSA Delegate to the ASA Legislative Component<br><br>
</ul>
<br><hr>
<p>Virginia Mason only has fourteen full-time faculty members. Over the past eighteen months they 
have participated in the following scholarly pursuits, national offices, major lectures, and other 
services to anesthesiology:<br><br>

<b>FROM JANUARY 1995 THROUGH JULY 1996...</b><br><br>

<b>Publications:</b><br>
Virginia Mason Anesthesiologists have authored or co-authored--
<ul>
<li>One book<br>
<li>Seventeen book chapters<br>
<li>30 peer-reviewed journal articles, with another seven submitted manuscripts<br>
<li>24 scientific abstracts
</ul><br>

<b>Editorships and Journal Review:</b><br>
<ul>
<li>Associate Editor:  <u>Anesthesiology</u><br>
<li>Guest Reviewers: <i>Anesthesiology, Anesthesia and Analgesia, Regional Anesthesia, Journal of Emergency Medicine</i>
<li>Editorial Board:  <i>Landmarks--News and Views in Regional Anesthesia</i>
</ul><br>

<b>Major Invited Lectures:</b><br>
<ul>
<li>Thirteen international lectures on six continents
<li>Ten lectures, refresher courses, and panels--ASA
<li>Sixteen lectures, panels, refresher courses, and workshops--ASRA
<li>Fifteen major invited national lectures
<li>31 university visiting professorships in eighteen states
</ul><br>

<b>Major Offices Held:</b><br>

<ul>
<dt><li>American Society of Anesthesiologists
<dd><li>House of Delegates
<dd><li>Chairs, Committees on Professional Liability; and Pain Management
<dd><li>Director, ASA Guideline Development
<dd><li>Editor-in-Chief, Self-Education and Evaluation (SEE) Program
<dd><li>Various committee assignments and guideline task forces
</ul>
</dl>

<ul>
<dl>
<dt><li>American Society of Regional Anesthesia
<dd><li>Two Past Presidents
<dd><li>Three Board members
<dd><li>Various task forces, workshop and meeting chairs
</dl>
</ul>

<ul>
<dl>
<dt><li>Other major national and state positions, including:
<dd><li>Anesthesiology Residency Review Committee (RRC) member
<dd><li>Foundation board members
<dd><li>WSSA board members
<dd><li>Vice-President, Pan Pacific Surgical Association
</dl>
</ul><br>


<b>American Board of Anesthesiology:</b>
<ul>
<li>ABA In-Training Council member<br>
<li>Four senior examiners, three junior examiners, one question writer
</ul><br><br>


