<DOCNO>WT19-B05-119</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA055-000923-B016-216</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.vmmc.org:80/urology/impotence.html 199.238.227.2 19970208013622 text/html 4362
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 08 Feb 1997 01:35:30 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4191
Last-modified: Wed, 29 Jan 1997 19:39:16 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Impotence</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	Virginia Mason Medical Center has one of the largest, most 
active impotence programs in the United States. Diagnostic 
tests are tailored to the individual, avoiding unnecessary, 
expensive testing. Diagnostic tests range from simple blood 
studies to state-of-the-art digital penile arteriograms and 
dynamic infusion canvernography and canverosmetry to plan 
vascular reconstruction in suitable individuals.
<p>
	Treatment options range from counseling to many of the newer 
oral and intrauretheral agents available only through  FDA 
trials. A full-time nurse clinician manged the largest 
pharmacologic erection program in the Pacific Northwest with 
more than 400 patients. Upon entry into this progrm, the 
patient and his partner receive in-depth training and 
instruction on inection vasoactive agents into the penis to 
allow a physiologic erection. The patient and partner 
complete this program with the knowledge and confidence to make this 
treatment option successsful.
<p>
	Newer surgically implanted inflatable devices are now a very 
safe, reliable means of correctiong erectile impotence in 
many individuals. Because the devices are inflatable, the 
patients looks completely normal in the flaccid state, and thus has 
no problems with concealment or activities. When inflated, the 
devices give a completely normal-appearing erection. 
Virginia Mason Medcial Center places more of these devices than any 
institution in the Pacific Northwest. The majority are 
treated on an outpatient basis and our success rates are some of the 
highest in the United States.
<p>
	Occasionally, although rare, a specific arterial or venous 
problem can cause impotence in a young, healthy individual. 
Cutting edge diagnostic and surgical procedures are 
available to diagnose and correct these difficult problems in suitable 
individuals.
<p>
	Members of the Urology Department at VM frequently lecture 
nationally and internationally on various topics related to 
impotence. A short list of recently published papers on 
impotence-related topics follows below.
<pre>

</pre>
<em><strong>For more inforamtion about impotence or an for an 
appointment, please call the Department of Urology and Renal 
Transplantation at Virginia Mason Medical Center, (206) 
223-6772, or Lindy Fisher, RN, (206) 625-7195.</strong></em>
<pre>

</pre>
<h3><strong>Publications</strong></h3>
<ol>
<li>Govier FE, McClure RD, Weissman RM, Gibbons RP, Pritchett 
RT, Kramer-Levine D (RN): "Experience With Triple-Drug Therapy 
in a Pharmacologic Erection Program." J Urol 1993; 150:18222-1824.</li>

<li>Govier, FE, Johanssen E, Kramer-Levien D (RN): "Oral 
Terbutalie for the Treatent of Priapism." J Urol 1994; 
151:878-879.</li>

<li>Govier FE, Asase D, Hefty TR, McClure RD, Pritchett TR, 
Weissman RM: "Timing of Peile Color Flow Duplex 
Ultrasonography Utilizing a Triple-Drug Mixture." J Urol 1995; 
153:1472-1475.</li>

<li>Govier, FE: "Surgical Management of Inflatable Penile 
Prosthetic Devices." AUA Update Series, Leeson 10, Vol. 15, 
1996; 78-83.</li>

<li>Govier, FE, McClure RD, Weissman RM, Kramer-Levien D (RN): 
"Endocrine Screening for Sexual Dysfunction Utilizing Free 
Testosterone Determinations." J Urol 1996; 156:405-408.</li>

<li>Govier FE: "Back Pressure Testing to Prevent Autoinflation 
of Penile Prosthetic Devices." (Accepted by Urology)</li>

<li>Govier FE, Gibbons RP, Correa RJ, Pritchett TR, 
Kramer-Levien D (RN): "Mechanical Reliability and Surgical Complications 
of the Modern Three-Piece Inflatable Penile Prosthesis." (Submitted to the Journal of Urology)</li>
</ol>  
<pre>


