<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Urinary Incontinence</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	Urinary incontinence in females is very common, affecting up 
to one in four patients over the age of 60. Its causes and 
treatments vary widely, from a simple urinary tract 
infection to complex neurologic problems. The Department of Urology 
and Renal Transplantation at Virginia Mason Medical Center 
offers the latest in diagnostic studies and all forms of treatment 
for both male and female urinary control problems. The 
diagnostic testing required varies with each patient, but ranges from a 
simple examination to the latest in video urodynamic 
studies. Within the Urology Department, we have a full-time nurse 
clinician who works closely with physicians to tailor 
urodynamic testing that can accurately assess all phases of urinary 
storage and emptying. This instrumentation and X-ray equipment--valued at over $500,000--is used to test patients 
on an outpatient basis.
<p>
	Treatment options vary and each patient will be given a 
range of options, starting with the more conservative therapies 
and moving to more complex surgical procedures, when necessary.  Some of the simpler options are described here:
<ol>
<li>Pelvic floor retraining. Pelvic floor retraining and 
biofeedback can be performed by specially trained physical 
therapists within the the medical center.</li> 

<li>Medications. A variety of medications are used in 
specific types of leakage, usually those involving abnormal nervous 
pathways. We often participate in FDA trials of newer drugs 
not available except on protocol.</li>

<li>Collagen implants. Certain patients are candidates for 
the newer collagen implants. This treatment is administered in 
about 20 minutes under local anesthesia. The patient has no 
incisions and can resume normal activities within 24 hours.</li>
</ol> 
	If surgical procedures are required, a wide range of options 
are available, ranging from standard retropubic repairs to 
more complicated artificial urinary sphincters and pubovaginal 
sling procedures.
<pre>

</pre>
<em><strong>For more information or to schedule an appointment with a physician who specializes in urinary control, call Virginia Mason's Department of Urology and Renal Transplantation, (206) 223-6772.</em></strong>
<pre>

</pre>
<h3><strong>Publications</strong></h3>
<ol>
<li>Govier FE, Pritchett TR, Kornman JD (RN): "Correlation of the Cystoscopic Appearance and Functional Integrity of the Female Urethral Sphincteric Mechanism." Urology 1994; 44(2):250-253.</li>

<li>Govier FE, Gibbons RP, Correa RJ, Weissman RM, Pritchett TR, 
Hefty TR: "Pubovaginal Slings Using Fascia Lata for the Treatment of Intrinsic Sphincter Deficiency." J Urol 1997;157:68-73.</li>
</ol>
<pre>


</pre>
