<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Kidney Transplantation</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	Virginia Mason Medical Center has the largest kidney 
transplant program in Washington state. The most recent data 
from the United Network for Organ Sharing show actual 
one-year kidney graft and patient survival of 92.1 percent and 97.7 
percent respectively. These excellent results (from May 1992 
through April 1994) demostrate the superior outcomes 
possible by our collaborative approach. The 50 busiest kidney 
transplant centers in the United States annually perform 90 to 100 
kidney transplants from cadaveric donors, living-related and 
living-unrelated donors. The Virginia Mason team includes 
the transplant surgeon, nephrologist, coordinator, experienced 
transplant nurses, social workers and dieticians. In 
addition, the referring nephrologist, an important member of the team, 
is kept abreast of the transplant recipient's progress in 
preparation for the patient's recovery.
<p>
<em><strong>For more information, call Virginia Mason's Department of 
Urology and Renal Transplantation, (206) 223-6772.</strong></em>
<pre>

</pre>
<strong><h3>Pancreas Transplantation</h3></strong>
	Virginia Mason Medical Center has a long-standing commitment 
to the care of diabetic patients. The first use of insulin 
west of the Mississippi in the 1920s occured here, and ever 
since, Virginia Mason healthcare providers have emphasized patient 
care, diabetes education, use of the latest techniques an 
basic research into the prevention of diabetes. Nearly one-third 
of the patients receiving kidney transplants here have diabetes 
and some of these individuals will benefit from a pancreas 
transplant as well. After the simultaneous transplantation 
of both a kidney and pancreas (for its insulin production), the 
patient can be free of dialysis as well as insulin 
injections. Many complications of diabetes can be stablized or improved 
by this approach.
<p>
<em><strong>For more information, call Virginia Mason's Department of 
Urology and Renal Transplantation, (206) 223-6772.</strong></em>
<pre>

</pre>
<strong><h3>Renal Sparing Surgery</h3></strong>
Avoiding renal failure is one of the most important goals in Urology.  Renal sparing surgery can effectively remove some kidney cancers without removing the entire kidney.  The patient with a tumor in his or her only kidney (or significant disease in the opposite kidney) can face a difficult decision: Inadequately treat the tumor or face renal failure.  Recent experience, however, shows that partial removal of a kidney is appropriate for some patients.  At Virginia Mason Medical Center, renal sparing surgery sometimes involves the use of transplantation techniques, including kidney preservation, back-table dissection and auto-transplantation in advanced or diffucult cases.
<p>
<em><strong>For more information, call Virginia Mason's Department of Urology and Renal Transplantation, (206) 223-6772.</strong></em>
<pre>


</pre>
