<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Peyronie's Disease</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	Peyronie's disease is a nonspecific inflammatory process 
that involves the tunica albuginea of the penis. The patient 
ususaly notes the onset of penile pain with an erection, 
followed by curvature of the penis. The majority of patients 
identify no trauma and the cause of the inflammatory 
reaction is unknown. While various medications, injection of the 
plaque, and raditation treatments have been tried, non have been 
found to be beneficial and some may cause the process to worse. In 
approximately 70 percents of patients, the disease fortunately 
is self-limited and will never require therapy. The pain 
resolves and the bend either improves or is not sevre enough 
to affect intercourse.
<p>
	In about 30 percent of patients, the bend is secure enough to 
preclude intercourse or the inflammatory process extends into 
the penile cylinders and causes vascular damage, so that the 
rection will not be firm enough for penetration. The 
mainstay of treatment in this 30 percent is surgical. A variety of 
surgical procedures and/or prosthetic options allow the 
majorty of these patients to return to normal function.
<p>
	As a tertiary referral center, Virginia Mason Medical Center 
managed a larger number of patients with Peyronie's disease. 
Little diagnostic testing is usually required and in 
general, after a simple history and physical examination, your 
physician can outline possible options for correction of this 
sometimes devastating process.
<p>
<em><strong>For more information, please call the Department of Urology 
and Renal Transplantation at Virginia Mason Medical Center, 
(206) 223-6772.</strong></em>
<pre>


</pre>
