<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="left"><br>
<font size=+3><strong>Site Specific Analysis: <br>Prostate Cancer 1995</strong></font>
<p>
<br clear=all>
<table width="85%" border=0>
  <tr>
    <td><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
    <td>
      <h3><strong>Prostate Cancer at Virginia Mason</strong></h3>
<em><strong>Robert P. Gibbons, M.D.</em></strong>
<p>
	Prostate cancer is the most common malignancy among men in 
the United States, with an estimated 240,000 new cases 
diagnosed in 1995, which is an increase of 18 percent above 
1994. Additionally, the mortality from prostate cancer in 
1995 was estimated to be 40,400. Some of the increased incidence 
undoubtedly has occurred as a result of improved detection 
derived in part from an increased awareness of prostate 
cancer by patients and physicians using an annual prostate-specific 
antigen (PSA) blood test (in use at Virginia Mason since 
1987) in combination with digital rectal examination (DRE). As a 
result of such early detection efforts, there has been a 
shift toward the identification of more clinically localized 
tumors with the greatest potential for cure.
<p>
	The Virginia Mason experience with prostate cancer mirrors 
the national trends. Prostate cancer was the most frequently 
diagnosed primary cancer seen at Virginia Mason in 1990 and 
1994, whereas it was secondary to lung cancer in 1980. There 
were 285 new analytic (a case is considered analytic when 
the patient is initially diagnosed and/or treated at VM) cases 
of prostate cancer seen in 1994, and nearly half (49.5 percent) 
were diagnosed elsewhere but referred to Virginia Mason for 
treatment. This compares with 249 new analytic cases at 
Swedish Hospital and 96 at the University of Washington Hospital in 
1994. The most favorable and positive trend attributable to 
early detection efforts is that only 5 percent of patients 
in 1994 had advanced systemic disease (Stages D-1 and D-2) 
compared to 11.5 percent in 1990 and 21.2 percent in 1980. 
One concern regarding early detection efforts was that an 
increase in "insignificant" (Stage A-1) prostate cancer would be 
detected that would not require treatment, but would be a 
source of anxiety to the patient. There has actually been a 
decrease in the percent of these "insignificant" Stage A-1 cancers 
detected, from 10.2 percent in 1980 in  9.1 percent in 1990, 
and 4.6 percent in 1994.
<p>
	For more than 30 years, Virginia Mason has been a leader in 
the definitive treatment of localized (Stages A-2, B and C) 
prostate cancer with surgery, radiation therapy, or 
combinations of both. Figures 1 and 2 illustrate the overall 
survival up to 10 years in patients treated in 1980 and up 
to five years following treatment in 1990. These illustrate the 
importance of early detection. Figure 3 is the Virginia 
Mason experience with 463 patients with Stages A and B prostate 
cancer treated with surgery with or without radiation 
therapy, and represents the percentage of patients who died of 
prostate cancer following treatment. For example, 15 years following 
treatment, only 11 percent had died of prostate cancer.
<p>
	The lifetime risk for a newborn male to develop prostate 
cancer is 13 percent, and his risk of dying of the disease 
is 3 percent. Currently in the United States, a man is diagnosed 
with prostate cancer every three minutes, and one dies of 
prostate cancer every 15 minutes. Effective treatment is 
available if it is detected early.
<p>
<tt><font size="+1">
<p>
<strong>Cancer Incidence by Site and Sex 1994</strong>
</font></tt>
