<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Stone Disease</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	Virginia Mason Medical Center's Department of Urology and 
Renal Transplantation has a long and rich history in the 
diagnosis and treatment of urinary tract stone disease. 
While we are a primary referral center in the Pacific Northwest for 
the management of difficult and challenging stone problems of 
the kidneys, ureters and bladder, our stone center, called the 
Lithotripter Unit, is designed to handle single or multiple 
uncomplicated stones in an efficient, timely, 
patient-focused manner. Because the Lithotripter Unit is a dedicated stone 
center encompassing an array of technologies, our ability to 
deal with a patient's stone problem in a single, outpatient 
visit is greater than 95 percent. Open surgical intervention 
for stone problems has fallen to less than 2 percent.
<p>
	The following technologies and expertise are available in 
the Lithotripter Unit:
<ol>
<li>Extracorporeal Shockwave Lithotripsy (ESWL) via a Dornier 
HM3 unit fractures kidney and ureteral stones into passable 
fragments. This procedure requires outpatient anesthesia, 
but no surgical incision.</li>

<li>Our on-site cystoscopy suite allows a urologist to 
perform appropriate manipulations of the stones just prior to ESWL 
therapy, including passing of tubes into the kidney via the 
bladder. These tubes (called stents) are helpful in keeping 
the kidney draining while stone fragments pass. Alternatively, 
many stones may be as effectively treated in the cystoscopy 
suite without the aide of ESWL by a variety of options:</li>
<ul>
<li><strong>Basket extraction.</strong> The physician passes a tiny wire 
basket into the lower ureter via the bladder, grabbing and pulling 
the stone free. This is an outpatient procedure with--or 
without--the need of a stent.</li>

<li><strong>Ureteroscopy.</strong> This allows the urologist to actually look 
up the ureter, visualize the stone and remove it using the 
basket under direction vision. If the stone is too large or 
impacted in the ureter, it can be fragmented with energy 
directly applied to it via a laser (Candella pulsed dye 
laser), ultrasound (high frequency sound waves) or electrical energy 
(electrohydraulic lithotripsy). This too is an outpatient procedure usually requiring a stent.</li>

<li><strong>Cystopscopy.</strong> This procedure used to remove bladder stones 
is also an outpatient surgery.</li></ul>

<li>Percutaneous ultrasonic lithotripsy is reserved for 
patients with very large kidney stones (too large for ESWL). 
This involves placing a special scope within the kidney 
through the patient's side under X-ray control. While directly 
visualizing the stone, high frequency sound waves break up 
and suction removes the stone. This requires a general 
anesthesia and a two- to three-day hospitalization, but a short 
post-hospitalization recovery.</li>

<li>In complicated situations, open surgery may still be 
necessary and remains a valued skill in our institution.</li>
</ol>
<pre>

</pre>
<strong><em>For more information, contact the Department of Urology and 
Renal Transplantation, (206) 223-6772, or the Lithotripsy Unit, (206) 223-8899.</em></strong>   
<pre>


</pre>
<h4><strong><em><a href="index.html">Back to Urology index</a></em></strong></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
</body>
</html>
