<HEAD>

<TITLE>Virginia Mason - Foundation Cardiology</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#0000ff">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1"VALIGN="TOP">
<IMG SRC="logo2.gif"><IMG SRC="logoc.gif">

                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1"  ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">

        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="287">
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">T</font>hanks to Virginia Mason donors, the cardiology department was able to purchase a new piece of technological equipment designed to image the interior surface of the coronary artery.  With intravascular imaging possible, physicians can assess what type of blockage a patient might have in their coronary artery.  Intravascular imaging offers a significant advancement in the evaluation of coronary artery disease by enabling physicians to determine the safest and most effective treatment for the patient.
<p>
<center>
<a href="give.htm">Make a Difference in Cardiology</a>
</center>
</td>
                <TD COLSTART="3" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="210">
<IMG SRC="cardio01.jpg" border=2><br>
<font size=2><i>Cardiology's new intravascular imaging system gives physicians the ability to diagnose and evaluate the treatment of patients with coronary artery disease.</i></font>
	</td>
</tr>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2" WIDTH="497">
   <hr>
	</td>
</tr>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2" WIDTH="497">
<b>Heart disease is America's number one killer.</b>  More people die each year from heart disease than from any other disease.
<p>
At Virginia Mason, a <b>non-profit</b> medical center, we want to enable our community to fight this disease before it strikes, and to save the lives of those it has already stricken.  Donors to Virginia Mason's Healthy Heart Fund have helped us to support crucial life-saving techniques, research, and preventitive services that keep hearts healthy.
<p>
Virginia Mason physicians use the latest technologies to diagnose, treat, and prevent dangerous heart conditions.  Our physicians use high-tech Echocardiographic Imaging Systems (echo-machines) to take ultrasonic images of the heart, which can eliminate the need for more invasive procedures.
<p>
<blockquote>
<i>
A school teacher in town for a math convention was brought to Virginia Mason exhibiting signs of a stroke.  Virginia Mason cardiologists performed a trans-esophageal echocardiogram and found a very small hole in her heart where a blood clot had formed, broken loose, and traveled to her brain, causing a stroke.
<p>
During a trans-esophageal echocardiogram, a probe is inserted into the esophagus, allowing the image of the heart to be taken without the obstruction of ribs and muscles, as it would be in a conventional echocardiogram, which is performed externally.  <b>Without a trans-esophageal echocardiogram, a hole of that size would not have been located.</b>  Virginia Mason Cardiothoracic surgeons repaired the tiny hole, possibly saving the teacher from additional strokes.
</i>
</blockquote>
<p>
Virginia Mason physicians also use these versatile echo-machines in open-heart surgeries, as well as to pinpoint areas where strokes have occured, and to locate embolisms.  Donors helped to purchase a new echo-machine and new trans-esophageal probes.
<p>
Advances in interventional cardiology have allowed patients with advanced coronary artery disease to be treated with catheter techniques rather than open heart surgery.
<p>
<blockquote>
<i>
A commercial fisherman from Alaska was transferred by plane to VMMC for evaluation of a threatening heart attack.  An angiogram of the coronary vessels revealed two vessels critically narrowed by atherosclerosis.  With a combination of balloon angioplasty, rotational atherectomy (also known as "coronary roto-rooter"), and stainless steel stent placement, his symptoms were resolved and he traveled home a few days later.
</i>
</Blockquote>	
<p>
To help guide therapy within the three-millimeter diameter coronary vessel, a one-millimeter diameter ultrasound device was used to observe the amount of cholesterol-filled plaque in the vessel. This ultrasound device was available thanks to a generous Virginia Mason donor.
<p>
Donors make a difference. Virginia Mason was able to establish its Electrophysiology Laboratory thanks to a generous donor. The Electrophysiology Lab uses sophisticated technology to evaluate heart rhythms that are too fast or too slow. The physicians and nurses in the lab also treat heart rhythm disorder patients using highly specialized cauterization techniques, pacemakers, and implantable defibrillators.
<p>
<blockquote>
<I>
A 29-year-old man was referred to Virginia Mason from a local hospital where he was diagnosed with a heart condition that caused his heart to beat too fast (atrial fibrillation).  During the patient 's evaluation at Virginia Mason, an echocardiogram uncovered a very large aortic aneurysm as well. Guided by a trans-esophageal echocardiogram, Virginia Mason Cardiothoracic surgeons removed the aneurysm. Following recovery, Virginia Mason's Electrophysiologist successfully treated the patient's heart condition and he no longer experiences atrial fibrillation.
</blockquote>
</I>
<p>
Donations to the Healthy Heart fund have supported vital research conducted at Virginia Mason. Researchers are continually learning more about heart disease and the effects of certain types of treatments by conducting clinical research that benefits patients and healthy hearts alike. Virginia Mason physicians conducted 18 clinical cardiology research projects in 1995. Research conducted today could save your life or the life of a loved one tomorrow.
<p>
Rehabilitating patients who have heart conditions is an important step in the healing process. Virginia Mason's Cardiac Rehabilitation Center provides patients with supervised exercise, heart monitoring, and education about lifestyle and dietary changes. Our rehabilitation center is a vital resource for patients. Your gift will help provide additional heart monitors, exercise bikes, and treadmills for these patients.
<p>
With an increasing number of patients coming to Virginia Mason for treatment of heart-related illnesses, Virginia Mason relies on philanthropy to help us provide life-saving, efficient procedures for the people of the Northwest. 

</table>
</HTML>
