<HEAD>

<TITLE>Virginia Mason - Foundation Hyperbaric</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#0000ff">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1"VALIGN="TOP">
<IMG SRC="logo2.gif"><IMG SRC="logoc.gif">

                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1"  ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">

        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="287">
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">V</font>M's Hyperbaric Department serves as the regional referral center for a variety of illnesses, including: decompression illness ("the bends"), healing of tissue injury following radiation therapy for cancer, carbon monoxide poisoning, and necrotizing soft tissue infections (the "flesh-eating" bacteria).  For some of these conditions, hyperbaric oxygen therapy offers the only hope of survival or recovery.  Virginia Mason Foundation embarked on a long-term program to find support to replace this equipment with a new multi-place hyperbaric chamber, which will increase our capacity by up to 400% and allow us to treat emergency cases (2/3 of our current caseload) without interrupting regularly scheduled patients.  In 1995, donors contributed more than $150,000 towards this fund.
</td>
                <TD COLSTART="3" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="210">
<IMG SRC="hyper01.jpg" border=2><br>
<font size=2><i>An 11-year-old-boy's chicken pox turned into a necrotizing soft-tissue infection caused by "flesh-eating" bacteria.  Doctors at Children's Hospital feared he might loose his leg, and possibly his life.  They referred him to VM's Hyperbaric Department, and after many hours of treatment, he had a complete recovery.</i></font>
	</td>
</tr>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2" WIDTH="497">
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4>Hyperbaric Program -- Facts</font>
</center>
<p>
<font size=2 color="#2222c2">WHY IS VIRGINIA MASON'S PROGRAM SPECIAL?</font>  VM's Hyperbaric Department, directed by Dr. Neil B. Hampson, has been in existence for over 27 years.  It is the only 24-hour, critical care, multi-person, non-private, patient-care based center in a five-state area.  In addition to patient care, VM's doctors also promote disease prevention through public education -- for example, since 1992 when Dr. Hampson published an article in <i>The Journal of American Medical Association</i> (summarized in <i>Reader's Digest</i>) detailing the risk of carbon monoxide poisoning for children riding in the back of pickup trucks, no additional victims have been seen (the caseload had been running at 5 to 6 patients per year).  VM's Hyperbaric Department is also the regional coordinating center for the Divers' Alert Network.
<p>
<font size=2 color="#2222c2">HOW MANY PEOPLE USE VM'S HYPERBARIC PROGRAM EVERY YEAR?</font>  As hyperbaric oxygen therapy has become an increasingly accepted therapy for a core group of 12 illnesses, and as more research is being done to support these treatments, VM's caseload has increased dramatically, from 164 patients treated just 5 years ago, to 273 in the last year (35 of them children, the youngest just 3 months old).  Almost 3,000 people have received hyperbaric treatment at VM since 1969.
<p>
<font size=2 color="#2222c2">WHY DOES VM NEED NEW EQUIPMENT?</font>  The positive results shown by VM's hyperbaric oxygen treatment have led to a rapidly increasing number of referrals, so that the program is operating at full capacity using current equipment (installed in 1969).  VM doctors estimate we could increase capacity by up to 400% by installing up-to-date equipment, which, because of its greater efficiency, would also reduce the cost of medical care for both patients and insurers.  Perhaps the most crucial need for new equipment, however, relates to how many patients we can treat, and on what time schedule.  In 1994 and 1995, more than two-thirds of our cases were emergencies.  Because we currently can treat only one critical care patient at a time, we must interrupt any regularly scheduled patients to accommodate critical care patients or emergencies.
<p>
<center>
<a href="give.htm">Make a Difference in Hyperbaric Treatment</a>
</center>
	</TD>
<tr>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2"  ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="497" VALIGN="TOP">
<hr>
		</TD>
</TR>
	
</table>
