<HEAD>

<TITLE>Virginia Mason - Foundation Research</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#0000ff">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1"VALIGN="TOP">
<IMG SRC="logo2.gif"><IMG SRC="logoc.gif">

                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1"  ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">

        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="287">
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">M</font>ore than 100 ongoing research projects focusing on diabetes, heart, arthritis, cancer, ataxia and other diseases are carried out at our internationally-renowned Research Center.  VM researchers have identified genes that contribute to diabetes and arthritis and are working on disease prevention.  With severe federal cutbacks in medical research funding, unrestricted program support is more important than ever to ensure that this vital work can continue.
</td>
                <TD COLSTART="3" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="210">
<IMG SRC="research.jpg" border=2><br>
<font size=2><i>Dr. Gerald Nepom.</i></font>
	</td>
</tr>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2" WIDTH="497">
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">RESPECTED INTERNATIONALLY AMONG ITS PEERS, THE VIRGINIA MASON RESEARCH CENTER IS COMPRISED OF A WORLD-CLASS TEAM.</font>
</center>
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">A</font>t Virginia Mason Research Center (VMRC), our scientists target disease at its core - - at the molecular and cellular level. Our researchers focus on the human body's immune system to determine genetic patterns, links, and codes in the hope of interrupting the pattern to prevent the onset of disease.

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">B</font>y focusing on the cellular biology of the human immune system, VMRC has built depth and expertise in diseases of the human immune system, such as diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, and cancer.

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">I</font>n addition to VMRC's core staff of principle investigators, post-doctoral scientists, and pre-doctoral and technical staff members, our scientists work hand-in-hand with their physician colleagues at Virginia Mason Medical Center on almost 100 ongoing research projects focusing on diabetes, heart, arthritis, cancer, ataxia, and other diseases. These clinical trials focus on turning "basic science" breakthroughs into practical applications for patients - - bringing the benefits of medical research from "bench to bedside."

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">T</font>o expand the impact of this work even further, VMRC scientists collaborate with universities throughout the United States, as well as with local biotechnology companies and medical researchers at Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center and the University of Washington.


<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">A PROVEN TRACK RECORD</font><br>
<i>HARD WORK, INNOVATION AND RESULTS.</i>

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">R</font>esearch at Virginia Mason began in the 1920s. For the first three decades, much of that research took the form of clinical reports and statistical analyses. In the early 1950s, a team of distinguished scientists, physicians and leaders founded the Virginia Mason Research Center to focus on basic research. In recent years VMRC researchers have identified genes that contribute to diabetes and arthritis and are working on disease prevention.

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">Highlights of recent VMRC accomplishments and awards include:</font>

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1995</font> The National Institutes of Health and the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation International name VMRC as one of only eight centers worldwide to receive their Centers of Excellence Award for VMRC's diabetes research program.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1994</font> The National Institutes of Health appoint Dr. Gerald Nepom, VMRC's Director, as chairperson of NIH's prestigious Immunological Sciences Review Group.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1993</font> The Juvenile Diabetes Foundation gives its Living and Giving Award to Dr. Gerald Nepom in recognition of VMRC's breakthroughs in the genetics of diabetes and Dr. Nepom's leadership of VMRC's internationally-known research program.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1992</font> A new inpatient clinical research unit is established at Virginia Mason Medical Center.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1991</font> VMRC researchers discover the blueprint that will lead to attempts to "switch off" the gene that makes some people susceptible to diabetes.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1989</font> VMRC scientists identify an important genetic marker for the most prevalent form of juvenile rheumatoid arthritis.
<br>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">1989</font> In 3 major publications, VMRC scientists describe for the first time the use of genetic engineering techniques to manipulate and modify the function of molecules that account for susceptibility in diabetes.

<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">T</font>hese and many other scientific breakthroughs at VMRC have meant a vast improvement in the quality of life for thousands of people. With your help, VMRC will continue to search for the causes and cures of many disabling auto-immune diseases.<p>
<center>
<a href="give.htm">Make a Difference in Research</a>
</center>
	</TD>
<tr>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2"  ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="497" VALIGN="TOP">
<hr>
		</TD>
