<HEAD>

<TITLE>Virginia Mason - Foundation Telemedicine</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#0000ff">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1"VALIGN="TOP">
<IMG SRC="logo2.gif"><IMG SRC="logoc.gif">

                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1"  ROWSTART="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="572">

        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="287">
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">I</font>n 1994 Virginia Mason donors provided support to build a telemedicine studio clinic at our main Seattle campus.  A live, interactive connection between this base and "clinics" in Alaska and rural Washington allows the VM consulting physician to examine a patient at the remote location as if the patient were in his office.  VM's telemedicine program is <b>the only operational studio</b> of its kind in the Northwest.  In 1995 donors provided $86,000 to support equipment upgrades in VM's Volney Richmond Auditorium, so that remote physicians and other healthcare specialists can "attend" weekly medical education lectures at VM in Seattle.
</td>
                <TD COLSTART="3" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="210">
<IMG SRC="telemed.jpg" border=2><br>
<font size=2><i></i></font>
	</td>
</tr>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2" WIDTH="497">
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">Telemedicine at VMMC</font>
</center>
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">A</font>s a continuation and expansion of VMMC's decades-long practice of taking a leadership role in the delivery of healthcare services throughout the Northwest, VMMC recently established a telemedicine studio clinic at our main campus in Seattle. Integrated with this base site are "studio clinics" located in outlying communities in Alaska and rural Washington. A live, interactive connection between the two sites gives the VMMC consulting physician the ability to examine a patient at the remote location as if the patient were in their office. VMMC's telemedicine program is unique in that it is the only operational studio of its kind in the Pacific Northwest and it uses the quality, integrated specialty services of Virginia Mason. In just the short time this project has been operating, the response from physicians, nurses, and patients who have benefited from these studio clinics has been overwhelming. For example, at a recent nursing oncology forum, one Juneau nurse remarked that for the next forum they would have to reserve their largest conference room -- since so many nurses wanted to attend.
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">S</font>uccessful pilot telemedicine projects in Sitka, Alaska, and Forks, Washington, led the way for new studios in Juneau, Alaska and in Port Angeles, Washington. Indeed, VMMC's pilot teleradiology program in Sitka was so successful that Sitka Community Hospital was able to recruit an on-site radiologist, predicated on the support provided by the continuance of the VMMC teleradiology link. Just recently a generous Alaska couple made it possible for us to purchase the telemedicine equipment needed to equip appropriately the Sitka and Juneau hospitals (the equipment we had been using there during the pilot projects was on loan).  A recent grant from the U.S. Dept. of Commerce will enable us to provide pain management and rehabilitation services to people in Forks, Washington, as well as in the Makah and Quileute tribal areas.  We are researching the opportunities to establish future studios in Petersburg, Craig, and Wrangell, Alaska, and elsewhere in the Pacific Northwest. With these existing and new studios, we anticipate serving significantly more patients and doctors in the near future.
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">R</font>emote patients in Sitka, Juneau, and elsewhere have received consultation and direct care from VMMC specialists in Allergy, Cardiology, Dermatology, Neurology, Orthopaedics and Hand Surgery, Pain Management, Psychiatry and Mental Health, Radiology, Rheumatology, and Speech Therapy. Physicians, nurses, and other healthcare providers in these areas have participated with VMMC health-care professionals in Tumor Boards, Diabetes Health Forums, Administrative Conferences, Cardiology Conferences, Oncology Nursing Forums, and Continuing Medical Education Forums.
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">A</font> wide variety of individuals, corporations, and foundations have provided support for the equipment and operating costs of our telemedicine program. Significantly, more than 40% of the individuals who have supported VMMC's telemedicine program have been Alaska donors. Additional support for the program has been provided by the remote sites themselves (which have committed facilities and staff to this project and are paying for local telephone network services), VM donors, and by VMMC physicians, who are not directly reimbursed for telemedicine consultations. VMMC is committed to working with the remote sites to find or provide the additional financial support needed to cover non-billable patient care fees, staff support, network service, and telemedicine equipment, so that this program can continue to serve an increased number of remote patients, nurses, physicians, and other providers.
<p>
<center>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">Conclusion</font>
</center>
<p>
<font size=4 color="#2222c2">V</font>MMC has a deep desire to continue serving the educational and consultative needs of the Northwest's rural and remote medical community and their patients. However, with changes in healthcare financing challenging the Medical Center's ability to support regional outreach programs, VMMC must rely on philanthropic assistance from private donors, corporations, and foundations to develop and maintain these linkages to Alaska healthcare providers and their patients.
<p>
<center>
<a href="give.htm">Make a Difference in Telemedicine</a>
</center>
	</TD>
<tr>
                <TD COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="1" ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="75" VALIGN="TOP">
                </TD>
                <TD COLSTART="2" COLSPAN="2"  ROWSTART="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="497" VALIGN="TOP">
<hr>
		</TD>
</TR>
	
