<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Virginia Mason Hospital, Transitional Internship</TITLE></HEAD>
<! Updated by Kent Hargrave, Virginia Mason Medical Center, Anesthesia Program>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><font size="6">Department of Anesthesiology</font><br>
<hr>

<Table>
<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>

</center>
<br>



<center>
<img src="trans.jpg" alt="Virginia Mason Hospital, Transitional Internship">
</center>

<blockquote>
	Virginia Mason Medical Center is a major referral center for the Pacific Northwest including Alaska; consequently, our house staff are exposed to the complex problems of tertiary care medicine.  In addition we provide for the continuing health needs of the Seattle community resulting in a large volume of patients admitted with common medical problems, such as GI bleeding, myocardial infarctions, diabetic ketoacidosis, and acute abdominal surgical emergencies.  The quality of our patient material is a major strength of our training programs.  Our patients represent a wide variety of diseases and come from all socioeconomic backgrounds.  Annually there are 11,902 admissions and 17,292 emergency room visits to the 233 bed Virginia Mason Medical Center.
</blockquote>
<h4>Faculty</h4>
<blockquote>
	The teaching faculty is comprised of physicians from the Virginia Mason Clinic which is contiguous with Virginia Mason Hospital.  The attending staff in all departments work well together permitting an efficient team approach to all patients.  The close relationship developed between house staff and teaching faculty permit expanded house staff responsibility to a degree unusual in most private hospitals.  The 270 Virginia Mason Medical Center physicians, representing all specialties of medicine and surgery, see 372,022 outpatient visits per year.  This wealth of clinical material becomes the teaching service of the Hospital when these patients are hospitalized.  The Clinic staff, most of whom retain academic appointments at the University of Washington, have come from full-time academic positions.  The opportunity to teach house staff is one of the major reasons these physicians have chosen to practice at Virginia Mason Medical Center, and they are deeply committed to providing an outstanding educational experience.  Although every section continues to do research, the primary responsibility of the teaching faculty is patient care, seeing patients daily in offices adjacent to the Hospital or in one of the nine satellite primary care clinics.  This environment provides highly skilled clinicians as teachers and, in addition, a unique opportunity for house staff involvement in a large ambulatory practice.
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
	The combined collegial efforts of teaching and attending staffs at Virginia Mason Medical Center provide outstanding medical care, evidence of which was provided in the New England Journal of Medicine.  Virginia Mason Medical Center was among the 100 hospitals (out of 3100 studied) with the lowest 30 day risk-adjusted mortality rates.   In fact, it was one of only 35 hospitals with "exceptionally low mortality rates" in both 1986 and 1987.  The prototype hospital for low mortality rates observed by Hartz et al* accurately describes Virginia Mason Hospital, i.e. a private, not-for-profit, teaching hospital with a high percentage of board-certified specialists, a high occupancy rate, technological sophistication, and a greater percentage of nurses who are R.N.s.
</blockquote>
<h4>Support</h4>
<blockquote> 
	Virginia Mason Medical Center has superb state of the art diagnostic laboratory radiology and pathology departments, which provide 24-hour coverage for emergency studies.  The expedient service furnished by these departments provide an excellent learning environment for the house staff.  Therapeutic interventions available include cardiac catheterization with PTCA, cardiothoracic surgery, hemodialysis, renal and pancreatic transplantation and renal lithotripsy.
<p>
	The library subscribes to more than 400 medical journals, employing two full-time librarians devoted to assisting the staff in reference searches.  The library has Medline access and has developed a close working relationship with the University of Washington Medical Library.
<p>
	The Virginia Mason Medical Center campus includes the Virginia Mason Research Center.  A staff of over 50 people, including 10 M.D.s and Ph.D.s, is actively engaged in clinical and basic research ranging from immunology to hyperbaric medicine.
</blockquote>
<h4>House Staff</h4>
<blockquote>
	The first graduate year program at Virginia Mason Hospital draws top applicants from many medical schools across the country.  Applicants who match at Virginia Mason Hospital rank in the upper one-third of their classes, many having attained high academic honors. The Transitional Year Program at Virginia Mason Medical Center fulfills the recommended year of basic clinical training.  It is designed to provide a year of broadly based clinical experience for first-year medical school graduates.  The cooperative relationship between the departments of Medicine, Surgery, Radiology and Anesthesia at Virginia Mason Medical and the Children's Hospital and Medical Center allows us to provide a top quality multi-disciplinary Transitional Year Program.
</blockquote>

<h4>Should you have unanswered questions, please feel free to contact the staff in the Office of House Staff Affairs at (206) 583-6079.</h4>

James W. Benson, Jr., M.D.<br>
Director of Medical Education<br>
<p>
* Hartz AJ, Krakauer H, Kuhn EM et al.  Hospital characteristics and mortality rates.  N Engl J. Med 1989; 321:1720-5.<br>


<center>
<h4><a href="residen3.htm">Return to VMMC Anesthesia Residency Page</a></h4>
</center>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

