<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<img src="../images/repoorgans.GIF" align=left hspace=7>
<h1>How does a vasectomy work?</h1>
	As you know, millions of sperm cells are produced in the 
testicles. These sperm then flow to the prostate gland 
behind the penis where they combine with semen, the sticky fluid 
that is ejaculated from the penis during an orgasm. The drawing 
shows how the sperm travel from each testicle by way of a 
tube known as the vas deferens. 
<p>
After a no-scalpel vasectomy, the testicles continue to produce sperm, but the route by which they travel to the penis has been blocked. The sperm are 
simply absorbed by the body.
<pre>

</pre>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><h2><a href="question5.html">What happens during a vasectomy?</a></h2></td><td><a href="question5.html"><img src="../images/rightarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td>
 </tr>
</table>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><a href="index.html"><img src="../images/leftarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td><td><h2><a href="index.html"><em>Back to overview</em></a></h2></td>
 </tr>
</table>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
