<DOCNO>WT19-B05-157</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA055-000923-B019-474</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.vmmc.org:80/urology/noscalpel/question5.html 199.238.227.2 19970208014809 text/html 1780
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 08 Feb 1997 01:47:17 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 1609
Last-modified: Thu, 30 Jan 1997 21:25:15 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<h1>What happens during a vasectomy?</h1>
	First, the scrotal area is cleaned and shaved. (You can do 
this at home yourself, if you prefer.) The diagram shows the 
area that needs to be free of hair. 
<p>
Then, the doctor will inject a local anesthetic. When the area is numb, the doctor makes a small puncture in the scrotal skin, then draws out 
and blocks (cauterizes) the tubes, one at a time.
<p>
During the procedure, there is no knife, no incision and no 
stitches. A simple gauze bandage is placed loosely over the 
site. 
<p>
The puncture, virtually invisible after the procedure, 
heals by itself. You'll experience less pain, fewer 
complications and quicker healing than with a conventional 
vasectomy.
<pre>

</pre>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><h2><a href="question6.html">And following the surgery  . . .?</a></h2></td><td><a href="question6.html"><img src="../images/rightarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td>
 </tr>
</table>
