<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<h1>And following the surgery  . . .?</h1>
	Although the vasectomy takes only a few minutes, you may 
still feel more comfortable having someone else drive you 
home.
<p>
	Lie down for the evening when you get home. This helps 
reduce the swelling. When needed for discomfort, you can take 
aspirin, acetaminophen such as Tylenol, or ibuprofen such as 
Advil or Nuprin.
<p>
	Apply an ice pack to the area for 10 minutes at a time that 
evening.
<p>
	The first few days following the procedure, you should wear 
an athletic supporter or snug-fitting jockey shorts to help 
support your scrotum.
<p>
	For the week following the vasectomy, don't lift items 
 heavier than 15 pounds--and avoid strenuous exercise or 
activity.
<pre>

</pre>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><h2><a href="question7.html">What signs should I be aware of?</a></h2></td><td><a href="question7.html"><img src="../images/rightarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td>
 </tr>
</table>
