<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<h1>Can I immediately stop using birth control?</h1>
	No. Sperm can remain in the upper part of the vas deferens 
and may still be ejaculated for a period of time after the 
surgery. That's why you absolutely must continue to use 
birth control methods until tests conclusively show that your 
sperm count drops to zero.
<pre>

</pre>
