<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<img src="../images/blurb4.gif" align="left">
<h1>How will I know when it's safe to have unprotected sex again?</h1>
	Eight weeks and 20 to 25 ejaculations after your vasectomy, 
a sperm count will be obtained from your semen sample. When 
there is no evidence of sperm in two samples, you are sterile and can stop using birth control. If there is still evidence of sperm in your first specimen, you will be asked to wait a month and bring in another sample for analysis.
<pre>

</pre>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><h2><a href="question11.html">Are there risks involved in having a vasectomy?</a></h2></td><td><a href="question11.html"><img src="../images/rightarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td>
 </tr>
