<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<img src="../images/noscapl2.GIF" align="middle">
<pre>
</pre>
<table width=85%>
<tr>
<td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
<td>
<h1>Are there risks involved in having a vasectomy?</h1>
	As with any procedure, there can be some risks. However, 
vasectomy is commonly performed without serious side 
effects. Very rarely complications occur, such as bleeding or 
infection. Up to one percent of patients may develop testis pain, which 
usually resolves on its own.
<p>
	A painful lump may develop at the site where the vas 
deferens are blocked--this is called a sperm granuloma. The lump 
normally resolves itself, but occasionally requires 
antibiotics or surgery.
<p>
	There are no proven long-term health risks from vasectomy. 
Heart disease, prostate cancer and other diseases have been 
looked at, but no conclusive link with vasectomy has been 
found.
<p>
	Sometimes the tubes try to grow back together again. The 
tubes, however, rarely reconnect. (The odds of this 
happening are about one in 1,000.) If the tubes were to reconnect, it 
would usually be discovered on your semen analysis, and your 
doctor would repeat the procedure without charge.
<pre>

</pre>
<table>
 <tr>
<td><h2><a href="question12.html">What Are the Advantages of a No-Scalpel Vasectomy?</a></h2></td><td><a href="question12.html"><img src="../images/rightarrow.GIF" border=0></a></td>
 </tr>
