<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="left"><br>
<font size=+3><strong>Site Specific Analysis: <br>Prostate Cancer 1995</strong></font>
<p>
<br clear=all>
<table width="85%" border=0>
  <tr>
    <td><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
    <td>

For more than 30 years, Virginia Mason has been a leader in 
the definitive treatment of localized (Stages A-2, B and C) 
prostate cancer with surgery, radiation therapy, or 
combinations of both. Figures 1 and 2 illustrate the overall 
survival up to 10 years in patients treated in 1980 and up 
to five years following treatment in 1990. These illustrate the 
importance of early detection.

	<center>
<strong>Figure 1</strong><br>
<img src="images/graph1.GIF">
<p>
	
<strong>Figure 2</strong><br>
<img src="images/graph2.GIF">
<p>
</center>
	Figure 3 is the Virginia 
Mason experience with 463 patients with Stages A and B prostate 
cancer treated with surgery with or without radiation 
therapy, and represents the percentage of patients who died of 
prostate cancer following treatment. For example, 15 years following 
treatment, only 11 percent had died of prostate cancer.
<center>
	<p>
<strong>Figure 3</strong><br>
<img src="images/graph3.GIF">
</center>
