<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Vasectomy Reversal</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
	While half a million men in the United States will have a 
<a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> this year, 5,000 (1 percent) will change their 
minds and decide to have their vasectomies reversed. A <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> 
reversal (vasovasostomy), performed on an outpatient basis 
under local anesthesia, takes approximately three hours. 
Recovery takes approximately three days.
<p>
	Due to a high divorce rate and subsequent remarriages, 
<a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> reversals have become increasingly popular. 
Skilled microsurgeons and sophisticated microscopic equipment have 
improved substantially the success rate of <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> 
reversals.
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to overview</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
</DOC>
