<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Success Rates</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
<strong>Before a man decides to have a <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> reversal</strong>, a 
<a href="glossary.html">gynecologist</a> should examine his partner to make certain that 
his partner's fertility is normal.
<p>
In 80 percent to 90 percent of patients who have a <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> 
reversal, male reproductive cells (sperm) return to the 
<a href="glossary.html">semen</a>. The patient's partner becomes pregnant in 55 percent to 65 
percent of these cases.
<p>
Reversals performed within seven to eight years after the 
<a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> have the highest success rate. Many males, 
however, 15 to 20 years after reversal are able to impregnate their 
partners.
<p>
The success of this procedure is based on several factors, 
such as findings at surgery (presence of <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a>), the 
microscopic equipment and instruments used, and the 
surgeon's skill and experience.
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to overview</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</DOC>
