<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Background</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
<h3><strong>Anatomy</strong></h3>
<a href="glossary.html">Sperm</A> are produced in the male sex gland (<a href="glossary.html">testes</a>). From here 
they travel through tubes (<a href="glossary.html">efferent duct</a>s) to a "storage 
site" (<a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>). While being stored in the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>, the 
<a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> mature. <a href="glossary.html">Sperm</A> that come directly from the <a href="glossary.html">testes</a> without 
going to the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> first are not able to move and cannot 
fertilize eggs. It is only after passing through the 
<a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> that <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> gain their ability to move and fertilize eggs. 
From the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>, a muscular tube (vas) caries the <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> to 
the <a href="glossary.html">urethra</a>. The <a href="glossary.html">urethra</a> carries <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> to the end of the penis.
<p>
<img src="../images/repro.GIF" border=2>
<p>
<h3><strong><a href="glossary.html">Vasectomy</a>: Interrupting the <a href="glossary.html">Vas</a></strong></h3>
	The <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is a 14-inch muscular tube that propels the <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> 
into the <a href="glossary.html">ejaculatory duct</a> in the penis. After a <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> the <a href="glossary.html">testes</a> still produces <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a>, but due to the blockage, or 
interruption, in the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a>, the <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> die and are reabsorbed.
<p>
	The part of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> coming directly out of the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> is 
thin and tightly coiled. Farther on, the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> becomes thicker and eventually straightens. Surgery on the thick, straight 
portion of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is easier than on the thin, coiled part. Surgery on the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> is the most difficult.
<p>
	The <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> is one continuous, tightly coiled 15- to 18-foot tube. Any disease in any part of this tube may block 
the <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a>, keeping them from traveling along the reproductive track.
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to overview</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
</DOC>
