</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Surgical Options</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
<h3><strong><A Href="Glossary.Html">Vasectomy</A> Reversal</strong></h3>
	This procedure, first popular in the 1980s, utilizes a 
microscope, which magnifies the delicate structures up to 40 
times their actual size. While viewing through the 
microscope, the surgeon cuts away the scarred ends of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> (resulting 
from the previous <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a>). Fluid from the lower 
testicular end is then examined for the presence of <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a>. If <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> are 
present in the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> fluid, the surgeon realigns the freshened 
ends of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> and reconnects them with stitches finer than 
human hair. The most successful reverse <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> procedure 
is a two-layer technique shown in FIGURE 2.
<p>
<img src="../images/suropt1.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>A. Fluid from the proximal end of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is tested for presence of <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a>. Note discrepancy between distal and 
proximal inner openings of <a href="glossary.html">vas</a>.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/suropt2.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>B. Fine sutures reconnect inner openings of <a href="glossary.html">vas</a>.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/suropt3.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>C. <a href="glossary.html">Vas</a> is rotated 180 degrees and fine sutures complete the reconnection of the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a>.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/suropt4.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>D. Outer, muscular layer (second layer) of <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is connected.</em></strong></font>
<pre>

</pre>
<h3><strong><a href="glossary.html">Bypass Procedure</a></strong></h3>
If <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> are not present, the surgeon must decide whether to 
perform a reverse <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> or a <a href="glossary.html">bypass procedure 
(vasoepididymostomy)</a>. The longer it has been since the 
original <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a>, the greater the back-pressure behind the point at 
which the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> was interrupted (due to the blockage in the 
vas). This back-pressure may cause a "blowout" of the duct system 
at its weakest point, which is in the epididymal tube. If this 
single continuous tube breaks at any point, it becomes 
blocked at that point. In such a case, a reverse <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> would 
fail, because the <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> would be blocked in the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>. By 
using the <a href="glossary.html">bypass procedure</a>, the surgeon connects the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> to the 
single epididymal tube. The success rate of this procedure 
has improved remarkably during the last several years with the 
use of the end-to-side technique show in FIGURE 3.
<p>
<img src="../images/bypass1.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>A1. Small button of tissue is removed from <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>.</em></strong></font><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>A2. Opening is made inside single epididymal tube.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/bypass2.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>B. Outer muscular layer of vas is connected to outer layer 
of <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a>.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/bypass3.GIF" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>C. Inner layer of <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is connected to side of epididymal 
tube with fine sutures.</em></strong></font>
<p>
<img src="../images/bypass4.gif" align="center"><br>
<font size=-1><strong><em>D. Completed connection with cut end of <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> attached to 
single epididymal tube.</em></strong></font>
<pre>

</pre>
<h3><strong>Why a Reverse <A Href="Glossary.Html">Vasectomy</A> May Fail</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>Approximately 30 percent of men who have had vasectomies 
develop a reaction against their own <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> (<a href="glossary.html">sperm 
antibodies</a>). High levels of these antibodies may completely impair the 
patient's fertility or delay the onset of his partner's 
pregnancy. Treatment options include steroids, such as 
prednison, intra-uterine <a href="glossary.html">insemination</a>, or <a href="glossary.html">in vitro 
fertilization</a> (test tube baby).</li>
<li>Occasionally, scar tissue develops at the site where the 
<a href="glossary.html">vas</a> is reconnected, causing a blockage. This is rare and can 
usually be corrected with repeat surgery.</li>
<li>If a blowout has occurred and is not found, the reverse 
<a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> will fail. A <a href="glossary.html">bypass procedure</a> would need to be 
performed.</li>
<li>In certain patients, when the <a href="glossary.html">vas</a> has been blocked for a 
long time, the <a href="glossary.html">epididymis</a> is adversely affected. In these 
individuals, <a href="glossary.html">sperm count</a>s may be normal, but <a href="glossary.html">sperm</a> movement 
may be poor. Over time, most patients gradually recover from 
this epididymal dysfunction.</li>
</ul>
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to overview</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

