<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel <A Href="Glossary.Html">Vas</A>ectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>After Surgery</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
<h3><strong>Recovery</strong></h3>
	After surgery the patient will recover at home in bed for 24 
hours. A small amount of swelling in the <a href="glossary.html">scrotum</a> (sac below 
the penis), discomfort and bruising are normal. Infrequently, 
bleeding or infection may occur. The patient should remain 
home for two to three days and should be able to return to work 
on the third or fourth day. While sexual function remains 
normal, intercourse should be restricted for three weeks after 
surgery to promote healing. Also, the patient should avoid heavy 
physical activity at work or during sports for three weeks.
<p>
<h3><strong>Follow-Up</strong></h3>
	Initial <a href="glossary.html">semen</a> testing is obtained by masturbation six weeks 
after surgery and again three months after surgery. Patients 
should abstain from <a href="glossary.html">ejaculation</a> for three days prior to 
<a href="glossary.html">semen</a> testing.
<p>
<h3><strong>Conclusion</strong></h3>
	Because surgeons have a better understanding of the changes 
that occur in the <a href="glossary.html">testes</a> following a <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a>, they have 
been able to increase the success rates of <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> reversals. 
In addition, advances in equipment (microscope, instrument and 
stitches) have improved the technical success of this 
procedure.
<p>
<strong>For more information on <a href="glossary.html">vasectomy</a> reversals, contact:</strong><br>
<blockquote>
R. Dale McClure, M.D., F.R.C.S.(C).<br>
Department of Urology and Renal Transplantation<br>
Virginia Mason Clinic<br>
Seattle, Washington<br>
(206) 223-6772
</blockquote>
	R. Dale McClure, M.D., is Director of the Male Reproductive 
and <a href="glossary.html">Microsurgery</A> Unit at the Virginia Mason Clinic. He is a 
board-certified urologist, a Fellow of the Royal College of 
Surgeons of Canada, as well as a Fellow of the American 
College of Surgeons. Dr. McClure is a member of the American 
Fertility Society, the Society of Reproductive Surgeons, the American 
Andrology Society and the American Urological Association.
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to overview</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
