<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>VMMC Department of Urology - No Scalpel Vasectomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../images/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="../../images/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle">
<font size=+3><strong>Glossary</strong></font>
<p>
<table width=85%>
 <tr>
  <td width="80"><img src="../../images/blank.gif" alt="" width="80" height="1"></td>
</center>
  <td>
<strong>Efferent Duct</strong><br>
Several tubes that connect the testes to the first part of the epididymis.
<p>
<strong>Ejaculation</strong><br>
The expultion of semen from the urethra at the time of male climax.
<p>
<strong>Ejaculatory Duct</strong><br>
A duct formed by the joining of the seminal vesicle with the vas defernes.
<p>
<strong>Epididymis</strong><br>
A tightly coiled system of tiny tubing where sperm collect after leaving the testicle.  The epididymis covers the top and back side of the testicle.
<p>
<strong>Gynecologist</strong><br>
A medical doctor who specializes in disorders of the female reproductive tract.
<p>
<strong>Insemination</strong><br>
A technique used to artificially place sperm in either the female vagina at the opening of the cervix or the uterus itself (intra-uterine insemination).
<p>
<strong>In Vitro Fertilization</strong><br>
Assisted reproduction that involves surgically removing an egg from the woman's ovary and combining it with sperm in a laboratory dish.  If the egg is fertilized, the resulting embryo is transferred to the woman's uterus.
<p>
<strong>Microsurgery</strong><br>
Surgery performed while viewing through a microscope and using very delicate instruments.
<p>
<strong>Scrotum</strong><br>
A sac that lies below the penis containing the two oval sex glands in the male.
<p>
<strong>Semen</strong><br>
The sperm and glandular fluid that come out of the urethra when a man has a climax.
<p>
<strong>Semen Analysis</strong><br>
The examination of a semen sample for volume, count, motility and morphology.
<p>
<strong>Sperm</strong><br>
The male reproductive cell that fertilizes a woman's egg. The sperm head carries chromosomes; the mid-piece produces energy for movement; the long tail wiggles to propel the sperm.
<p>
<strong>Sperm Antibodies </strong><br>
Proteins that a male produces against his own sperm.
<p>
<strong>Sperm Count</strong><br>
The number of sperm per millimeter of semen.  A normal count is usually 20 million or more per millimeter.
<p>
<strong>Sperm Morphology</strong><br>
The shape of individual sperm as seen under a microscope.  At least 50% of the sperm in the semen sample should have oval heads and slightly curved tails.
<p>
<strong>Testicle (Testes)</strong><br>
Oval sex glands in the male that are suspended in the scrotum and produce sperm.
<p>
<strong>Urethra</strong><br>
The tube leading from the bladder and carrying both urine and semen to the end of the penis.
<p>
<strong>Vas (Vas Deferens)</strong><br>
The muscular tube that carries sperm from the epididymis to the urethra.
<p>
<strong>Vasectomy</strong><br>
Procedure in which the vas deferens is interrupted.  Usually a small portion of the vas is removed, and the ends are either cauterized or tied.
<p>
<strong>Vasoepididymostomy (Bypass Procedure)</strong><br>
The connection of the vas to the single epididymal tube.
<pre>

</pre>
<h4><em><a href="index.html">Back to index</a></em></h4>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

