<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>VMRC - Arthritis Clinical Research Unit - Dr. Daniel Furst</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; U) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Ron Klapperich">
   <META NAME="KeyWords" CONTENT="research, arthritis, schleraderma, clinic, drug, trial, pharmaceutical, pharmacology, pharmacokinetic, disease, pathogen, therapy, rheumatic, rheumatoid, FDA">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/vmbg.gif">

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/vmsqlog2.jpg" HSPACE=15 HEIGHT=101 WIDTH=100 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>

<TD align="left" nowrap><FONT SIZE=+2>Dr. Daniel Furst<BR>
Arthritis Clinical Research Unit<BR>
Virginia Mason Research Center/Medical Center<BR>
Seattle, Washington</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/danphoto.jpg" ALT="Portrait of Dr. Furst" HEIGHT=273 WIDTH=198>
</TD>

<TD valign="top"><FONT SIZE=+1>Musculoskeletal diseases are the most common
reason patients visit physicians offices. In that broad spectrum of illnesses,
osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis are the most common degenerative
and inflammatory musculaskeletal ailments, respectively. Systemic sclerosis,
in contrast, is an uncommon illness whose etiology remains a mystery but
whose prognosis is particularly grim.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD>
<H4><FONT SIZE=+1>Departmental goals of the Arthritis Clinical Research
Center:</FONT></H4>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>The Arthritis Clinical Research Unit is concentrating on the above
three rheumatic diseases with one of this unit's goal being to &quot;bring
the bench to the bedside&quot;. In the larger context of clinical pharmacology
and pharmacokinetics, the Arthritis Clinical Research Unit (ACRU) seeks:</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><FONT SIZE=+1>1. </FONT></TD>

<TD>To rationalize the therapy of rheumatic diseases, using the tools of
clinical pharmacology. At present rheumatic disease therapy relies principally
on an empiric base; with a better understanding of the pharmacology of
drugs used in the rheumatic diseases, it is hoped that more rational approaches
to rheumatic disease therapy will be possible. In this context the pharmacokinetics
and pharmacodynamics of therapy and disease, respectively, are being investigated.
Further, examining the interface between these two areas should make prediction
of therapeutic success and minimization of toxicity more likely.</TD>
</TR>

<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><FONT SIZE=+1>2.</FONT></TD>

<TD>To use medications such as genetically engineered proteins and xenobiotics
as probes of disease pathogenesis. With therapies whose mechanism of action
is quite specific (e.g., block IL-2 receptors, or prevent TNF action),
one can test specific mechanisms of disease pathogenesis.</TD>
</TR>

<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><FONT SIZE=+1>3.</FONT></TD>

<TD>To improve methods to measure change and compare relative efficacy/toxicity.
Without improved methodology, discerning the efficacy of a therapeutic
intervention becomes very difficult. The ACRU seeks to examine and improve
the methods to measure activity or change in rheumatoid arthritis, systemic
sclerosis and osteoarthritis.</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/PriorStudies.html">Click
here to see some of the studies we have done in the past.</A></FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/hr.gif" HEIGHT=4 WIDTH=400></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD>
<H3>ONGOING STUDIES<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+0>These studies are accruing new patients who want to be involved
with a pharmaceutical drug trial. The contact coordinator is listed for
each study, or you can contact Dr. Furst's office directly so you can be
included in our participant database for accruing studies.</FONT></H3>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/ProsorbaStudy.html">PROSORBA
COLUMN TREATMENT FOR RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS</A></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>TNFR:FC</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>FK506</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/acru/hr.gif" HEIGHT=4 WIDTH=400></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD>
<TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD><B><FONT SIZE=+1>CONTACTING THE ACRU:<BR>
</FONT>You can call the office directly, or you can fill out a simple questionaire
about your medical history to help us determine which study best matches
your medical profile.</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=+1>Click here for the medical history form. <B>[coming
soon]</B></FONT></P></CENTER>

<TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><B>Mail:</B></TD>

<TD><FONT SIZE=+1>Dr. Daniel Furst<BR>
Virginia Mason Research Center<BR>
1000 Seneca Street<BR>
Seattle, WA 98101</FONT></TD>
</TR>

<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><B>Phone:</B></TD>

<TD><FONT SIZE=+1>(206) 223-6836</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><A HREF="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/research.html">Research at VMRC<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/vmrc.html">VMRC Home</A> </P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

