<tr>
<td width="40"><img src="images/blank.gif" alt="" width="40" height="1"></td>
<td>
<PRE>


</PRE>
<CENTER>
<h2>The Research Center at Virginia Mason</h2>
World-class medical research focused on diagnosing,<BR>
treating, and curing auto-immune diseases.
<P>

<b>AN INVITATION TO BE A PARTNER IN THE CREATION<BR>
OF LIFE-SAVING KNOWLEDGE.</b>
</CENTER>
<p>
<blockquote>
<B>S</B>upporting medical research is one of the most rewarding of all philanthropic
activities. As your gift leads to breakthroughs in understanding the
fundamental nature of a disease, you will literally have helped add new
knowledge to the medical community.
<p>
This knowledge can lead to earlier diagnosis, more effective treatment, and
ultimately <em>a cure for a disease.</em> When this occurs, countless generations of
people will benefit from an advancement you helped make possible.
<p>
We invite you to join our research efforts at the Virginia Mason Research
Center and discover how rewarding it can be to help save lives.
<p>
<CENTER>
<b>RESPECTED INTERNATIONALLY AMONG ITS PEERS,<BR>
THE VIRGINIA MASON RESEARCH CENTER<BR>
IS COMPRISED OF A WORLD-CLASS TEAM.</b>
</CENTER>
<p>
<B>A</B>t Virginia Mason Research Center (VMRC), our scientists target disease at its
core -- at the molecular and cellular level. Our researchers focus on the human
body's immune system to determine genetic patterns, links, and codes in the
hope of interrupting the pattern to prevent the onset of disease.
<p>
By focusing on the cellular biology of the human immune system, VMRC has built
depth and expertise in diseases of the human immune system, such as diabetes,
rheumatoid arthritis, lupus and cancer.
<p>
In addition to VMRC's core staff of principle investigators, post-doctoral
scientists, and pre-doctoral and technical staff members, our scientists work
hand-in-hand with their physician colleagues at Virginia Mason Medical Center
on almost 100 ongoing research projects focusing on diabetes, heart, arthritis,
cancer, ataxia, lupus, and other diseases. These clinical trials focus on
turning "basic scientce" breakthroughs into practical applications for patients
-- bringing the benefits of medical research from "bench to bedside."
<p>
To expand the impact of this work even further, VMRC scientists collaborate
with universities throughout the United States, as well as with local
biotechnology companies and medical researchers at Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Center and the University of Washington.
<p>
<em>VMRC invites you to join this workd-class team</em> and help us to find cures for
diseases sometimes  considered hopeless.
<p>
<CENTER>
<b>A PROVEN TRACK RECORD:<BR>
<em>HARD WORK, INNOVATION AND RESULTS.</em></b>
</CENTER>
<p>
<B>R</B>esearch at Virginia Mason began in the 1920s. For the first three decades,
much of that research took the form of clinical reports and statistical
analyses. In the early 1950s, a team of distinguised scientists, physicians and
leaders founded the Virginia Mason Research Center for focus on basic research.
In recent years VMRC researchers have identified genes that contribute to
diabetes and arthritis and are working on disease prevention. 
<p>
<b><em>Highlights of recent VMRC accomplishments and awards include:</em></b>
<p>
<b><em>1995</em></b>  The National Institutes of Health and the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation
International name VMRC as one of only eight centers worldwide to receive their
Centers of Excellence Award for VMRC's diabetes research program.
<p>
<b><em>1994</em></b>  The National Institutes of Health appoint Dr. Gerald Nepom, VMRC's
Director, as chairperson of NIH's prestigious Immunological Sciences Review
Group.
<p>
<b><em>1993</em></b>  The Juvenile Diabetes Foundation gives its Living and Giving Award to Dr.
Gerald Nepom in recognition of VMRC's breakthoughs in the genetics of diabetes
and Dr. Nepom's leadership of VMRC's internationally-known research program.
<p>
<b><em>1992</em></b>  A new inpatient clinical research unit is established at Virginia Mason
Medical Center.
<p>
<b><em>1991</em></b>  VMRC researchers discover the blueprint that will lead to attempts to
"switch off" the gene that makes some people susceptible to diabetes.
<p>
<b><em>1989</em></b>  VMRC scientists identify an important genetic marker for the most
prevalent form of juvenile rheumatoid arthritis.
<p>
<b><em>1989</em></b>  In 3 major publications, VMRC scientists describe for the first time the
use of genetic engineering techniques to manipulate and modify the function of
molecules that account for susceptibility in diabetes.
<p>
These and many other scientific breakthoughs at VMRC have meant a vast
improvement in the quality of life for thousands of people. With your help,
VMRC will continue to search for the causes and cures of mahy disabling
auto-immune diseases.
<p>
<CENTER><b>YOUR GIFTS CAN HELP CARRY ON THIS IMPORTANT WORK.</b></CENTER>
<p>
<B>C</B>ontriubutions to the Virginia Mason Research Center support:
<p>
<b><em>Scientists</em></b>
<p>
Our most valuable resource, with their spirit of innovative inquiry at the
heart of our advancements.
<p>
<b><em>Visiting scientists</em></b>
<p>
Visiting scientists aid the exchange of information and speed discoveries.
<p>
<b><em>Educational programs</em></b>
<p>
VMRC researchers share their knowledge through educational programs for
patients at VMMC's Benaroya Diabetes Center and through teaching programs at
the Virginia Mason Medical Center and the University of Washington.
<p>
<b><em>Modern equipment</em></b>
<p>
The precision and exactness of science require specialized equipment that can
be purchased only with philanthropic support.
<p>
<b><em>Supplies</em></b>
<p>
On-going supplies, such as radioisotopes, are in axpensive but indispensable
part of today's medical research.
<p>
<b><em>Databases</em></b>
<p>
Maintaining VMRC's linkages with computerized research databases worldwide
speeds discoveries and eliminates duplication of research efforts. 
<p>
<CENTER><b>YOUR GIFTS ARE ESPECIALLY IMPORTANT RIGHT NOW.</b></CENTER>
<p>
<B>A</B>s a non-profit medical research center, VMRC relies on the generosity of
individual, corporate, and foundation donors to provide the critucal funding
necessary to purchase state-of-the-art equipment, to create endowed support
funds and chairs to retain top researchers , and to support research costs.
<p>
The National Institutes of Health and National Cancer Institutes, which have
supported much of VMRC's ground-breaking research, are facing reduced budgets
-- just at the time when medical researchers are making the most promising
breakthroughs! Your help is needed to enable Virginia Mason to continue these
life-saving medical advances.
<p>
<b>Virginia Mason Research Center Chapter</b>
<p>
Gifts of $125 or more annually qualify donors for membership in the Virginia
Mason Research Center Chapter, with special invitations to research briefings
and educational forums.
<p>
A wide variety of donor recognition opportunities, ranging from recognition in
the Annual Report, to listing on VM's donor walls, to named endowed research
chairs, to named laboratories, are available. Please call the Virginia Mason
Foundation at (206) 583-6083 for further information.
<p>
Thank you for supporting Virginia Mason Research Center.
<p>
</blockquote>
<CENTER>
<P>
