<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMRC - Gerald T. Nepom</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="graphics/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%">
<tr><td><img hspace="15" src="graphics/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="left" nowrap><font size="5">Virginia Mason Research Center<br>
Gerald T. Nepom</font></td></tR></table><p>

<center>

<table border="0">

<TR>

<td>
<img src="graphics/lggn.jpg"><p>
</td>

<TD valign="top">
Although we know that HLA genes are implicated in 
many autoimmune diseases, we do not yet understand 
the molecular mechanisms responsible 
for such genetic associations.  Nor do we understand 
how to use this information to design better 
diagnostics, prognostics, and therapeutics for clinical 
applications.  In my laboratory, we use a combined 
structural, genetic, and functional approach to study 
the interaction between MHC molecules, peptides, 
and T cell recognition, focused on the HLA molecules 
associated with autoimmune disease.  We would like 
to understand what are the unique features which lead 
to the expression and function of these molecules 
contributing to autoimmunity, and gain some practical 
insight into opportunities to modulate or block the 
specific molecular pathways in disease pathogenesis.
</td>


</tr>
</table>
<p>
<img src="graphics/hr.gif">
<p>


<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<h3>PROJECTS</h3>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<b>HLA and disease.</b><br>
Vivian Gersuk, Sharon Kochik, Susan Masewicz, 
Helena Reijonen, Niecey Meldrum<p>

Identification of specific HLA genes associated with autoimmune diseases 
such as diabetes and rheumatoid arthritis leads to a series of hypotheses 
and predictions about disease mechanisms and clinical course.  We are 
investigating the use of HLA genetics as predictive markers of disease 
progression and prediction, and using HLA genetics to stratify patients 
for further studies of disease mechanisms and response to therapy.  We are 
developing rapid DNA diagnostics for routine clinical use to help improve 
differential diagnosis, prognosis, and selection of therapy.<P>

<b>Transcriptional regulation of class II genes.</b><br>
Jon Beaty, Linda Shewey, Teresa Sukiennicki<p>

HLA genes are polymorphic.  That is, they exist in multiple allelic forms 
in the population.  We investigate the structural and functional 
consequences of polymorphisms in the coding region (see below), but we 
also have discovered and are investigating DNA polymorphisms in the 
promoter and regulatory regions of these genes.  Regulatory region 
polymorphisms modify specific DNA protein interactions which modulate 
transcriptional levels.  Thus, the unique ways in which specific HLA genes 
are transcriptionally regulated may provide important clues to understand 
gene inducibility, tissue specificity, and expression in immune-mediated 
and autoimmune diseases.  A multidisciplinary approach is used for these 
investigations, including analysis of DNA-protein binding interactions, 
reporter gene transcriptional assays, measurements of endogenous gene 
expression, and analysis of functional consequences of disregulated gene 
transcription.<P>

<b>The MHC peptide complex as a flexible structural unit for T cell 
recognition.</b><br>
Jane Buckner, Mary Ellen Domeier, Ben Falk<P>

The principal known function of HLA class II molecules is to bind and 
present peptides for T cell recognition.  This is accomplished by specific 
molecular interactions within a binding pocket on the HLA class II 
molecule which recognizes specific amino acid side chains on peptides 
generated during antigen processing.  The unique genetic polymorphisms 
which characterize disease associated class II molecules create a set of 
distinct motifs for binding to some but not all possible peptides.  We are 
characterizing the structural rules which control this interaction and 
using it to predict and analyze the nature of the HLA-peptide complex in 
autoimmune diseases.<P>

<b><a href="gnpubs.html">Publications</a><P>
<a href="http://nucleus.immunol.washington.edu/Graduate_program/Faculty/nepom_res.html">
Gerald Nepom's page at the University of Washington</a></b><P>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<img src="graphics/hr.gif"><P>

<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr><td>
<a href="research.html">Research at VMRC</a><br>
<a href="vmrc.html">VMRC Home</a>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
