<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMRC - Eric C. B. Milner</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="graphics/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%">
<tr><td><img hspace="15" src="graphics/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="left" nowrap><font size="5">Virginia Mason Research Center<br>
Eric C. B. Milner</font></td></tR></table><p>

<center>

<table border="0">

<TR>

<td valign=top>
<img src="graphics/lgem.jpg"><p>
</td>

<TD valign="top">
Studies in my laboratory address questions aimed at understanding how 
the human B cell repertoire is generated and selected, with the intent 
of asking how variation in the B cell compartment contributes to 
disease resistance or susceptibility. Recent observations made in 
the laboratory are that 1) the number of heavy chain variable region 
(VH) genes contributing to the adult repertoire is smaller than generally 
thought, and the VH3 and VH4 components of the repertoire are dominated by 
a few elements, 2) the antibody repertoire is limited to a relatively few 
elements as early as the pre-B cell stage of differentiation, 3) bone 
marrow transplant recipients exhibit a markedly reduced level of somatic 
mutation that is consistent with a maturational arrest at a fairly late 
stage of differentiation. Current efforts are addressing questions that 
have arisen during the course of this work and which concern somatic 
diversification of the repertoire.
</td>


</tr>
</table>
<p>
<img src="graphics/hr.gif">
<p>


<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<h3>PROJECTS</h3>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>

<b><a href="empubs.html">Publications</a><P>
<a href="http://nucleus.immunol.washington.edu/Graduate_program/Faculty/milner_res.html">
Eric Milner's page at the University of Washington</a></b><P>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<img src="graphics/hr.gif"><P>

