<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMRC - Barbara S. Nepom</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="graphics/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%">
<tr><td><img hspace="15" src="graphics/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="left" nowrap><font size="5">Virginia Mason Research Center<br>
Barbara S. Nepom</font></td></tR></table><p>

<center>

<table border="0">

<TR>

<td valign="top">
<img src="graphics/lgbn.jpg" ><p>
</td>

<TD valign=top>
Research in Dr. Barbara Nepom's laboratory is focused on HLA class II genes
and their contribution to the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases, 
particularly adult and juvenile rheumatoid arthritis. Current studies are 
directed towards understanding the structural requirements for antigen
binding to disease-associated polymorphic HLA molecules. Antigens which may
be relevant to the initiation and maintenance of adult and juvenile
rheumatoid arthritis are also under investigation. Other studies include
the transcriptional regulation of HLA-DRB genes, particularly disease-associated
alleles; and investigation of factors allowing "non-professional antigen 
presenting cells", such as breast cancer cells, to become immunologically 
functional.
</td>


</tr>
</table>
<p>
<img src="graphics/hr.gif">
<p>


<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<h3>PROJECTS</h3>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<b>Triggering antigens in juvenile rheumatoid arthritis</b><br>

Laboratory contributors:<br>
Pauciarticular onset juvenile rheumatoid arthritis is the most common
pediatric rheumatic disease, and accounts for significant morbidity from 
both musculoskeletal and ocular complications. The etiology is unknown. 
Unique and complex HLA associations with this condition include DR8, DR5, 
and DPB2.1. Some evidence of oligoclonal T cell receptor usage is also
emerging. The triggering antigen, however, remains a crucial factor in 
disease pathogenesis about which very little is known. We are utilizing
molecular approaches to begin to identify such antigen(s) in pauciarticular
JRA. Specifically, we are detailing the structural requirements for peptides
which bind well to disease-associated alleles, using molecular modeling and 
experimental peptide binding assays. Using those motifs, we will identify 
potential binding peptides from known sequences of candidate triggering 
antigens and test these directly for binding. As a complementary approach,
we are attempting to identify DR8- and DR5-binding peptides that are 
expressed in JRA synovial samples, using novel molecular expression methods.
Finally, we plan to test these peptides directly for reactivity with patient
synovial T cells. This project tackles a critical gap in our understanding
of this disease, and potentially will provide the basis for novel 
therapeutic or preventive strategies.

<P>



<b><a href="bnpubs.html">Publications</a></b><P>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<img src="graphics/hr.gif"><P>

<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr><td>
<a href="research.html">Research at VMRC</a><br>
<a href="vmrc.html">VMRC Home</a>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
