</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VMRC - William W. Kwok</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="graphics/vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%">
<tr><td><img hspace="15" src="graphics/vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="left" nowrap><font size="5">Virginia Mason Research Center<br>
William W. Kwok</font></td></tR></table><p>

<center>

<table border="0">

<TR>

<td>
<img src="graphics/lgbk.jpg"><p>
</td>

<TD valign=top>
Studies in Dr. Kwok's laboratory are focused on two areas: (1) Structural 
polymorphism of the HLA-DQ molecule is implicated in the pathogenesis of 
autoimmune diseases, including IDDM. Binding of diabetogenic peptides to 
highly polymorphic DQ molecules may trigger the initial events that lead 
to the disease. Peptide binding studies are used to identify specific
peptide motifs. The ability of these DQ-peptide complexes to initiate DQ
restricted T cell activation is also investigated. (2) The study of molecular
mechanisms of T cell unresponsiveness includes biological stimuli that lead
to partial T cell responses and biochemical pathways that lead to 
unresponsiveness.

</td>


</tr>
</table>
<p>
<img src="graphics/hr.gif"><p>

<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<h3>PROJECTS</h3>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><b>The DQ-peptide/TcR complex in DQ associated autoimmune diseases.</b>
<P>

The principle function of class II molecule is to bind and present 
antigenic peptide. Structural polymorphism of the DQ molecule will affect 
peptide binding and thereby influencing the potential immune repertoire.  
Analysis  of the ability of DQ molecules to bind and present antigenic 
peptide should aid in understand the role in immunity and in development 
of HLA-DQ-associated autoimmune disease. In the case of IDDM, it is 
proposed that binding of a diabetogenic peptide to the DQ3.2 molecule 
trigger the initial events that lead to the disease.<P>

However, the nature of this diabetogenic peptide remained unidentified. 
Identification of the DQ3.2 ligand is critical for understanding the 
pathogenesis of IDDM.   Binding assay will be established to examine the 
effect of  DQ polymorphism on peptide binding. Peptide analogs will be 
used to establish the binding motif of  DQ3.2  binding peptides. Peptides 
with the predicted motifs from potential autoantigens will be synthesized. 
The ability of these peptides to function as antigenic peptide will be 
examined. T cells that recognize this DQ/peptide complex will be generated 
and characterized.  Similar approaches can be extended to predicted DQ 
restricted T cell epitopes of other DQ alleles. These studies address an 
important and poorly understood area of immunogenetics and diabetes, 
namely, the specific nature of peptides with are preferentially bound to 
DQ molecules associated with disease. This information is essential for 
the rational design of immunotherapeutic directed at the trimolecular 
complex in IDDM.<P>

<b>Molecular Mechanism for T cell unresponsiveness.</b><P>

T cell receptor engagement with an MHC/peptide complex does not necessary 
lead to induction of IL-2 secretion and T cell proliferation.  A wide 
spectrum of response can be observed. These included  T cell anergy, 
apoptosis or partial T cell activation.  Our focus will be the 
identification of MHC/peptide complex that can induce T cell 
unresponsiveness in human T cells. We proposed that both peptide analogs 
and mutagenized class II molecules can induce T cell unresponsiveness. 
The biochemical pathways that lead to the generation of a negative signal 
which triggers unresponsiveness will also be identified.
<P>


<b><a href="bkpubs.html">Publications</a></b><P>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<img src="graphics/hr.gif"><P>

<table width="80%" border=0>
<tr><td>
<a href="research.html">Research at VMRC</a><br>
<a href="vmrc.html">VMRC Home</a>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
</body>
</html>

