<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Virginia Mason Research Center</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY background="graphics/atmback.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<center>
<h1>Welcome to the Ataxia-Telangiectasia Mutation Database</h1>
<img src="graphics/atm.gif">
</center>

<b>


<ul>

<li><h3><a href="atmtab.txt">ATM mutations detected in AT patients</a></h3>
These are alterations observed in AT patients which are likely to be deleterious to ATM function (e.g. truncation mutations).
<a href="graphics/atmut.gif">Distribution of mutations by exon</a> - 
Feel free to download this figure, but please acknowledge the source by not deleting the website address in the corner.<P>

<li><h3><a href="atmcarr.txt">ATM mutations in carriers</a></h3>
These are alterations known to be, or likely to be, deleterious to ATM function that have been observed in individuals without a family history of AT.
This category would typically include mutations detected by population screening, as, for example, in breast cancer patients.
<P>
<li><h3><a href="atmpoly.txt">ATM polymorphisms/variants</a></h3>
These include nucleotide substitutions and other alterations in the ATM gene that have been observed in individuals without a family history of AT where the predicted effect is not obviously deleterious.<P>
</ul>

<h3><a href="tabinfo.htm">Explanation of the tables</a></h3><P>

<h3><a href="atminfo.htm">Information about ataxia-telangiectasia</a></h3><P>

<h3><a href="atmseq.txt">Nucleotide sequence of the ATM gene</a></h3>
<P>

We will attempt to the keep the information on this website as accurate and up to date as possible.
If you find errors, have questions, or wish to contribute new mutations (which we would be happy to hold confidential until publication), please contact one of the curators:
<blockquote><a href="mailto:patcon@u.washington.edu">Pat Concannon, Ph.D.</a><br>
Virginia Mason Research Center<br>
Seattle, Washington 98101<P>
<a href="mailto:rgatti@pathology.medsch.ucla.edu">Richard A. Gatti, M.D.</a><br>
Department of Pathology<br>
UCLA School of Medicine
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h3>Other Web Resources</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://ww2.med.jhu.edu/ataxia/">AT Children's Project</a><P>
<li><a href="http://www.graylab.ac.uk/cancernet/600349.html">National Cancer Institute</a><P>
<li><a href="atmrf.htm">The Ataxia-Telangiectasia Medical Research Foundation</a><P>
<li><a href="http://www.familyvillage.wisc.edu/lib_attl.htm">The Family Village</a><P>
<li><a href="http://www3.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov:80/htbin-post/Omim/dispmim?208900">The OMIM reference for AT</a><P>
</ul>


<hr>
This page supported by <a href="http://www.vmmc.org/vmrc/vmrc.html">Virginia Mason Research Center</a> and the AT Medical Research Foundation.







</b>

</body>
</html>
