<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Virginia Mason Research Center</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY background="graphics/atmback.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<b>

<map name="arrow">
<area shape="poly" coords="34,42 36,44, 217,98 215,41" href="#ataxia">
<area shape="poly" coords="286,39 289,98 496,94 490,39" href="#cancer">
<area shape="poly" coords="5,134 6,210 201,213 200,137" href="#pulmon">
<area shape="poly" coords="12,244 11,329 224,327 229,254" href="#chrom">
<area shape="poly" coords="335,136 338,204 544,209 544,130" href="#radio">
<area shape="poly" coords="299,253 298,312 522,320 517,252" href="#cycle">
</map>

<center>
<h2>THE A-T SYNDROME</h2>
<img src="graphics/arrow.gif" width="550" height="368" usemap="#arrow">
</center>
<P>


The ataxia-telangiectasia (A-T) syndrome varies little from family to family when seen in its late stages.  Its primary features include: 
1) progressive gait and truncal ataxia with onset from 1 to 3 years of age, 
2) progressively slurred speech, 
3) oculomotor apraxia, i.e., an 
inability to follow an object across the visual fields, 
4) oculocutaneous 
telangiectasia, usually by six years of age, 
5) an elevated serum 
alphafetoprotein, 
6) frequent infections, with accompanying serum and 
cellular immunodeficiencies, 
7) cancer susceptibility, usually leukemia 
or lymphoma,  
8) hypersensitivity to ionizing radiation, contraindicating the use of conventional doses of radiation therapy for cancer and 
9) reciprocal translocations that involve chromosomes 7 and 14 almost exclusively.  Other features include premature aging and endocrine 
abnormalities.  This figure highlights some of the major features of 
this complex syndrome and its underlying pathogenesis.  The information 
that follows is excerpted from "Metabolic and Molecular Basis of Inherited 
Disease" Seventh Edition.  Eds. CR Scriver, AL Beaudet, WS Sly, and 
D Valle.  McGraw-Hill, publishers.  New York 1996 (also available on CD-ROM).
Readers interested in more detailed information about the syndrome and 
relevant references should consult this source.<P>  

<a name="ataxia">
<h3>Ataxia</h3></a>
The most obvious and troubling characteristic of the A-T syndrome is the 
progressive cerebellar ataxia.  Shortly after learning to walk, A-T 
children begin to stagger  By ten years of age, they are confined to a 
wheelchair for the remainder of their lives.  The ataxia begins as purely 
truncal but within several years involves peripheral coordination as well.  
Deep tendon reflexes are decreased or absent in older patients; plantar 
reflexes are upgoing or absent. Slurred speech and oculomotor apraxia are 
noted early on.  Both horizontal and vertical saccadic eye movements are 
affected.  Writing is affected by 7 or 8 years of age.  Choreoathetosis is 
found in almost all patients.  Myclonic jerking  and  intention tremors 
are present in about 25%.   Drooling is a frequent complaint; this can 
sometimes be helped with medication. All teenage patients need help 
dressing, eating, washing, and toiletting.  The neurological status of 
some patients appears to improve from 2-4 years, then begins to progress 
again; this is probably due to the rapid neurological learning curve of 
young individuals.  Muscle power is normal at first but wanes with disuse, 
especially of the legs.  Arm strength generally remains.  Contractures in 
fingers and toes are common in older patients but may be preventable 
through rigorous exercise. <P>

The typical patient with A-T is of normal intelligence, although slow 
responses make it difficult to support this by timed IQ testing.  Many 
American and British patients have finished high school with good grades; 
some have finished college or university.  A few do seem minimally retarded.<P>

The most obvious lesion in the central nervous system at port-mortem 
examination is the paucity of Purkinje cells (PC) in the cerebellum.  
About ten years ago, we wished to determine whether these cells were 
absent from birth or whether they degenerate thereafter.  Knowing that 
Basket cells only form around preexisting PC, we sought to visualize 
Basket cells by Bielschowsky silver staining.  We showed that normal or 
near-normal numbers of Basket cells were present.  We concluded, 
therefore, that PC numbers must also have been normal at birth and that 
they degenerate after birth. <P> 

PC migration and arborization are not completely normal.  A significant 
number of ectopic PC can be found in cerebellar sections from A-T 
patients, both from undermigration and overmigration.  PC make their last 
cell division at about 13 weeks of gestation and then begin to migrate 
towards the pial surface.  Following the tracts of climbing fibers, they 
arrive at the single cell PC layer during the fifth to seventh months of 
gestation.  Thus, this lesion of ectopic PCs would most likely be 
expressed by the last trimester of pregnancy.  This is the earliest known 
manifestation of the A-T defect.<P>  	

It remains possible that PCs are not the primary A-T lesion and that the 
observed PC defects are due to other factors, such as an absence or 
abnormalities of supporting cells like Basket cells, mossy fibers, 
parallel fibers, climbing fibers or glial cells.  Anteriograde or 
retrograde degeneration of PCs would then occur, with the underlying 
lesion being either afferent or efferent to the PCs.  We have recently 
been able to demonstrate the presence of ATM message in PCs, as well as in 
cells of the internal and external granular layers, and in neurons of the 
dentate nucleus.  We see ATM mRNA in both healthy and affected tissues.  
Even mRNAs containing serious ATM mutations are apparently stable in A-T 
cells.  Thus, the primary site of action for the ATM protein in the 
cerebellum remains undetermined at this writing.<P>  

Changes have also been noted in the dentate and olivary nuclei. 	
The medulla shows neuroaxonal dystrophy.  Degenerative changes are seen in 
the substantia nigra.  Diffuse demyelination in the posterior columns of 
the spinal cord was noted in some of the original autopsies and is a 
progressive change.  For further details of post-mortem changes in A-T 
patients, the two lengthy reviews authored by Segdwick and Boder in the 
Handbook of Neurology should be consulted.<P>

Throughout the tissues of the body of A-T patients, nucleomegaly is a 
universal finding.  This is best seen in organs where nuclear morphology 
is usually very regular, such as in the hepatic cords or renal tubules.  
Here, it is obvious that the size of the nucleus is extremely variable in 
A-T tissues, as compared to normal.  Some nuclei are very large, 
hyperchromatic (dark-staining) and irregular in shape.  Nucleomegaly  is 
also seen in association with aging and in viral lesions.  However, 
numerous studies have failed to demonstrate virus or viral particles, 
including an attempt by Gadjusek to inoculate primates with brain tissue 
extracts from two A-T patients.  It is entirely possible that the 
nucleomegaly seen in A-T tissues results from defective cell cycle 
checkpoints leading to mitotic division without cell replication in 
random cells.  Naeim et al  have demonstrated polyploidy (4N and 8N) in 
lymphoblastoid cell lines (LCLs) from A-T patients by flow cytometric 
cell-cycle analysis.<P>  
	

<h3>Telangiectasia</h3>

Telangiectasia are composed of dilated small blood vessels that can be 
observed over the ocular conjunctiva, the bridge of the nose, the pinnae 
of the ears, or sometimes even behind the knees or in the ancubital 
fossae.  Telangiectasiae do not usually appear until 4-6 years of age, 
well after the onset of ataxia in most cases.  In a few families, 
telangiectasia is not apparent even in older patients with all of the 
other characteristic signs and symptoms of the disease.<P> 

<a name="pulmon">
<h3>Pulmonary Infections</h3></a>

At post-mortem examination, virtually every A-T homozygote has a small 
embryonic-like thymus.  In the late 1960s and again in the early 1980s, 
many attempts were made to characterize the immunodeficiencies of A-T 
patients.  No single consistent abnormality could be identified in all A-T 
patients affected sibs often differ in the degree and profile of their 
immunodeficiencies.  In a recent review of British patients, Woods and 
Taylor noted normal immunological function in 27 of 70 patients.  
Only 10% had severe immunodeficiencies.<P>  

When the genomic arrangement of the IGH V, D, J and H gene subfamilies was 
first described, we noted that the immunoglobulin (Ig) classes that were 
most frequently decreased in A-T patients were those with the greatest 
distances between the variable genes and the respective heavy chain genes; 
roughly 60-80 percent of A-T homozygotes manifest an IgA, IgE and/or IgG2 
deficiency, whereas serum levels of IgM, IgG1 and IgG3 are usually normal.  
This suggests that B cells from these patients have a maturational problem 
with Ig class switching, perhaps based on a recombinase deficiency.  On a 
similar note, an increased proportion of T gamma/delta cells noted in one 
early study suggested a maturational delay in T cells; however, this was 
before normal T gamma/delta cell ranges had been clearly defined and has 
not been generally confirmed.  IgM levels are occasionally extremely high; 
this could be based on a similar defective maturational mechanism that 
arrests some B cells at the IgM-producing stage.  On the other hand, when 
V(D)J recombination was examined in A-T cells, both signal and coding joint 
formation were normal.<P>  

Approximately half of A-T patients with immunodeficiencies have T cell 
deficiencies.  CD4+/CD45RA+ (naive) T cells are decreased in some patients.
Responses to antigens are poor, especially allogeneic antigens.  T cell 
cytotoxicity to influenza-infected target cells is reduced.  T lymphocytes 
show abnormally fast capping of FITC-labelled Concanavalin A.  Markedly 
elevated cyclic AMP levels have been observed in T cells from A-T patients.
Neutrophil chemotaxis was reported to be decreased in some studies and 
normal in others.  Similarly, NK cell activity and NK cell levels have 
been described as normal, decreased, or increased in various studies.  
Some of these discrepancies no doubt reflect the transient immune status 
of patients with active infections.   Although 91% of Costa Rican A-T 
patients had diminished PHA responses, recall that 65% of this patient 
cohort have the same mutation; thus, this sample would be skewed against 
some features and in favor of others and these might have little bearing 
on patients around the world with other mutations.  Further analyses of 
this cohort are underway.<P>

<a name="chrom">
<h3>Chromosomal changes</h3></a>

A-T homozygotes show non-random chromosomal aberrations in lymphocytes, 
such as translocations and inversions, which preferentially involve 
chromosomal breakpoints at 14q11, 14q32, 7q35, 7p14, 2p11 and 22q11.  
These appeared to correlate generally with the regions of the T cell 
receptor (TCR alpha, beta, and gamma) and B cell receptor (IGH, IGK and IGL)
gene complexes.  Since these six sites contain the only gene complexes in 
the genome that are known to require site specific gene 
rearrangement/recombination prior to expressing a mature protein, it was 
logical to examine V(D)J recombination mechanisms in A-T cells.  As noted 
above, signal and coding joint formation are both normal.  When we 
examined the chromosomes of fibroblasts from eight A-T homozygotes, all 
with typical 7:14 translocations in their lymphocytes, the fibroblast 
aberrations were totally random.  In addition, Hecht studied almost 50,000 
amniotic fluid cell metaphases; of 37 translocations in that sample, none 
involved chromosomes 7 and 14.  This is intriguing when one also considers 
that fibroblasts and amniotic cells do express the radiosensitivity defect.
Heterozygotes show t(7;14) translocations in lymphocytes but only in 1-2% 
of metaphases.<P>

In some patients, cell clones with the above breakpoints expand, sometimes 
accounting for 100% of the lymphocytes that are karyotyped.  Despite this, 
lymphocyte counts remain within normal range for years thereafter.  
Some of these clones have been followed for 10 to 20 years, by us and by 
others.  These clones tend to progress, with subclones adding new 
rearrangements, such as: inv(14;14)(q11;q32), i(8q), and 6q-, in addition 
to many other smaller clones.  Eventually, such patients develop T cell 
prolymphocytic leukemia (T-PLL), previously referred to as T-CLL (T cell 
chronic lymphoblastic leukemia).  Affected sibs are usually not concordant 
for developing such clones.<P>

These clonal expansions have recently allowed the breakpoint sites to be 
analyzed by molecular techniques.  Three types of patients have been 
studied:  1) A-T patients with non-leukemic clones, 2) A-T patients with 
leukemic clones, and 3) non-AT patients with similar cytogenetic 
translocations and T-PLL.  Thanks to many years of perseverance by Taylor 
and coworkers in trying to pinpoint the breakpoints of these 
translocations or inversions, a fascinating story is now emerging that is 
quite similar to that of myc in Burkitt lymphoma.  The A-T expanded clones 
always involve one of the TCR sites, usually TCR-alpha, being juxtaposed 
to another family of genes that are located proximal, but not actually 
within, the B cell receptor gene complexes.  The most common and best 
studied translocations are those involving 14q11 (TCR-alpha) and a 
breakpoint cluster region ~10 Mb proximal to the IGH locus at 14q32.  
Within ~400 kb, at least eight such breakpoints have been identified in 
A-T patients with and without leukemia, and in several non-AT patients 
with T-PLL.  This region centers around the TCL-1 (T cell leukemia-1) 
gene, the 1.3 kb transcript of which is preferentially expressed in 
immature (and leukemic) B and T cells.  Circulating mature lymphocytes do 
not express this gene.  Leukemia cells without the t(14;14 or inv(14;14) 
do not express TCL-1.<P>

An occasional A-T patient has a large t(X;14)(q28;q11) clone, including at 
least two who have developed T-CLL/T-PLL, and one without leukemia when 
last studied.  The breakpoints at Xq28 cluster to within a few kilobases, 
in a region of ~70 kb proximal to the Factor VIII gene.  This region 
contains the genes c6.1A and c6.1B.   The latter gene is believed to be 
the crucial one in these translocations since two of the breakpoints fall 
within the first exon of c6.1B (also know as MTCP1 for "mature T cell 
proliferation-1").  Most interesting, c6.1B has homology with TCL-1 (40% 
identity; 60% similarity) and is a mitochondrial protein .  TCL-1 and 
MTCP-1 also share three-dimensional structure.  TCL-1 prevents apoptosis 
and is p53 independent.  Since TCR/TCL-1 translocations do not by 
themselves cause leukemia, another factor must interact with the protein 
product(s) resulting from the translocations.  This factor could very well 
be the ATM gene product.  If this proves true, it would suggest that 
non-AT patients with T-PLL may also be A-T heterozygotes in whom the 
normal ATM gene has been disabled or deleted, as in a "two-hit model".<P>
	
Constitutional cytogenetic defects involving translocations or deletions 
at 11q22-23 have not been observed in A-T homozygotes, even though 
karyotypes of >500 patients have been examined worldwide.  Many 
cytogenetic reports on children with suspected A-T return: "insufficient 
metaphases for analysis".   This is because the lymphocyte response to 
mitogens, such as phytohemagglutinin (PHA), is often weak or very slow in 
A-T patients, and when cell cultures are harvested routinely at 48 hours, 
few cells are dividing.  Harvest results can be improved by using a double 
dose of mitogen and harvesting at 72 hours or at several time points.<P>  

Telomeric fusions are observed frequently in A-T patients.  Tumor cells 
and senescent cells of normal persons can also show such fusions.  Further 
understanding of this observation was limited until, in 1988, the DNA 
structure of the telomere and the mechanisms of its maintenance were 
elucidated.  When the role of telomerase in telomere stability was first 
introduced, it was logical to examine telomerase levels in A-T cells.  
Pandita et al showed that although the telomeres of A-T cell lines are 
shorter than normal cells, telomerase activity was normal.<P>

Metcalfe et al have recently demonstrated significant telomere shortening 
in A-T peripheral blood lymphocytes (PBL).  PBL from 20 A-T patients 
showed an average loss of 95 +23 bp/year of age, as compared to a loss of 
35 +9 bp/year in normals.  The preleukemic T cell clones described above 
showed an even greater loss of 158 +9 bp/year, and are especially prone to 
show telomeric fusions.<P>  
	
Accelerated telomeric shortening is probably a characteristic of all 
rapidly-dividing A-T cells.  It is of further interest that telomeric 
shortening is associated with senescence of CD28-/CD8+ T cells in AIDS 
patients and in centenarians; in both situations this may account for a 
waning T cell immunity.  A similar mechanism might explain the abnormal 
development and function of the immune system in A-T patients.  Thus, the 
precocious onset of cancers, such as basal cell carcinoma, leiomyosarcoma 
and T-PLL, may reflect: 1) the basic propensity of their cells to 
accelerate telomere shortening, and 2) a waning immunity.  This would also 
provide a p53-independent, radiation-independent pathway, to cancer 
susceptibility in A-T patients.<P>

When the ATM gene was isolated and sequenced, it was noted to have strong 
homology to the yeast tel1 gene, primarily through sharing a region of 
PI-3 kinase homology, and secondarily through sharing weak homology with 
rad3. Rad3 is a  fission yeast gene containing helicase motifs and 
required for G2 arrest after DNA damage.  Of the large family of genes 
sharing PI-3 kinase homology with ATM, only tel1, mec1 (another yeast 
gene) and mei41 (of Drosophila) also share some rad3 homology.  (The rad3 
homology of tel1 is admittedly weak.)  A growing body of evidence suggests 
that tel1, mec1 and ATM perform overlapping functions.  Of the three, only 
mec1 is an essential gene.  In yeast, mec1 (mitosis entry checkpoint) is 
required for regulation of the S/M and G2/M checkpoints, the rate of 
ongoing S phase in response to damage and meiotic recombination.  Cells 
with mutations in mec1 (also called ESR1 or SAD3) proceed directly to 
mitosis when DNA replication is inhibited with hydroxyurea and are unable 
to delay the onset of mitosis (G2/M) on induction of DNA damage.  RAD53 is 
also regulated by MEC1 and TEL1.  Although tel1 mutants not are 
radiosensitive and mec1 mutants are, tel1/mec1 double mutants somehow 
synergize to increase the sensitivity to DNA damage from ionizing 
radiation and radiomimetic drugs. The human homologue of mec1, FRP1 
(FRAP-related protein), has recently been cloned and maps to chromosome 
3q22-q24; it is called ATR (AT-related, rad3-related).  Using antibodies 
to either ATR and ATM, it has been possible to show that these two 
homologous molecules form part of synaptonemal complexes during meiosis 
and bind in a complementary pattern, with ATR binding to non-synapsed 
chromosome pairs and ATM binding to synapsed pairs.<P>   

<a name="cancer">
<h3>Cancer susceptibility</h3></a>

During their shortened lifetimes, 38 percent of A-T homozygotes develop a 
malignancy.  This represents a 61-fold and 184-fold increase in Euro-
American and Afro-American patients, respectively.  Roughly, 85% of these 
malignancies are either leukemia or lymphoma.  In younger patients, an 
acute lymphocytic leukemia is most often of T-cell origin, although the 
pre-B common ALL of childhood (HLADR+, CD10+, CD5+, and CD19+) has also 
been seen in A-T patients.  When leukemia develops in older A-T 
homozyogtes, it is usually an aggressive T cell leukemia with a morphology 
similar to chronic lymphoblastic leukemia, hence the old name of "T-CLL"; 
T cell prolymphocytic leukemia (T-PLL) is the equivalent modern 
nomenclature.  The leukemic cells often contain a translocation and/or 
inversion involving the T cell receptor alpha chain gene complex at 
14q11-12.  Myeloid leukemia has not been reported in A-T patients.  
Lymphomas in A-T homozygotes, in contrast to leukemias, are usually B cell 
types, although T cell lymphomas have also been observed.  As A-T patients 
are living longer, more non-lymphoid cancers are being observed.  Several 
of our older patients have developed breast cancer and melanoma.  Cancers 
of stomach and ovary have been reported.  When fibroids or leiomyomas are 
found in A-T females, a special effort should be made by the pathologist 
to quantitate high power fields for mitotic figures since leiomyosarcomas 
of precocious  onset have been reported.<P>

A-T heterozygotes are also believed to be cancer-prone, perhaps accounting 
for as many as 5% of all cancer patients under 45 years of age in the 
United States.  They are not clinically distinguishable from normal 
individuals.  An increased incidence of breast cancer in female A-T 
heterozygotes has been reported from the United States, England and 
Norway.  In the U.S. study, the risk of breast cancer was found to be 
5-fold higher among the mothers of A-T homozygotes than in a comparable 
female population.  Based on this observation, Swift et al estimated that 
between 8 and 18 percent of all breast cancer patients may be A-T 
heterozygotes.  This would imply that ATM is the most common cancer 
susceptibility gene in the general population.  While the issue is far 
from settled, several recent genetic studies of breast cancer patients 
have failed to produce convincing evidence in support of Swift's 
predictions.  Croce and coworkers looked for ATM mutations in tumor tissue 
from 38 breast cancers.  They first screened this material by single 
stranded conformational polymorphism (SSCP) gels and then sequenced any 
regions suspected of harboring mutations.  They found no significant 
mutations.  We similarly screened cDNAs from nine breast cancer patients 
who had been radiation technologists, using a combination of protein 
truncation testing (PTT) and conformation sensitive gel electrophoresis 
(CSGE).  We found no significant mutations.  Spurr and coworkers looked 
for linkage to BRCA1 and BRCA2 in 63 early-onset breast cancer families; 
55 percent linked to BRCA1 and 45 percent linked to BRCA2.  This implied 
that none linked to 11q22-23, as Wooster et al.  and Cortessis et al. had 
reported earlier.  The Spurr et al data also suggest that late-onset or 
sporadic breast cancers may still be related to ATM mutations.  This 
interpretation would be compatible with the epidemiological data from A-T 
families showing that breast cancer seen among A-T mothers (who are 
obligate heterozygotes) peaks in the age group of 45-54, not really an 
early-onset pattern.  Another study by van t'Veer et al, still in 
progress, has so far found two truncating ATM mutations among eight women 
who developed breast cancer following radiation therapy for Hodgkin's 
disease.   Recent reports describing ATM knockout mice are confirming the 
extreme cancer susceptibility of the homozygotes; virtually all of the 
homozygous mice died with massive, widely-metastasized, malignant thymic 
lymphomas.  Heterozygous animals have not yet shown tumors.  Another 
report by Carter et al found significant loss of heterozygosity in 
sporadic breast cancers across chromosome 11q22-23.  Although this region 
includes the ATM gene, it measures ~35 cM and probably includes more than 
1000 other genes as well.  Thus, the contribution of ATM mutations to 
familial breast cancer is likely to be low, with ATM perhaps playing a 
more important role in a sporadic, low-penetrance form of breast cancer.<P>

The most frequently reported cancers in American heterozygotes 
have been: breast, trachea/bronchus/lung, stomach, prostate, melanoma, 
gall bladder.  In Italy and in Costa Rica, gastric cancer has been 
especially noteworthy.  Among 64 A-T parents and grandparents in Costa 
Rica, half of the 12 cancers reported were gastric cancer.  (On the other 
hand, Costa Rica ranks among the top three countries in the world for 
stomach cancer in the general population, making it difficult to interpret 
these observations.)  In Italian families, 7 of 20 cancers in grandparents 
were gastric cancer.  Stomach cancer has been reported in homozygotes as 
well, including two families in which both affected sibs developed stomach 
cancer.  Morrell et al failed to note any increase in stomach cancers in 
A-T homozygotes.<P>  

<a name="radio">
<h3>Radiosensitivity</h3></a>
	
Almost thirty years ago, radiation therapists observed that when A-T 
patients with cancer were treated with conventional doses of ionizing 
radiation, they developed life-threatening sequelae characteristic of much 
higher doses.  This radiosensitivity was later demonstrated in vitro using 
fibroblasts from A-T homozygotes, which are not only sensitive to ionizing 
radiation but to a variety of radiomimetic and free-radical-producing 
agents.<P> 

Early radiosensitivity assays for A-T measure colony formation efficiency, 
i.e., cells are irradiated, then cultured, and the number of colonies that 
grow are scored after a measured time period.  Fibroblasts from A-T 
heterozygotes form colonies with an efficiency that is intermediate 
between A-T homozygosity and normal; the same observation can be made 
using neocarzinostatin.  In general, however, colony forming efficiency is 
not a reliable way to detect individual heteroyzotes.  Many other methods 
have been tested for identifying A-T heterozygotes; none are reliable 
because the normal and heterozygous datasets overlap.<P> 

Now that A-T heterozygotes (carriers) can be identified more easily by 
genetic testing, in families with prior affected patients, physicians are 
confronted with the dilemma of having to advise carriers about the risks 
of radiation exposure.  Unfortunately, there are as yet no clinical 
studies upon which to base such advice.  For example, data are lacking on 
whether the in vitro radiosensitivity of heterozygotes has any clinical 
correlate, i.e., unusual reactions to standard radiological procedures.   
One can only make the general recommendation that exposure to all types of 
ionizing radiation should be minimized in persons suspected of being A-T 
carriers, remembering that two-thirds of the sibs of A-T patients are 
likely to be carriers, as well as the parents.  Whether routine dental 
X-rays should be recommended in A-T patients is also an unresolved 
issue.<P>
	
ATM knockout mice that are heterozygous (ATM+/-) do not show any abnormal 
response to total body irradiation.   Swift's epidemiological data suggest 
that exposure of heterozygotes to myelograms and other diagnostic x-rays 
may increase cancer risk.  There is also cause for concern about 
mammograms in female A-T carriers, who appear to be at an increased risk 
of breast cancer. The recommendation at this writing is that mammograms be 
continued on the same age-dependent schedule as for non-carriers, but that 
the most up-to-date mammography machines be employed to minimize exposure 
to only a few rads.  The added risk of cancer to such women is only 
slightly increased [from 1.5/100 from annual mammography screening doses 
in non-carriers to perhaps 2/100 in A-T carriers] and this should be 
compared to a 1/9 natural lifetime risk and the 30% reduction in mortality 
from annual mammography screening in women over 40.<P>

Epidemiological and radiosensitivity studies on A-T family members further 
suggests that many cancer patients in general may be receiving the wrong 
doses of radiotherapy: too much for A-T heterozygotes, and too little for 
non-carriers.  Considering that 5 percent of cancer patients under 46 
years of age may be A-T carriers and intermediate in their 
radiosensitivity, this issue could involve many thousands of patients 
annually.  Some x-ray dosage regimens are first tested empirically on 
cadres of cancer patients and if these cadres contain up to 5 percent A-T 
carriers, one can easily imagine how radiation sequelae might be more apt 
to appear in the A-T carriers, thereby lowering the "safe" dosages defined 
for everyone else.  Hopefully, once A-T carrier testing can be implemented 
on a wide scale, these issues will be resolved.<P>

Although radiation damage to DNA has been used for many years as a 
laboratory tool for characterizing the phenotype of A-T cells, it should 
be remembered that A-T cells are not usually exposed to irradiation in 
vivo!  Thus, the radiosensitivity of A-T cells is a laboratory artifact.  
Despite this, the complex A-T syndrome develops quite uniformly in most 
affecteds.  From this, one might conclude that the substrate for the ATM 
protein is ubiquitous in our bodies and that whatever DNA damage occurs 
must result from some naturally recurring insult to all cells.  Oxidative 
stress and the normal production of DNA-damaging free radical products of 
metabolism are certainly good candidates for the naturally-recurring 
insult.  Although many attempts have been made to demonstrate defective 
DNA repair in A-T cells, none has been convincingly demonstrated.  Recent 
observations suggest that it is the inability to sense this damage that is 
defective in A-T cells, not the actual mechanisms of repair.<P>  

<a name="cycle">
<h3>Cell cycle checkpoints</h3></a>

Important checkpoints monitor the progress of the cell cycle and prevent 
mutagenic damage to DNA from being fixed into future cell generations.  
The G1 checkpoint prevents replication of a damaged DNA template; the G2 
checkpoint prevents segregation of damaged chromosomes.  Kastan et al have 
shown that A-T cells have a delayed radiation-induced increase in p53, as 
compared to normal cells.  P53, dubbed the "guardian of the genome", acts 
to suppress normal cell cycle progression at G1 until DNA repairs have 
been completed.  It accomplishes this by binding DNA at sequence-specific 
sites, thereby transcriptionally activating a signal-transduction 
cascade.  In so doing, p53 functions as a tumor suppressor.  Cells from 
p53 knockout mice, lacking both normal alleles of p53 (p53-/-), fail to 
observe the G1 checkpoint; they do not experience G1 arrest after 
irradiation; nor do these mice show neurological abnormalities, immune 
defects or problems with sterility.  The phosphorylation of replication 
factor A (RPA) is similarly delayed in A-T cells post-irradiation.  Lavin 
and coworkers have confirmed the p53 expression delay and further 
demonstrated cell cycle defects upstream from p53, at PKCepsilon.  The 
fact that the newly-cloned A-T gene has a putative kinase domain supports 
the significance of these studies.  Given the strong association of 
multiple types of cancer with p53 deficiency further suggests that 
involvement of this pathway in apoptosis and in the pathogenesis of A-T 
may help to explain the increased frequency of cancer.<P> 

Interestingly, p53-/- mutants are not radiosensitive.  Thus, 
another mechanism must account for this facet of the A-T syndrome. Much 
work still needs to be done before the role of ATM proteins in 
intracellular signaling can be understood.  For example, despite much 
evidence for the inefficiency of G1/S, S and G2/M checkpoints in A-T 
cells, holding A-T cells in Go for up to seven days, does not improve 
their post-irradiation survival, suggesting that even these checkpoint 
defects may not be the crucial common denominator underlying A-T 
pathogenesis.  Recent evidence presented by Jung and Dritschilo implicates 
the NF-kappaB and IkappaB-alpha proteins in ATM function; the ATM protein 
appears to phosphorylate IkB-alpha, thereby activating the transcription 
factor NF-kappaB.  These findings would also support observations of 
increased radiation-induced apoptosis in cell lines derived from A-T 
patients.<P>  

When DNA synthesis of irradiated fibroblasts is measured, A-T homozygotes 
show a characteristic dose response curve, one that is diagnostic of the 
disease.  This phenomenon is called "radioresistant DNA synthesis (RDS)" 
because, unlike normal cells that temporarily halt the synthesis of new 
DNA after irradiation damage, A-T cells simply continue into S phase of 
the cell cycle.  Later experiments that attempted to complement RDS by 
transfecting cDNA transcripts or microcell-mediated chromosome transfer 
and other radiomimetic features of A-T cells found, however, that the two 
phenomena often were dissociated.  Thus, RDS most likely reflects a cell 
cycle checkpoint failure at S phase that is independent of other 
radiosensitivity phenotypes of A-T cells.  Using RDS, heterozygous cells 
cannot be distinguished from normals.<P> 

The shape of the RDS curve for A-T cells has been insightfully interpreted 
by Painter as having two components: one reflecting replicon initiation, 
and the other reflecting chain elongation.  The second component is 
determined by the slope of the curve above 2 kilorads, and this slope does 
not differ from normal to A-T fibroblasts.  The early component, however, 
is essentially missing from the A-T curves, suggesting that replicon 
initiation is quite abnormal.  Painter further suggested that while in 
unirradiated normal cells initiation occurs synchronously at the origins 
of a cluster of about five replicons and in irradiated normal cells damage 
to one replicon inhibits the entire cluster of five, in irradiated A-T 
cells damage to one replicon inhibits only that one replicon, i.e., the 
damage is not sensed or translated to the rest of the cluster and chain 
elongation near the growing forks is not curbed.  Thus, radiation to A-T 
cells blocks initiation of only individual replicons rather than blocking 
the initiation of clusters of replicons.  Hand and Gautschi provide 
evidence that one single-strand break may inactivate the initiation of as 
many as a hundred replicons!  Although Painter's interpretation of the RDS 
curve was put forth over ten years ago, it remains a very attractive 
hypothesis for explaining one facet of the pathogenesis of A-T.<P> 

<h3>Genetics</h3>

The disease is transmitted as an autosomal recessive.  The incidence of 
A-T has been estimated at 1 in 40,000-100,000 live births, while the gene 
frequency is believed to be as common as 1-3% of the general population.  
All races are affected.  Despite the fact that the A-T gene impacts upon 
so many different and apparently unrelated systems, the disease is 
inherited in each family as a single autosomal recessive gene defect.  It 
is unclear why, for an autosomal recessive disorder, so many of the 
parents of British, Italian, and American patients are unrelated.  This is 
borne out by the recent finding that most A-T patients, worldwide, are 
compound heterozygotes, i.e., they have two different mutations.  The 
large size of the gene certainly provides a large target for new 
mutations.  Recent studies also suggest that gametogenesis is abnormal in 
ATM knockout mice and that both mitotic and meiotic recombination is 
increased in A-T patients.  Furthermore, the newly cloned ATM gene shares 
homology with mec1 in yeast and mei41 in Drosophila, and both are meiotic 
recombination defective mutants, as discussed above.  Whether this would 
affect the heterozygous parents in A-T families sufficiently to influence 
the incidence of some affected fetuses remains to be clarified.<P>

Claims that "A-T is not always a recessive disorder" are misleading and 
belie the consortium experience of having localized the ATM gene to within 
less than 0.5 cM based on a model that assumed autosomal recessive 
inheritance in 176 families from eight countries.  Families that do not 
link to 11q22-23 will have mutations in other genes and other names will 
have to be given to those "AT-like" disorders.<P>
  
The rate of spontaneous mutations is unknown.  However, of the 176 
consortium families, all but five linked to chromosome 11q23.1.  (A sixth 
family with two affected children now links.)  Since linkage rules out 
spontaneous mutations, only these five could harbor spontaneous 
mutations.  Using the ratio of 5/176 and a gene frequency estimate of 
0.01, mutation rate estimates approximate 1.5 x 10-4.  This is rather 
high, even for a large gene.  Of course, if the ATM gene product really 
affects gametogenesis, it may not even be appropriate to apply standard 
genetic algorithms, based on Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, to the existing 
epidemiological data.  It may also be that some young patients succumb to 
malignancies before a diagnosis of A-T can be recognized, further skewing 
the data.<P>

<h3>AT-related Syndromes.</h3> 
 
The related Nijmegen Breakage Syndrome (NBS) and Berlin Breakage Syndrome 
(BBS), respectively assigned to complementation groups V1 and V2, do not 
have ataxia and do not link to chromosome 11q23.  They found their way 
into the A-T literature because they also manifest the 7;14 translocations 
and radioresistant DNA synthesis.  NBS further includes cancer 
susceptibility and immunodeficiency.  Telangiectasia are absent and the 
serum AFP level is normal.  NBS further includes "bird-like facies", 
microcephaly and mental retardation (A-T patients typically are not 
mentally retarded.)  BBS very closely resembles NBS and may not represent 
a different syndrome or a different gene.  However, NBS cells complement 
the RDS of BBS, implicating a second gene.  Only a handful of BBS patients 
have been described in the literature.  They include most of the signs and 
symptoms of NBS, with the possible addition of syndactyly, anal atresia, 
hypospadias and prominent nose.  Most of the reported NBS and BBS families 
have been of Eastern European origin.  Efforts are underway to localize 
and clone the gene(s) for both syndromes.<P>

ATFresno (ATF) combines the classical A-T syndrome with NBS, including an 
elevated AFP.  Whenever microcephaly and mental retardation are seen in an 
otherwise classical A-T patient, an ATF diagnosis should be suspected.  On 
the other hand, since ATF families link to chromosome 11q23.1 and ATM 
mutations have been found in some patients, it is unclear what the 
clinical importance of this diagnostic distinction will be.  Meanwhile, we 
have found both ATM mutations in one patient suspected of ATF, and one of 
the two expected ATM mutations in three other patients.  It may be that 
ATF is associated either with particular ATM mutation sites or perhaps 
these patient carry mutations from two different, but closely linked, 
genes that interact.  The nearby CAND3 gene could be a candidate for the 
second modifier gene.<P>

<h3>A-T Variants</h3>

There is an abundant literature describing patients who do not meet all of 
the diagnostic criteria discussed above.  Many of these describe very 
young patients, transient ataxias, probable A-T patients without 
telangiectasiae, patients with normal AFP levels or those with near-normal 
immunological parameters.  Recent screening for ATM mutations of such 
"variant" families in the international consortium (families that were 
categorically excluded from the linkage analyses) would now suggest that 
most of these are A-T.  In several families with classically affected 
patients, prominent telangiectasiae have been noted in members who do not 
have ataxia and do not carry the two affected ATM haplotypes.  Some of 
these are bonafide A-T heterozygotes.  Conversely, we have one family in 
which both affected alleles appear in a teenager with full-blown 
telangiectasia but without ataxia. (This family was one of six non-linking 
families in the consortium linkage analyses.)  Other families have been 
described with intermediate radiosensitivity, a parameter that is 
difficult to quantitate; nonetheless, in some hands this must be 
considered a reliable finding that will probably relate in some way to the 
sites of ATM mutations in those families .  No doubt there is also a 
sizable population of radiosensitive individuals whose symptoms partially 
overlap the A-T syndrome.  It will be interesting to learn whether these 
patients have ATM mutations or mutations in other genes that interact with 
the ATM protein.   In some families with later-onset ataxia, 
telangiectasiae often do not become very prominent.  On the other hand, we 
have recently found ATM mutations in several of these families, thus, 
confirming them as bonafide A-T patients.<P>

<h3>Prenatal diagnosis</h3>

With the fine-mapping of the ATM gene, a set of highly informative genetic 
markers was developed that now allows accurate haplotyping within 
families, with basically 100% risk of the fetus either being affected or 
not being affected.  The finding of only a single A-T gene for all 
complementation groups also simplifies this diagnostic approach.  This is 
in contrast to earlier attempts to perform prenatal diagnoses by trying to 
quantitate spontaneous chromosome breakage, radiation-induced chromosomal 
damage of amniocytes or fetal fibroblasts, and RDS -- all of which were 
misleading at one time or another (personal communications).  Hopefully, 
these approaches have now been abandoned.<P>

Prenatal diagnosis by haplotyping relies upon a prior affected child to 
identify the two affected chromosome 11q23.1 segments (i.e., haplotypes) 
carrying the ATM gene.  Having DNA from a prior affected child in the 
family is a prerequisite for prenatal diagnosis by haplotyping, while 
consanguinity is not.   The markers used today are all within 1% 
recombination of the ATM gene: D11S1817, D11S1819, NS22, D11S2179, and 
D11S1818.  Two of these markers are within the ATM gene itself, thereby 
circumventing the need for even reporting the risk of recombination 
separating the testing markers from the actual ATM gene.  Most of this 
testing can be performed prior to conception and continued once the mother 
is pregnant, so that once a DNA sample is available from the fetus -- 
either from growing amniocytes or from a chorionic villous biopsy -- the 
entire haplotyping can be completed within a week.  Because abortion 
guidelines vary with the country or state of residence of the mother, we 
ask not for the due date or for the date of last menses, but for the 
referring laboratory's own deadline for reporting the results of prenatal 
diagnosis to the family.  The testing laboratory director must also insist 
that the prenatal testing results be conveyed to the family by a genetic 
counselor.<P> 

Determining whether two mutations exist within the ATM gene of a child suspected of A-T would certainly be the most definitive way of establishing the diagnosis.  
Unfortunately, at this writing, such an approach is not feasible, with rare exceptions, i.e., in families of certain ethnic backgrounds, a limited number of rapid DNA assays are now available. 
However, unless the patient is homozygous for that mutation  -- which is very unlikely unless the parents are consanguineous -- a second mutation must still be sought. 
This requires a great deal of effort, either by mRNA/cDNA/RT-PCR-based screening assays or by a systematic genomic search of the 66 exons of the ATM gene.  
Even this approach is not 100% effective in finding all mutations at the present time since some lie deep within introns and others are deceptive.  
Eventually, we hope to determine the mutations of most A-T families worldwide.  
Only then will it be possible to perform prenatal diagnosis.<P>
  
</b>
