     <tr><td valign=top width=5%> <img align=top src="blueball.gif"></td><td><Font size=2>Urology</font></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
     <tr><td><b><h2>Inpatient Rotations</h2></b></td></tr>
     <tr><td><font size=2>Teaching on the inpatient rotations is provided by our 80 Board certified Internal Medicine specialists and subspecialists who are active faculty in our medicine residency programs.  With their offices located adjacent to the hospital, guidance in patient care issues occurs, formally and informally, on an ongoing basis with every admission to the teaching services.  Many of these faculty have chosen clinical practice at Virginia Mason because of the opportunity to participate in the residency program. Most of the faculty hold teaching positions at the University of Washington and positions of distinction in their regional and national medical organizations such as the American College of Physicians, the American Heart Association, the American Cancer Society, and the American Lung Association.
<br><br>
As a regional referral medical center, Virginia Mason Hospital provides exposure to patients with both common and rare diseases.  Listed below are consecutive, unselected admissions evaluated by a Medical R-1 on the inpatient service:</font></td></tr>  
</table></center>

<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td><b><h3>Medicine A</h3></b></td><td><b><h3>Medicine B</h3></b></tr>
<tr><td><font size=2><li>UGI-Variceal Bleed
<li>S/P ERCP for Common Bile Duct stones<li>Vasculitis<li>Clotting of AV Graft<li>Anterior MI<li>Post PTCA<li>CHF<li>Mental Status Change R/O Seisure Disorder<li>Seizures<li>Vertigo<li>Acute Renal Failure with Uremia<li>Diabetes Mellitus w/ Foot Ulcer, Cellulitis<li>Tracheal Cancer<li>ALL on Chemo<li>MI<li>DM - Cellulitis, Hyponatremia<li>Hypoglycemia<li>DKA</td><td valign=top><font size=2><li>Unstable Angina<li>CHF<li>UTI, Confusion in Elderly<li>Angina; R/O MI<li>Progressive Anemia and Azotemia<li>Cadaveric Renal Transplant<li> Anaphylactic Rxn to Contrast Dye, Hepatoma<li>Respiratory Failure, Secondary to Known Metastatic NSC Lung CA<li>Lymphoma on Chemo<li>Hypoxemia Secondary to Sleep Apnea<li>Cystic Fibrosis<li>Thoracic Aortic Dissection<li>DiabeticFoot<li>Rheumatoid LungDisease<li>Vasculitis<li>Crohn's Flare<li>Pancreatic CA
</font></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td><b><h3>Medicine C</h3></b></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=2><li>Syncope<li>Failure to Thrive<li>Over-anticoagulation<li>Fasciitis<li>CVA<li>CHF<li>Cervical Radiculopathy<li>Vertigo, H/O Herpes Encephalitis<li>Depression, Failure to Thrive</td><td><font size=2><li>Staphlococci Sepsis<li>Severe CHF<li>Metastatic Lung Ca, Acute Renal Failure<li>Abdominal Pain R/O Obstruction<li>Metastatic Rectal CA-CNS<li>Gastroesophageal CA-chemo<li>Lung Abcess<li>Pheumocystitis Carinii Pneumonia<li>COPD Exacerbation<li>Grave's Disease
 </font></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><table width=80%>
 <tr><td><font size=2>A  
 typical ward team consists of one senior resident (R-2 or R-3) and two interns.  Medical students may also be a part of a ward team.  Ward teams admit patients three out of six days. A typical census for a hospital ward team is 6 - 10 patients per intern.  Overnight call is every sixth night.  Because the team approach is an important aspect of the practice of Internal Medicine, residents work with all members of the health care team: other residents, medical students, attending physicians, physician consultants, nursing staff, and ancillary health care workers.
<br><br>
First year residents have initial and primary responsibility for decision-making, care planning, record keeping, and continuing management for all inpatients, subject to review and approval by supervising residents and the managing attending physician. Housestaff write all orders for patients under their care.  Residents are granted independent decision-making and care planning commensurate with their demonstrated abilities to provide excellent patient care.
<br><br>
The Critical Care team consists of one senior resident (R-2 or R-3) and one intern.  Two Critical Care teams cover the medical patients in the Critical Care Unit. A typical census for the Critical Care Unit is 8 to 12 patients.  The teams take overnight call every other night for a two week block. Board certified subspecialists in Critical Care Medicine, Pulmonary Medicine,and Cardiology teach and help with patient care management in the Critical Care Unit as their primary activity for their assigned month.</td></tr>
</font></table></center>                  
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>           
<CENTER><IMG  SRC="edures.gif" USEMAP="#edures"ismap border="0"></CENTER>
