<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
     <tr><td><b><h2>Teaching Conferences</h2></b></td></tr>
     <tr><td><font size=2>Morning report occurs daily throughout the year for R-2 and R-3 ward residents and is run by the Chief Medical Resident with teaching faculty in attendance on a rotating basis.  Our medical librarian also attends morning report to help with literature searches.<br>
<br>
Medicine Noon Conference occurs daily throughout the year and is often viewed as an ongoing "board review course."  Included below is a typical Medicine Noon Conference schedule:

</font></td></tr>  
</table></center><br>
<center><img align=bottom src="month1.jpg"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
     
     <tr><td><font size=2>Clinical Pathological Conference (CPC) occurs once monthly and is centered around important learning cases from our own Medical Center. One academic year's cases included:</font></td></tr>
<tr><td><font size=2><li>37 year old female with cough, fever, nausea and diarrhea for three days<li>46 year old male with recurrent pyurea, general malaise and weight loss<li>62 year old male with pain and weakness of his extremities<li>18 year old female with persisting jaundice<li>33 year old white male with substernal burning<li>62 year old male who presents with incidental findings of hyponatremia on routine PE<li>32 year old white female with progressive dysarthria<li>38 year old male with fevers and chills after returnig from Sudan, Africa<li>61 year old white male with history of vasculitis presents with DVT<li>73 year old male with weight loss, LUQ pain and fevers is sent for evaluation of splenic mass</font></td></tr><br>
<tr><td><font size=2>Morbidity and Mortality Conference occurs once monthly and focuses on active cases for the current Housestaff and Attendings.  An overview of all deaths on the medicine services is part of this conference.<br>
<br>
Grand Rounds occurs once weekly from September through June and is a combined conference of all services in the Medical Center.<br>
<br>
Autopsy Conference occurs when an autopsy is performed on a patient that has died on the medicine service.  Residents involved with the case are paged by the pathologist at the time of the autopsy and assembled for discussion of the case.<br>
<br>
Journal Club occurs once monthly and is a critical reading seminar for all medicine residents led by our local expert in evidence-based medicine.  The core reading material for this conference is the User's Guides to the Medical Literature from McMaster University.  The User's Guides are applied to relevant, current articles in the medical literature.

</font></td></tr>  
</table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
     <tr><td><b><h2><center>Continuing Medical Education</center></h2></b></td></tr>
     <tr><td><font size=2>Virginia Mason has a fully accredited CME program, sponsoring outstanding continuing medical education opportunities on the main campus.  These course offerings are open to our residents free of charge.

</font></td></tr>  
</table></center><br>


