<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Roger W. Bush, MD, FACP - Program Director <tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Internal Medicine</h3></b></center></td></tr>
     <tr><td ><font size=2>A graduate of the University of California, San Francisco School of Medicine in 1980, Dr. Bush completed his Internal Medicine training at Virginia Mason Medical Center in 1983.  In addition to practicing General Internal Medicine, Dr. Bush is an elected member of the Society of General Internal Medicine's regional council, and expert in HIV disease management, and a leader in continuous quality improvement. As a Fellow of the American College of Physicians, Dr. Bush is frequently an invited speaker at the College's national meetings.</td></tr>
</font></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>

<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>James R. Simmons, MD - Associate Program Director <tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Internal Medicine</h3></b></center></td></tr>
     <tr><td ><font size=2>A graduate of Tulane University Medical School in 1969, Dr. Simmons completed his training in Internal Medicine at Grady Memorial Hospital, Alanta, in 1972.  In 1974, Simmons founded the Section of General Internal Medicine at Virginia Mason and continues to be a leader, master clinician, expert teacher, and facile at applying the rules of evidenced-based medicine to his clinical practice.  Dr. Simmons was instrumental in building our General Internal Medicine Faculty Journal Club.  He recently published a book chapter on venous thromboembolism.</td></tr>
</font></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>

<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Paul A. Smith, MD - Associate Program Director <tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Internal Medicine</h3></b></center></td></tr>
     <tr><td ><font size=2>A graduate of the University of Washington School of Medicine in 1980, Dr. Smith completed his training in Primary Care Internal Medicine at the University of Rochester in1983 where he also served as Chief Medical Resident.  A long time champion of medical education for residents and life-long learning for faculty, Dr. Smith developed our residents' continuity clinic practice and our primary care training pathway.  He has a special interest in preventive health services and recently published a book chapter on this topic.  He currently serves as a tutor for medical students at the University of Washington.</td></tr>
</font></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>

<tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3>Lucy R. Sutphen, MD, FACP - Associate Program Director <tr><td colspan=2><center><b><h3> Internal Medicine</h3></b></center></td></tr>
     <tr><td ><font size=2>A graduate of Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine in 1985, Dr. Sutphen completed her training in Internal Medicine at Johns Hopkins Hospital in 1988.  In addition to practicing General Internal Medicine, Dr. Sutphen helped to found Virginia Mason's Center for Women's Health.  As an expert in health screening, Dr. Sutphen has been an invited speaker on this topic at several regional meetings.  Also a championof medical education and community service, Dr. Sutphen has devoted her talents to enhancing the continuity clinic experiences in our Internal Medicine training program both on the Main Campus and in our Community Clinic sites.</td></tr>
</font></table></center>
