<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Internal Medicine</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center">
<img align="center" src="postgrad.gif"></td></tr>
</table>
<br>
<center><img align="" src="internal.gif"</center>
<br>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td colspan=2><fontsize=2>The fully accredited Graduate Medical Education Program in Internal Medicine at Virginia Mason provides an academically rigorous and supportive educational enviornment for all residents.  The goal is to foster a commitment to life-long learning and to develop the knowledge, skills, and attitudes necessary to be highly competent and highly satisfied clinicians, both during residency and for the duration of one's medical career.<br><br>

The Internal Medicine Program is committed to:</font></td></tr>
             <tr><td valign=top><img align=top src="blueball.gif"></td><td><h4>Providing our residents with a                             first rate education in Internal Medicine</h4></td></tr>
             <tr><td valign=top><img align=top src="blueball.gif"></td><td><h4>Providing a flexible curricular program that is responsive to the evolving career goals of each resident; and</h4></td></tr>
             <tr><td valign=top><img align=top src="blueball.gif"></td><td><h4>Providing an evolving  curriculum that assures marketability for its graduates</h4></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><h2>Positions Available</h2><center>
<center><table width=80%>
            <tr><td colspan=2><fontsize=2>For the 1997-98 academic year, Virginia Mason Medical Center offers 13 first year positions in Internal Medicine:</font> </td></tr></table></center>
<center><table width=60%>
           <tr><td valign=top width=50%><h4>Preliminary Medicine<br>Catagorical Medicine<br>Primary Care Medicine</td>
           <td width=40%><h4>3 one-year positions<br>6 three-year positions<br>4 three-year positions</h4></td></tr>

</table></center>
<center><table width=80%>
            <tr><td><fontsize=2>Although the career goals of the medical school graduates interested in these different positions may vary widely, the Residency strives to provide a cohesive, integrated program that will meet the educational meeds of each resident.  Residents from all three tracks work together alongside the residents in General Surgery, Anesthesiology, Diagnostic Radiology and Transitional Year.</font>
 </td></tr></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><h2>ABIM Scores</h2><center>
<center><table width=80%>
            <tr><td><fontsize=2>Both the Catagorical Medicine and the Primary Care Medicine tracks qualify a resident for examination by the American Board of Internal Medicine.  Most graduates of the program have consistently passed the qualifying examination on the first attempt with scores above the 80th percentile. </font>
 </td></tr></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><h2>Fellowship Training</h2><center>
<center><table width=80%>
            <tr><td><fontsize=2>Graduates of the three year programs are well trained for the practice of General Internal Medicine and for additional subspecialty training.  Approximately 20% of our graduates enter subspecialty fellowship training programs each year.  Below is a list of fellowships for the last six years.</font>
 </td></tr></table></center>
<center><table width=60%>
           <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1996</td><td width=90%><h5>none</td>
           <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1995</td><td width=90%><h5>Cardiology, University of                              California at Irvine<br>Gastroenterology, University of Chicago<br>Rheumatology, U. of                  Iowa
           <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1994</td><td width=90%><h5>Pulmonary Medicine,                                   University of Washington</td>  
            <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1993</td><td width=90%><h5>Gastroenterology,                                    University of Texas at Galveston</td>  
            <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1992</td><td width=90%><h5>Cardiology, University of                             Maine<br>Cardiology, University of Florida<br>Endocrinology, University of California at San                        Francisco</td>  
             <tr><td valign=top width=15%><h5>1991</td><td width=90%><h5>none</td>
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><h2>Practice after Graduation</h2><center>
<center><table width=80%>
            <tr><td><fontsize=2>The remaining 80% of our graduates enter the practice of General Internal Medicine after graduation.  Examples of practice choices include:</font>
 </td></tr></table></center>
<center><table width=60%>
         <tr><td valign=top width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><h5>Virginia Mason in the Department of Satellites</td>
            <tr><td valign=top width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><h5>Virginia Mason, Section of General Internal Medicine, Main Campus</td>
               <tr><td valign=top width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><h5>Community Clinic Faculty</td>
                 <tr><td valign=top width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><h5>Rural practice in Washington, Montana, and California</td>
                    <tr><td valign=top width=5%><img align=bottom src="blueball.gif"></td><td width=95%><h5>Internal Medicine group practice in the Seattle area</td>
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
