<HEAD>
<TITLE>Surgery</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center">
<img align="center" src="postgrad.gif"></td></tr>
</table>
<br>
<center><img align="center" src="surgery.gif"></center>
<br>



<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>
<center><table width=80%>
 <tr><td><font size=2>
The Virginia Mason surgical residency is the oldest approved surgical residency in the Pacific Northwest.  It was instituted in 1920 when Virginia Mason Clinic first opened its doors and is now a five-year residency in General Surgery that qualifies the resident for examination by the American Board of Surgery. Candidates who have completed the full program have been uniformly successful in gaining certification by the American Board of Surgery and in developing active surgical practices or going on for advanced fellowships in surgery.  Since 1978, 64 percent of our graduating residents have entered practices in general surgery.  The remainder completed fellowships in vascular, cardiac, plastic, pediatric and colorectal surgery, and subsequently, entered practices in their respective fields.<BR>
<BR>

Eight positions are available at the first-year postgraduate level; four of which are designated for categorical or five-year general surgical training. Four appointments are made for students interested in two years of general surgery training prior to subspecialty training.<BR>
<BR>	
The first two years of the surgical residency are organized to provide the trainee with a basic core of knowledge, stressing a physiologic approach to pre- and postoperative care.  Clinical rotations include general/thoracic surgery, vascular surgery, cardiothoracic surgery, gynecology, neurosurgery, plastic/head and neck surgery, transplant and urology.  First-year residents in surgery are on call every third or fourth night and cover his/her own and other surgical services.  The second-year surgery resident who is on call at night is the most senior surgeon in the hospital and evaluates emergency room problems, takes care of patients in the intensive care units, and serves as a consultant for the first-year surgical residents.  The senior resident and the attending staff on call serve as back-ups for the in-house second-year surgery resident.<BR> 
<BR>
An excellent interchange and camaraderie exists between the surgical and medical services at Virginia Mason Medical Center.  This is fostered by the first-year surgical residents' rotation in the various medical services.  Patients in Virginia Mason Medical Center often have a medical as well as a surgical team involved with their care.  This tradition at the Clinic, fostered by the residency program, leads to excellent communication with the medical residents and the senior medical attendings and is a strong part of our program.  The relationships with Pathology, Radiology, and Anesthesia are also excellent. Experience in the treatment of severely injured patients is provided by Emergency Room, Trauma, and Burn Service rotations at Harborview Medical Center during the R-1, R-2, and R-3 years.  A Pediatric Surgery rotation is provided at Children's Hospital and Medical Center in Seattle for third-year residents designated to complete the General Surgery Residency.  Elective rotations are also available in Anesthesia, GI Endoscopy, Surgical Pathology, and Radiology.  Research opportunities are available on an ad hoc basis with no formal research year required.  For residents interested in surgical subspecialties (e.g., Orthopedics, Urology, ENT), individual schedules are prepared allowing extra rotations in these areas during the R-1 and R-2 years. <BR> 
<BR>
Each of the seven general surgery services at the Virginia Mason Medical Center is under the direction of only one attending surgeon.  An average of 40-50 operations per month are performed on each service.  Surgical residents in the R-1 through the R-5 years have the opportunity to work closely with a single attending rather than with a group of surgeons.  Fourth- and fifth-year residents have senior responsibility on general surgery services.  The senior resident is assigned to one staff surgeon and works with that surgeon in the operating room, on hospital rounds, and in the surgeon's private offices in the clinic.  This close apprenticeship experience, especially in the outpatient setting, is one of the unique aspects of our residency training at Virginia Mason Medical Center.  Another unique aspect of our surgical residency training program is the operating room experience of the junior housestaff.  Junior housestaff are not relegated to ward duties while the senior surgeons are in the operating room. First and second year residents scrub on all operations upon patients on their service.  They are the primary surgeons on all appropriate operations, depending on their level of expertise.  Typical daily schedules will vary depending upon operating room responsibilities.  While on general surgery services, houseofficers perform operations three out of five days.  While covering specialties, operating room time is increased to about 70 percent of the day.  Representative schedules are listed below.<BR>
<BR>
</td></tr>
</font></table></center>
<center><table width=70%>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
