<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Internal Medicine</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center">
<img align="center" src="postgrad.gif"></td></tr>
</table>
<br>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>

<center><img align="center" src="transit.gif"></center>
<br>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>


<center><table width=80%>
<tr><td><font size=2>
Virginia Mason Medical Center currently offers a Transitional Year Program for six positions approved by the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education. The program provides a maximum breadth of experience in all aspects of patient care.  Required rotations include: 5 blocks of Medicine; 3 blocks of Surgery; 1 block of ER and 1 block of Pediatrics at Children's Hospital and Medical Center.  The remaining 3 blocks are electives.
<BR><BR>
The Transitional Year Program is designed for individuals with an interest in Radiology, Anesthesiology, Psychiatry, Emergency Room Medicine, Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation, Ophthalmology, Orthopedic Surgery, and those residents who will go into the armed services.  The flexibility of the year's experience is well suited to all of these careers and, after completion, the individual can proceed directly to the appropriate residency program.
<BR><BR>
In addition, the Transitional first year is excellent preparation for a career in Family Practice or Internal Medicine.  Historically, many Virginia Mason medical residents have been selected from individuals completing this program.
<BR><BR>
The resident rotating through the medical and surgical services assumes the same responsibility given to a resident in one of the categorical programs.  The R-1 is a key figure in the management of patients on all services with responsibilities that include initial workup, initial orders, progress notes and diagnostic tests.
<BR><BR>
On all rotations, the R-1 works directly with an R-2 or R-3 in Medicine and with an R-4 or R-5 in Surgery who is available for teaching, advice and assistance in procedures.  Representative daily schedules are listed under the medicine and surgical training programs.
<BR><BR>
All residents must spend a four-week rotation covering the Emergency Department. A resident assumes primary medical responsibility for emergency visits, which average 40 per day.  Teaching and supervision in the Emergency Department is under the direction of five full-time teaching staff.  These individuals are board certified Internists and have demonstrated excellent teaching interest and ability.
<BR><BR>
The Transitional Year Program is designed to provide the greatest possible individualization of assignments.  After an appointment through the National Resident Matching Program, the new house officer is sent a list of possible rotations and asked to state a preference for assignment.  Every effort is made to fill this request, as it is the belief of the Office of Housestaff Affairs that the individual is in the best position to recognize his/her most important needs at this level of training.
<BR><BR>
Candidates who have performed credibly in the first postgraduate year are given preferences for opening in the R-2 year in categorical problems.  Those who seek specialty training elsewhere are aided by letters of recommendation from the teaching faculty.
<BR><BR>
A representative schedule for the Transitional Year is listed below. Each rotation is of a four week duration with the night call averaging every fourth night. 
</font></table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center><br>\
