<H1><CENTER><B>Computed Tomography (CT)</B></CENTER></H1>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><table  width = "65%">
                   <tr><td valign=top width=30%><H5>Section Head:<BR>
                                                      Supervisor:<BR><br>
                                                      Hours of Operation</h5></td>
                        <td valign=top width=80%><h5>Bert Crane, M.D.<BR>            
                                                      Danny Lopez, R.T.<BR><br>
                                                      8:00 am - 6:00 pm. Monday thru Friday<br>
                                                      8:00 am - 12:00 pm Saturday</h5></td></tr>
</table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><table width="80%">
        <tr><td valign=top><font size=2>Unlike General radiographic units, CT scanners are high technology imaging machines that use high speed computers to reconstruct cross-sectional images of the part being examined.  Main parts of the unit are:
      <ul><li>Technologist work consule<br>
            <li>Computers<br>
            <li>Table<br>
            <li>Gantry. </ul>
CT Imaging is divided into four sections:  </font></td>
<td><img height="200"width="200"align=bottom src="ctunit.jpg">
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><table width="70%">
                 <tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=top SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Head and Neck - </b></font><font size=2>
diagnostic examinations include:- Head</a>, Neck and Sinuses</A></font></td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=TOP SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Abdomen - </b></font><font size=2> examinations include: - Kidneys, Liver, and Pancreas <BR></font></td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=TOP SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Spine - </b></font><font size=2>
examinations include: Cervical, Thoracic and Lumbar Spine</font></td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=TOP SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Pelvis and Extremities - </b></font><font size=2>
examinations include: Organs located in the pelvis and bones of the extremities</font></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><table width="80%">
        <tr><td><font size=2>We will be developing informational materials in order to give you some idea on what to expect during your imaging examinations.  Information will include length of examinations, any preparation needed, and a brief explaination of what will be done.  Some examinations will require little or no explaination at all, others will be quite lengthy.  Examinations that have instruction or educational material available will be highlited in <blink> <font color=blue>blue</font></blink> above. </font></td></tr></table></center>


