<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<H1><CENTER><B>General Radiology</B></CENTER></H1>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><table width = "65%">
          <tr>         <td width=30%><H5>Section Head:<BR>
                                                      GI Radiology<BR>
                                                      Supervisor:<BR>
                                                      <BR>
                                                      Hours of Operation</h5></td>
                        <td valign=top width=80%> <h5>Reiley Kidd, M.D.<BR>            
                                                      Felicia Cummings, M.D.<BR>
                                                      Sharon Hemphill, R.T.<BR><BR>
                                                      24 hours per day Sunday - Saturday</h5></td></tr>
</table></center>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><table width="80%">
        <tr><td><font size=3>General Radiology is the largest section of the Radiology Department. The General section of Radiology at the Virginia Mason Medical Center is divided into three areas: </font></td></tr></table></center>

<center><table width="70%">
                 <tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=top SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>General Imaging - </b></font><font size=2>
diagnostic examinations include:<a href="upextrem.htm"> upper extremities</a>,<A HREF="lowext.htm"> lower extremities</A>, spine, head, pelvis, chest, and abdomen.<BR></font></td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=TOP SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Gastrointestional (GI) - </b></font><font size=2> examinations include: esophagus, stomach (Upper GI), small bowel, and colon. <BR></font></td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td width=5%><IMG valign=TOP SRC="blueball.gif"></td>
                                      <td width=95%><fontsize=3><b>Interventional - </b></font><font size=2>
examinations include: arthrograms, myelograms, and studies requiring intravenious injections.</font></td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><table width="80%">
        <tr><td><font size=3>We will be developing informational materials in order to give you some idea on what to expect during your imaging examinations.  Information will include length of examinations, any preparation needed, and a brief explaination of what will be done.  Some examinations will require little or no explaination at all, others will be quite lengthy.  Examinations that have instruction or educational material available will be highlited in <blink> <font color=blue>blue</font></blink> above. </font></td></tr></table></center>

