<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cirriculum </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%">
<img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vrad.gif"><br>

<center>
<br><img src="radres2.gif" alt="VMMC Radiology Residency">
</center>
<center><HR  SIZD=3 width=65%></center>
<CENTER><H3><b><i>    Curriculum</i></b></h3></CENTER>
<center><TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="85%">
<tr>    <Td COLSPAN=2><H4>
The program provides training in all facets of diagnostic radiology including Angiography/
interventional, MRI, Trauma Radiology, CT, GI, GU, Mammography, Neuroradiology, Nuclear
Medicine, Musculoskeletal, Pediatric Radiology and Ultrasound including obstectrical
and Vascular Ultrasound.  Our residents spend the majority of their training period at this
institution.  They are away for the following rotations:</H4></td>
</table></Center>
<center><TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="75%">
<tr>     <Td valign=top width = 5%><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="blueball.gif"></Td>
              <Td ><H4>Pediatric Radiology - Each resident spends a total of four months at Children's                              Hospital and Medical Center, an academic pediatric hospital that is one of the                              teaching hospital  of  the University of Washington.  It is located approximately 6                              miles from this institution.</H4></td>
<tr>     <Td valign=top width = 5%><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="blueball.gif"></Td>
              <Td ><H4>Trauma Radiology - Each resident spends a total of four months at                               Harborview Medical Center which is the regional Level I trauma center.  Harborview                               is also a major teaching hospital of the University of Washington and is located 0.6                               miles from this medical center.</H4></td>
<tr>     <Td valign=top width = 5%><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="blueball.gif"></Td>
              <Td ><H4> Armed Forces Institute of Pathology (AFIP), Bethesda, Maryland.  Each                                resident attends this six week course in radiologic-pathologic correlation. Tuition is                                paid and a generous stipend is provided for travel and living expenses.
</H4></td>
</table></Center>
<center><TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="85%">
<tr>
     <td><h4>The remaining time is divided among the rotations at Virginia Mason Medical Center.  Each rotation is four weeks in length providing thirteen rotations per year.  The four year cirriculum is included. There is also a sample rotation schedule provided. A given residents actual 
schedule will vary slightly.<BR><BR>

During the first six months of radiology training (PGY-2), the resident completes rotations in GI, CT, Ultrasound and Nuclear Medicine.  .  The resident is on call with a senior resident beginning in September and begins taking call with attending back-up in December.The remainder of the year is spent on Chest, Neuroradiology, Angio/Interventional, Mammography,MRI and GU.<BR><BR>

                     During the second year of radiology residency (PGY-3) there is an eight week rotation at 
                     Children's Hospital for Pediatric radiology and an eight week rotation at Harborview Medical 
                     Center for Trauma radiology.  Training also continues in all modalities at Virginia Mason.  By 
                     the latter part of this year, the resident accepts progressive responsibility in the department 
                     and eventually performs major portions of all exams independently.<BR><BR>

                    In the third year (PGY-4), the final rotation at Harborview Medical Center is completed.  
                    There is also a second eight week rotation at Children's Hospital.  During this year each 
                    resident attends the Radiologic Pathologic Correlation Course at the Armed Forces Institute
                    of Pathology in Bethesda, Maryland.<BR><BR>  

                    In the last year of training (PGY-5) the residents have primary responsibility for diagnostic 
                    procedures, under the supervision of a supporting staff person.  Senior residents have five 
                    elective rotations.  These can be arranged on any service and one can be designated for 
                    research.  
</H4></td>
</table></Center>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER= CELLSPACING= CELLPADDING= WIDTH=100%>
