<HEAD>
<TITLE>Terms </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">

<table cellspacing="2" cellpadding="2" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center"><img align="center" src="vrad.gif"></td></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="pacs.gif"></CENTER>
<H1><CENTER><B>Terminology and Standards</B></CENTER></H1>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<center><TABLE WIDTH="85%">
<tr>
<td valign=top ><Font size =3>

<CENTER><B><H1>Standard Ethernet</B></H1></CENTER>
Traffic on the ethernet used in our network consists of serial data transmissions controlled by a communications protocol named Carrier Sense Multiple Access/Collision Detection (CSMA/CD).  Basically, one network node at a time can broadcast a carrier signal and data packets with the network address of the intended destination embedded in the packet header. The network interface card in the computer listens for other carriers and when the line is free, initiates a transmission. Each of the nodes on the LAN look at the address in the packet and either receives or ignores the transmission as appropriate.   If two nodes attempt to transmit simultaneously, a "collision" is detected by the interface and the nodes back off for a random amount of time and then retry the transmission. The data packets range in size from a minimum of 64 bytes to a maximum of 2048 bytes (2KB).The "bandwidth" or maximum data capacity for standard ethernet is 10 Megabits per second (Mbps) (or about 1.25 Megabytes/sec). In shared ethernet this capacity must be divided among all of the active nodes in a given segment on the LAN. 
<BR>
<BR>
Ethernet connections were originally made with coaxial cable routed from node to node in what was called a "bus topology" or "10base2" after the ANSI standard. There were reliability problems with this method because a malfunctioning interface card or broken/bad cable or connection could adversely affect a large portion of the network. This type of problem was difficult to isolate and repair without taking the whole network down. The "star topology" (AKA 10baseT) was developed to overcome some of these limitations using two twisted pairs of unshielded wires routed from each node to a central connection point. Inexpensive telephone cable (known as Level 3 cable) is commonly used for standard 10Mbit/s ethernet. In fact, some facilities have used existing telephone wiring (sometimes referred to as "POTS" - plain old telephone service) for their network interconnections. A "hub" or "concentrator"  is used at the central connection, and it is common for modern hubs to monitor network traffic, looking for excessive collisions and illegal sized packets. These hubs can automatically identify and partition (shut down) a malfunctioning node connection without affecting the rest of the network. It is then relatively simple to identify the bad component and correct the problem.<BR>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<h4>Due to the bandwidth limitations of the ethernet, it is often desirable to break up the network into a hierarchy of logical work groups called segments. These segments can be interconnected by one of three types of devices:</h4>
<CENTER><TABLE  WIDTH="90%"><tr><td><H4>
<CENTER><B><H1>Bridge</B></H1></CENTER>
The basic purpose of a bridge is to separate (filter) the network traffic unless the destination of a data packet is in another segment. They either learn or are told (through software) all of the network addresses on at least one side. The destination of each data packet is checked and the device determines whether or not it is necessary to pass (forward) the data out of the work group through the bridge to reach it's intended destination. Bridges are usually only a single port and often do no more than check the address of a packet and consequently do not slow down the apparent speed of the network.
<CENTER><B><H1>Router</B></H1></CENTER>
A router generally has multiple ports, not necessarily all utilizing the ethernet protocol and learns all of the addresses on the network. The router looks at the packet destination, decides what is the best path to that destination and can convert the packet to different network protocols such as Token Ring or FDDI (or one of many others) if necessary.  It can also isolate networks by controlling data flow bidirectionally.   Because the router stores the entire packet before operating on it and/or forwarding, it is slower than a bridge by an order of magnitude. However, since it stores the entire packet, data integrity can be checked before forwarding, preventing the propagation of corrupted and truncated packets through the network. This is an important feature because these errors are generated during normal network operations as a result of collisions. Some devices combine features of a bridge and a router into a single unit.
<CENTER><B><H1>Switching Ethernet Hubs</B></H1></CENTER>
A switching ethernet hub is basically a group of bridges connected in a cross-point matrix that can filter addresses and forward the packets to the appropriate port at full bandwidth ("wire speed") independently of the activity of the other ports in the switch. There are several different vendors of switching hubs; some basically utilize bridge technology, others have many of the features of a multi-port router.
</h4>
<td></TR></TABLE></center>
A telecommunications analogy is often used to describe the difference between shared and switched ethernet hubs. A shared ethernet hub is like being on a party line; only one conversation can be carried on at a time. Switched ethernet is like a PBX where multiple conversations can occur simultaneously. However, you can still get a busy signal if the person you call is already on the line. Consequently, switched ethernet is most appropriately used where there are a significant number of peer to peer conversations going on as opposed to several clients primarily communicating with a single server.<BR>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<CENTER><B><H1>Full Duplex Ethernet</B></H1></CENTER>
<BR>
This is a proprietary (non-standardized) implementation that permits simultaneous bi-directional operation of standard 10Mbps ethernet, yielding 20Mbps. Useful when there is a need to handle substantial traffic flowing in both directions. Primary applications would be for file servers and for interconnecting LAN segments. Full duplex ethernet requires the use of specialized hubs and network interface cards.

<CENTER><B><H1>Fast Ethernet</B></H1></CENTER>

This is also a proprietary protocol. In fact, there are two very different proposals in the category. One referred to as 100baseT, is being supported by Cabletron, SynOptics, and Sun Microsystems. It retains the current architecture of 10baseT ethernet on better cable (Level 5) and the afore-mentioned standard ethernet CSMA/CD communications protocol. The other, called 100VGanyLAN, is supported by AT&T, HP, IBM, and Proteon. It is significantly different from the current ethernet in that it uses a completely different communications protocol called Demand Priority Method Access, which as you might guess from the name supports several different priority levels for an interface card to use in obtaining access to the network. In addition, the interconnection architecture utilizes 4 pairs of wires instead of the two pairs used by 10baseT. This is not as great a problem as it might seem due to the fact that Level 5 cabling consists of four pairs of wire of which two pairs are not (generally) used. It would also seem significant to note that HP developed the communications protocol specifically to provide support for real-time video and voice processing. Fast ethernet also requires the use of vendor-specific, specialized hubs and network interface cards.

<CENTER><B><H1>Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI)</B></H1></CENTER>

100Mbps FDDI initially was developed for fault tolerance with a dual redundant "counter-rotating" ring (point  to point) topology utilizing two pairs of fiber optic cables. Devices on the ring are referred to as dual-attach stations, and must be operating to complete the network circuit unless equipped with electrically-operated optical by-pass switches. The cabling is expensive and difficult to terminate. FDDI star topologies have been developed utilizing a single fiber optic pair from a hub (referred to as a concentrator for FDDI) to the devices on the network, known as single-attach stations. As with 10baseT, problems on an individual port does not normally adversely affect the rest of the network. Most recently, FDDI has been implemented on shielded and unshielded twisted pair cable in this star topology. This has been standardized as Twisted Pair - Physical Media Dependent (TP-PMD) FDDI. Network equipment from different vendors will general work together with little risk of incompatibility.

<CENTER><B><H1>Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM)</B></H1></CENTER>

This is the newest development in network technology, still (a year?) away from wide commercial availability. Virtually every aspect of the network communication protocol has been redesigned from packet size ("cells" in ATM-ese) to destination addressing. Even bandwidth is supposed to be scalable from 25Mbps to 250Mbps and higher. ATM has been optimized for transmission efficiency and simple switching/routing that can be implemented entirely in hardware (like some ethernet bridging technologies). Essentially, each ethernet packet must be directed to it's destination, one step (bridge/router) at a time. ATM transmits a "scout" to determine the best route and establish a "connection" with the destination. This routing information is then included in the header of subsequent cells. These connections can be set up by a network administrator as a Permanent Virtual Circuit (PVC) or on demand by the network as a Switched Virtual Circuit (SVC). ATM also uses a fixed size cell (53 bytes) compared to ethernet's variable 64 to 2048 byte packet, which allows the ATM network to manage traffic through Quality of Service (QoS) requests. This ability to allocate bandwidth permits delay-tolerant traffic to be intermixed with time-sensitive traffic like voice and video.<BR>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>

<CENTER><B><H1>TCP/IP and the DICOM Standard</B></H1></CENTER>

TCP/IP is part of a networking protocol that governs the communication between computers. Refering to the "OSI model", the universal framework for communications between computers, the protocols corresond to the Network and Transport layers, between the user interface and the physical network operations. :
<CENTER><TABLE  WIDTH="90%">
<tr>
           <td valign=top width=15%><h5>Layer 1:</h5></td>
               <td width=40%><h5>Physical electical components</h5></td>
                      <td valign=top width=50%><h5>NIC, wiring, hubs</h5></td></tr>
<tr>
           <td><h5>Layer 2:</h5></td>
               <td><h5>Data Link</h5></td>
                  <td><h5>Ethernet, FDDI,etc aka MAC and LLC layers<h5></td></tr>
<tr>
           <td valign=top><h5>Layer 3:<h5></td>
               <td valign=top><h5> Network<h5></td>
                    <td valign=top><h5>Internet Protocol<h5></td></tr>                    
<tr>
           <td valign=top><h5>Layer 4:<h5></td>
               <td valign=top><h5> Transport<h5></td>
                  <td valign=top><h5>Transport Control Protocol, User Datagram Protocol<h5></td></tr> 
<tr>
           <td valign=top><h5>Layer 5:<h5></td>
               <td valign=top> <h5>Session<h5></td>
                    <td valign=top><h5> Connection services<h5></td></tr>
<tr>
           <td valign=top><h5>Layer 6:<h5></td>
               <td valign=top><h5>Presentation<h5></td>
                   <td valign=top><h5> Operating System (DOS, UNIX)<h5></td></tr>
<tr>
            <td valign=top><h5>Layer 7:<h5></td>
                <td valign=top><h5> Application<h5></td>
                    <td valign=top><h5> user programs<h5></td>
</tr></table></center><BR>
		

TCP/IP was probably chosen as part of the DICOM specification because of several factors; automatic routing capabilities inherent to the equipment addressing scheme, independence from specific types of physical network structures, and the popularity  of UNIX (of which TCP/IP is an integral part) in research and engineering applications. <BR><BR>

The DICOM standard defines most of the parameters necessary for computers from different manufacturers to exchange and manipulate various types of data. In addition to transfer and display parameters, there are parameters for filming and a Hospital/Radiology Information System interface. <BR>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<CENTER><B><H1>Design considerations for Diagnostic Imaging</B></H1></CENTER>
Several factors impact the design of our Imaging Network, beyond the obvious roadblocks presented by the compatibility (or lack thereof) of image file formats between multiple vendors. We must assume that the ACR-NEMA DICOM 3.0 standard will eventually provide the basis for that connectivity. <BR><BR>Technolgically outdated and/or proprietary computer architectures used by some imaging vendors must be accomodated, as well as the huge traffic loads present in exams consisting of 10 to 20 Megabytes of data. Imaging Nodes, particularly workstations, will eventually be widely distributed throughout the medical center, satellites, and perhaps even to client facilities.  <BR>

<CENTER><B><H1>Building Blocks</B></H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><TABLE  WIDTH="90%">
<tr><td>
<CENTER><B><H2>1. Network Interface Cards (NIC):</B></H2></CENTER> This is the base on which the network is built. We predict that we will be tied to 10 Mbps ethernet for propriatary devices (such as CT, MR, DSI, DECUS, Lasers) for several more years. The aquisition modalities have generally not utilized "state of the art" computer hardware because of the time and investment required to develop and certify the systems. Along with card availability, NIC driver software must also be available that is compatible with the respective operating systems and be transparent to application software. High speed NICs will be available for the systems that utilize off the shelf computer hardware (such as workstations and archival systems), but we must ensure that compatible, industry standard cards and driver software are available for all of these platforms. <Br> 

<CENTER><B><H2>2. Network Cabling:</B></H2></CENTER> There are established standards for cable types and hardware specific to the various types and speeds of network interconnection. All of the wiring components and techniques used in the current network project are intended to meet the requirements of "Level 5", which should be adequate for at  least 100Mbps. There is no established theoretical bandwidth limit for the fiber optic cabling interconnectiong the 5th Floor South Pavillion to the North Pavillion, MRI, and Hospital buildings; the telephone switch room and the link to the Metro Building in the Clinic Basement.  The rationale behind our wiring plan is to provide flexibility by permiting installation or migration of any computing device at any point of our network. Specifically, we anticipate that the IdxRad serial terminals will soon be replaced by either diskless PCs or Graphics Workstations. PCs or workstations will also be more widely utilized in the physician's offices. Additional digital image acquisition devices will be added as DICOM standards are implemented and deployed into the marketplace.  <BR><BR>

Initially, the fiber optic cables will be utilized not for their potential speed advantages, but for extended range. The Level 5 wiring will function out to approximately 328 feet. The fiber optic cables are rated for more than 1640 feet, and is necessary for the network extensions to the other buildings.

<CENTER><B><H2>3. Connections:</B></H2></CENTER>
<center><B><I> Phase One:</i></b></CENTER>
 We have purchased six, 12 port 10 BaseT (10 Mbps twisted pair) Shared Ethernet Hubs and a 16 port, store and forward Ethernet Switch to provide the connectivity for our computers. Please refer to the attached diagram. The acquisition devices, work stations, and file servers will be connected to the workgroup hubs, organized for the most part by section or modality. Each hub will in turn be connected to a port on The Switch, which will serve as a bridge to restrict normal traffic to their respective segment. Traffic specifically intended for destinations outside the segment will be passed. Several devices will be plugged directly into the switch to take advantage of the dedicated 10Mbps bandwidth provided between switch ports. These particular devices were selected for direct connection to the switch because of the predicted load and traffic patterns between them. The connection to the existing Medical Center Ethernet will also be through one of the switch ports. Initially, the equipment installed in the North Pavillion will be directly connected via fiber optic cables and ethernet transceivers (transmission media adapters) to their logical modalities. <BR><BR>

Telecommunications has made a commitment to share the T-1 (dedicated 1.44 Mbps) phone lines to several of the VM satellite clinics. Via the fiber optic cables to the Telephone Switch Room, we will have access to 684KBps (approximately  7% of ethernet bandwidth) per satellite for establishing a wide-area network (WAN). Through these connections, we will be able to accomplish such tasks as providing workstation services and importing Ultrasound, CT, and MRI images from the remote sites. Information Systems is in the process of selecting new modular equipment and there is a chance that Radiology may acquire routers and communications/data service units (CSU/DSU) from IS. <BR><BR>

<CENTER><B><I>Phase Two:</I></B></CENTER>
 Eventually, it will be necessary to connect more than six devices in the North Pavillion to our Radiology Imaging Network. At this time, a second Ethernet Switch will be installed with a high speed (FDDI or perhaps ATM) interswitch link to the existing Ethernet Switch. The network traffic will be able to connect with their modality segments through the high speed link and switch ports with little or no degradation in speed over the discrete connections implemented in Phase One. <BR><BR>

<CENTER><B><I>Phase Three:</I></B> </CENTER>
We will be locked in to 10Mbps ethernet for many of our acquisition and printing devices for several years. But the modality segments will be relatively small and automatically pushing images to file/print/archival servers not particularly time-sensitive as there will seldom be a person waiting for the images to arrive. However, we anticipate that many of the workstations will not be modality-specific. In fact, multi-modality image envelopes are expected in conjunction with the Idx project workstations, and there will definitely be a person awaiting the arrival of images when they are called up as part of a referring physician's review of the exam interpetation or a radiologist's consultation. Logically, these multi-use workstations should reside on their own segment, and this segment will be a high-speed protocol as determined by the selection of the inter-switch link in Phase Two. 

<CENTER><B><H2>4. Network Management:</B></H2></CENTER>
 All of the equipment being purchased is compatible with the Simple Network Management Protocol (SMNP) software, which we have also purchased. We will be able to collect statistical data on network activities, tune, configure, and troubleshoot hardware from a network workstation. We will be able to analyze and document the growth and traffic patterns, placing and purchasing hardware in a logical manner. We currently have an assigned block of Internet addresses on which we will organize the network structure, perhaps opening our system to the exchange of images and information from outside VMC. <BR><BR>
</td></tr>
</table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>


</font></TR>
</table></center>
