<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ltrasound </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000">
<table cellspacing="2" cellpadding="2" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center"><img align="center" src="vrad.gif"></td>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="pacs.gif"></CENTER>
<H1><CENTER><B>Digital Fluoro Network</B></CENTER></H1>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
 
<center><TABLE width ="85%">
<tr><td align=top width=50%><H5>In 1990, the department started replacing its older fluoroscopic units with new digital units.  One important condition of purchase was that all units were to be completely digital with no "add on" digital divices manufactured and installed by a third party.  Having a totally integrated single vendor system is a very important consideration. <BR><BR>
The Digital Fluoro network consists of each fluoroscopy unit interconnected by a 10mb/s ethernet
hub.  The Hub is connected to the High Speed Switch for rapid transmission of images to a laser printer.  There is also an ethernet to a server/workstation for viewing of fluroscopic images.<BR><BR>
In early 1997, the fluorscopy section hopes to be the first test of an HL-7 interface to the operators console of the x-ray equipment for the purpose of uploading demographic data.  If successful, this eliminate double entry of patient demographics, and insure the integrity of our future archival system.  It is our opinion that the RIS/PACS interface has to be completed before an archival system is installed.<BR><BR>
</h5></td>
<td width=50% ><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="gennet.gif"></td></tr></table></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="fluoro.jpg"></center><BR>
