<HEAD>
<TITLE>Upper Extremity </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="vmbg.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000"link=#ffffff>

<table cellspacing="2" cellpadding="2" width="85%">
<tr>
<td><img hspace="15" src="vmsqlog2.jpg" align="middle"></td>
<td align="center"><img align="center" src="vrad.gif"></td></TR>
</TABLE>
<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<CENTER><H1><B>Upper Extremity</B></H1></CENTER>

<center><table CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 width="85%">
             <tr><td width=35%><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="skele2.gif"></td>
             <td width=65%><font size=-1>The Upper Extremity consists of the Clavicle (collar bone), Scapula (Shoulder Blade), Humerus (arm), Elbow, Radius and Ulna (forearm), Wrist, and Hand<br><br></font>
<b><i>Preparation</i></b><br>
<font size=-1>There is no preparation for the patient in order to examine the upper extremity other than to remove hardware such as splints or ace bandages.  If a cast is applied to the injured part, films are taken with the cast on.<br><br></font>
<b><i>Procedure</i></b><br>
<font size=-1>Generally examinations of the upper extremity are done with the patient in the sitting position.  Hands, wrists, forearm and elbows are done with the patient sitting with the part to be examined resting on the x-ray table.  Shoulder and arm views are taken either lying flat on the table or standing in front of an upright film holder.  <br><br>
</font>
</td></tr></table></center>
<br>

<center><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="vmbbarw.gif"></center>
<CENTER><IMG  SRC="radbar1.gif" USEMAP="#radbar"ismap border="0"></CENTER>
