<HEAD>
<TITLE>Body CT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="" TEXT="#ffffff" LINK="#ffffff" VLINK="#ffffff" ALINK="#ffffff">

<H3>HISTORY:</H3>

<H4>45 y.o. male with a history of colectomy for polyposis.  <BR>
Prior small bowel study shows displacement of bowel loops.  
</PRE>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="body1.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct.jpg"></A>
<A HREF="body2.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct2.jpg"></A>
<A HREF="body3.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct3.jpg"></A>
<A HREF="body4.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct4.jpg"></A>
<A HREF="body5.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct5.jpg"></A>
<A HREF="body6.htm"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="sct6.jpg"></A>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<PRE><H4> <B>FINDINGS:</B>  Images through the upper abdomen demonstrate a 5 cm left adrenal mass, 
                       and a large, irregular mass in the mesenteric root with strand-like extensions 
                       into the adjacent fat.  This appearance is consistent with a desmoid tumor.


  DIAGNOSIS:  Gardner's syndrome, with  
                                                   a.) mesenteric desmoid
                                                   b.) a left adrenal neoplasm   
</H4>  </PRE>
<PRE><H4> <B>DISCUSSION:</B> Gardner's syndrome is familial polyposis coli in association with a variety of
                            extraintestinal manifestations including osteomas, soft tissue tumors (including desmoids
                            and sarcomas), and an increased incidence of ampullary carcinoma.  More recently, an
                            association with the Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndromes has also been recognized.
                            This probably accounts for the co-existing left adrenal mass in our patient.  Patients with
                            Garners (unlike those with familial polyposis coli) are at higher risk for the developing
                            desmoid tumors, peritoneal adhesions, and keloids in surgical sites.  This places these
                            patients at increased risk of retroperitoneal fibrosis, and ureteral or bowel obstruction due
                            to the desmoplastic response they mount following surgery.
</H4>  </PRE>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=4 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=2WIDTH=70%>
      <TR>
          <TD ALIGN=CENTER width =25%><A HREF="vmrad.htm"><Font size =2>Home<BR> Page</Font></TD>
          <TD ALIGN=CENTER  width =25%><A HREF="floor.htm"><Font size =2>Floor<BR> Plan</Font></TD>
          <TD ALIGN=CENTER  width =25%><A HREF="teach.htm"><Font size =2>Teaching<BR> File</Font></TD>
          <TD ALIGN=CENTER  width =25%><A HREF="resmain.htm"><Font size =2>Residency <BR>Program</Font></TD>
                   </TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>












</DOC>
