<tr>
<td width=440>

<UL>
   <LI><a href="mil_c4ix.html-ssi">Infiltrations at military facilities.</a>  Received on G-Two.<BR>
<BR>
   <LI>National Defense University releases highly critical report of <BR><a href="mil_c4iw.html-ssi">info ops in Bosnia.</a><BR>
<BR>
   <LI>Defense Daily reports that <a href="mil_c4iv.html-ssi">troops in Bosnia</a> have been left out of the information loop.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>The Army's War  College Strategic Studies Institute has a worthwhile resource at 
<A HREF="HTTP://carlisle-www.army.mil/usassi/ssipubs/catalogs/catarma.htm">http://carlisle-www.army.mil/usassi/ssipubs/catalogs/catarma.htm</A>
Included is one of the articles titled <a href="mil_c4iu.html-ssi">THE FUTURE OF AMERICAN LANDPOWER:  STRATEGIC CHALLENGES FOR THE 21st CENTURY ARMY</a> - an excellent read!<BR>
<BR>
     <LI>Report on European peacekeeping Conference - <a href="mil_c4it.html-ssi">US ARMY PKI</a><BR>
<BR>
   <LI><a href="mil_c4is.html-ssi">Non-traditional resupply methods/Marines</a><BR>
<BR>

   <LI><a href="mil_c4ir.html-ssi">Marine Corps Modernization</a> By John Robinson<BR>
<BR>

<LI><B>The Militarily Critical Technologies List:</B><BR>
What Is the MCTL Process?  It is the systemic ongoing assessment and analyses of technologies to determine which technologies are <U>Militarily Critical</U>. 
Infowar.com has been given permission to publish the <a href="mctl/mctl.html-ssi">Military Critical Technologies List - Part I:  Weapons Systems Technologies</a>.  It is available in .pdf format.   This is the first of three parts.  Part two:  Weapons of Mass Production and  Part three: Critical Developing Technologies are in development and will be published when completed and made available to us.<BR>
<BR>
   <LI><a href="mil_c4iq.html-ssi">Commandant's Planning Guidance for the USMC
</a>  Thank you to Col. Gary Wilson, OSD/RA GWilson@osd.pentagon.mil<BR>
<BR>
 
   <LI>NATIONAL DEFENSE UNIVERSITY, <a href="book/sa96cont.html-ssi">Strategic Assessment 1996:  Elements of U.S. Power. </a><BR>
<BR>
   <LI><a href="mil_c4ip.html-ssi">AFCEA/NAVY ASW CONFERENCE</a>, 3-4 DEC 96<BR>
<BR>
   <LI>USAF Opens First <a href="mil_c4io.html-ssi">Information Warfare Training Laboratory</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI>Presented at InfoWarCon this past September,  you won't want to
miss reading- <a href="mil_c4i8.html-ssi">"The E-Bomb- a Weapon of Electrical Mass Destruction."</a> by Carlo Kopp. (Large HTML with many graphics)<BR>
<BR>   
   <LI><a href="mil_c4in.html-ssi">Virtual Reality-Training For the Future,</a> points out that there may
be more than one way to learn marksmanship and other skills that may be needed in a military/crisis environment.<BR>
<BR>
   <LI>A valuable resource... <a href="mil_c4im.html-ssi">Stateless Warfare: Commandant's Planning Guidance</a><BR>
<BR>
   <LI>Sometines referred to as 4th generation warfare, read <a href="mil_c4il.html-ssi">G-TWO Open Source Intelligence</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI>From Steve Macko, ENN editor, <a href="mil_c4ik.html-ssi">a briefing and analysis</a> on the
Russian military.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="mil_c4ij.html-ssi">THE ETHICS OF INFORMATION WARFARE AND STATECRAFT.</a> Dr Dan Kuehl, distinguished author and professor from NDU wrote this excellent piece you will want to read!<BR>
<BR>

<LI>The author calls this piece an Alternative View of Info War but the second title <a href="mil_c4ii.html-ssi">"The fictive environment of DoD infowar kooks"</a> kind of gives away 
the author's real viewpoint. Take a gander.<BR>
<BR>

<LI>Ft. McClellan General Announces <a href="mil_c4ih.html-ssi">Reserve Bio-War Unit</a><BR>
<BR>

  <LI>What do Air Force personnel need to learn in order to operate
effectively in an information warfare (IW) environment?  The question asks
for a bridge to the twenty-first century multipolar world. Find out the
answer in <a href="mil_c4ig.html-ssi">"Avoiding Technologically-Induced Delusions of Grandeur:
Preparing the Air Force for an Information Warfare (IW) Environment"</a>, by
Captain Patrick K. Barker, USAF.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="mil_c4if.html-ssi">Cyberwar</a>, by Campen, Dearth, and Goodden, AFCEA International Press, 1996<BR>
<BR>

<LI>"The Army War College's Unclassified Advanced Course on Protecting 
Critical Infrastructures." Just a link for now. Hoping to get the real thing 
here, soon.  <a href="http://CARLISLE-WWW.ARMY.MIL/usacsl/iw/tutorial/intro.htm"> http://CARLISLE-WWW.ARMY.MIL/usacsl/iw/tutorial/intro.htm</a><BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="mil_c4ie.html-ssi">"Information War and Some Aspects of A Computer Operator's Defense"</a> by, Victor I. Sointev, Ph.D. An interesting paper by one of  Moscow's
leading professors that was presented at InfoWarCon5.<BR>
<BR>
   
<LI><a href="mil_c4id.html-ssi">"First Steps Toward a Defense"</a> by Michael Wilson. Wilson clearly
demonstrates that we can mount defensive information warfare.  We just have to start!<BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="mil_c4ic.html-ssi">"New World Vistas - Air and Space Power For The 21st Century".</a>  A
comprehensive report by the Air FOrce Scientific Advisory Board that identify technologies that will guarantee the air and space authority of the United States.<BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="mil_c4ib.html-ssi">"Hardwar, Softwar, Wetwar: Operational Objectives of Information Warfare"</a> by Michael Wilson, The Nemesis Group. Read about the "value chain"...an
aggregate infrastructure of processes, best explained by example.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>By Capt. Roger D. Thrasher, USAF:  <a href="thesis.pdf"> "Information Warfare:
Implications For Forging The Tools."</a> (in PDF file Format) Direct your comments to Capt. Thrasher at:  <a href="MAILTO:thrasher@RL.AF.Mil">thrasher@RL.AF.Mil</a><BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="mil_c4ia.html-ssi">"CORNERSTONES OF INFORMATION WARFARE"</a> The Information Age is also transforming all military operations by
providing commanders with information unprecedented in quantity and quality.
The commander with the advantage in observing the battlespace, analyzing
events, and distributing information possesses a powerful, if not decisive,
lever over the adversary.  Ronald R. Fogleman, General, USAF   and    Sheila
E. Widnall Secretary of the Air Force.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="mil_c4i9.html-ssi"> "Managing INFOWAR in the Future"</a>,  by Arnold E. Donahue.  Where
should the leadership and stewardship of the multi-faceted efforts that make up the offensive and defensive parts of INFOWAR be housed?  Who should be the head honcho of these efforts?  <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Presented at InfoWarCon96, Professor Dr. D.S. Chereshkin's <a href="Doclusa.doc">"Realities of InfoWars"</a> a brief thesis from the distinguished Vice President of the Russian Academy of Natural Science, Moscow, Russia. (322K DOC Format)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Russian views on Infosecurity.  Prof. Vitaly Tsygichko, prof.Dmitry Chereshkin, prof. Georgy Smolian. <a href="mil_c4i7.html-ssi">"ESTIMATION OF EFFICIENCY FOR INFORMATION SECURITY SYSTEMS"</a> <BR>
<BR>

<LI>By Robert David Steele-Vivas, founder of Open Source Solutions, Inc. <a href="mil_c4i6.html-ssi">"Creating a Smart Nation"</a> will illustrate to you how the United States needs
to approach: Strategy, Policy, Intelligence and Information. This will get your wheels moving!<BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="mil_c4i5.html-ssi">"The Essence of Warfare - A Return To First Principals"</a> by Michael Wilson of the Nemesis Group.  It is no surprise, that some basic principles behind the Art or Science of War are becoming more evident as we once again transform our ways of thinking on the subject.<BR>
<BR>

<LI>Maximizing the flow and control of information is key to competitiveness, whether it be on the battlefield, in the marketplace, or on the campaign trail.  An innovative tool and approach to planning and managing intelligence or information in these very intense, time sensitive environments is the <a href="mil_c4i3.html-ssi">"WarRoom".</A> by Mark Gembecki and Steven Shaker.<BR>
<BR>

<LI>This paper will examine a new threat and highly unconventional military environment, discussing the challenges facing the tactical and strategic military environments as they conduct operations in the <a href="mil_c4i4.html-ssi">Fifth Dimension of Warfare</a>. Written by Richard F. Forno .<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="ukwar.html-ssi">The UK High Level Wargaming Facility</A> Presented at the NATO Defence Research Group 36th Seminar, IDA.<BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="iwchall.html-ssi">The Information Warfare Challenges of a National Information Infrastructure</A> by Ron Gove, SAIC. Presented originally at InfoWarCon III, Sept., 1995. (23K)<BR>
<BR>

<LI><a href="howie_sh.html-ssi">Measuring Effectiveness of Theater IW/C2W Campaigns</A> by Howard W Clark and Saundra K Wallfesh of Dynamics Research Corporation is a favorite paper presented at InfoWarCon 3, Sept. 1995. This is the short version, introduction only. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>The complete version of <a href="howie2.doc">Measuring Effectiveness of Theater IW/C2W Campaigns in Word 2.0</a> is also available for download. About 90K. <BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="swett.html-ssi">A Strategic Assessment: The Internet</A> is Charles Swett's classic paper. Long, 103K, but worth the effort.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="export.html-ssi">Export Control As Proactive Defensive Information Warfare</a> by Winn Schwartau looks at a new angle for IW; whether we wage it or it's waged against us. ITAR has many different applications. (22K)<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="iw_thics.html-ssi">Ethical Conundra in Information Warfare</a> examines a number of issues that must be considered before the military can launch IW offensives. (20K)<BR>
<BR>

<LI>Written by Col. Charles Dunlop, USAF,<a href="dragon.html-ssi">Sometimes The Dragon Wins</a> is a <B>Must Read</B> for anyone involved in Infowar. Col. Dunlap also wrote <I>How We Lost the High-Tech War of 2007: A Warning from the Future </I> a seminal work on the topic. This paper was first presented at InfoWarCon IV, Brussels, May, 1996. (53K - and worth every byte!)<BR>

<BR>
<LI>Some people say Infowar is just Infosec revisited. This article by Winn Schwartau says <a href="iw_x_is.html-ssi">Infowar Is Not Just Infosec With a Budget</a>. Naysayers beware. (10K)<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="stein1.html-ssi">INFORMATION WAR - CYBERWAR - NETWAR </a>by George J. Stein is a thoughful analysis on the issues. Includes observations on different aspects and views and terminologies. (50K)<BR>
<BR>
<LI><a href="szfran.html-ssi">An Information Warfare SIIOP</a> by Richard Szafranski, Colonel, USAF (Ret.) Air War College National Military Strategy Chair. His concepts on a Single Interagency Information Operations Plan. (32K)<BR>
<BR>

<LI>Paul Strassman's interesting comments in his article<a href="strass.html-ssi">The Thickness of Concrete on the Maginot Line</A><BR>
<BR>
<LI>News on <a href="chinaiw.html-ssi">Chinese Information Warfare</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI>Shane D. Deichman of NCCOSC RDT&amp;E Division writes <a href="deich.html-ssi">On Information War</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI> If the facts get in the way of a theory, then the theory should be discarded, not the facts of
history. Written by R.L. DiNardo and Daniel J. Hughes <a href="dinardo.html-ssi">Some Cautionary Thoughts on Information Warfare</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI> Comments from Moscow about their attitudes to <a href="mil_c4i1.html-ssi">Information Warfare.</a><BR>
<BR>
<LI> The final schedule for <a href="mil_c4i2.html-ssi">Global Business Intelligence</a>
, Sept 18, 1996. Winn Schwartau will be a featured speaker.<BR>

</UL>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
