<HEAD><TITLE>

New Fingerprint System

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="class_1.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/sponsors.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad6.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/class1.gif">
</td>

<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
UK: CONNECTED - COUNTING ON FINGERTIP PRECISION.<BR>
By PATRICK HOOK.
</h3>
</center><BR>
<p>December 31, 1996</p>


<P> Police will be able to compare marks found at the scene of a crime with 4.5
million others.
 
<P>AN AMERICAN space exploration company is hoping to ensure that many more British
criminals are caught and convicted. As part of a $100 million contract, TRW, a
systems integration company that was largely responsible for providing the
high-technology input to the Apollo space programme, is now busy designing a
computer system that, it hopes, will provide all police forces in England and
Wales with the ability to identify the fingerprints of known criminals within
seconds.
<P>The scheme is expected to go "live" in September 1997, with the last forces
getting their equipment by the year 2001.
<P>The new system will, according to Home Office sources, be capable of checking
more than a million fingerprints a second from any of the 50 or so fingerprint
bureaux in England and Wales.
<P>The National Automated Fingerprint Identification System (NAFIS) is expected to
be the most advanced system of its kind anywhere in the world, enabling police
to compare marks found at the scene of a crime with the 4.5 million sets of
<P>"10-print" fingerprints in the national collection at Hendon, a procedure that
is not routinely carried out except in the most serious cases.
<P>"Even for quite serious offences, the police service does not currently have the
ability to compare marks found at the scenes of crimes against the national
fingerprint collection," said John Hoddinott, Chief Constable of Hampshire.
<P>"To do so would take weeks, and even with our current automated system we search
only against our own, local fingerprint collection."
<P>The Home Office specification nearly doubles the existing ability of computer
software to match accurately fingerprints found at the scene with those taken
from prisoners, and has demanded a response time of less than one hour.
When it was first announced in September 1991, the Home Office originally
intended that the system should follow in the footsteps of a similar project
being developed in America for the FBI, but which is now 18 months behind
schedule and $119 million over budget.
<P>Standing in the wings is the British AFR Consortium of 32 UK police forces,
which, at the end of November, completed the roll-out of its own system,
covering about 75 per cent of the population in England and Wales.
Although tight-lipped in public, the consortium is known to be interested in
providing the national fingerprint identification system if the TRW solution
should collapse.
<P>"You may wish to draw the conclusion that the AFR Consortium is ideally placed
to provide a national AFR system in the event that TRW fails," said Mr
Hoddinott, "but I could not possibly comment."
<P>Meanwhile, the NAFIS project continues, apparently on time and on course. If it
achieves what is expected, it will mean that officers will, for the first time,
have access to the identity of prisoners within an hour of arrest, will know the
identity of a burglar within seconds of arriving at the scene of a crime and
will, again for the first time, be able to link suspects to crimes committed
anywhere in England and Wales.
<P>(c) Telegraph Group Limited, London, 1996. 
<P>UNITED KINGDOM <BR>
DAILY TELEGRAPH 24/12/96 P3 </P>

<BR>


</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>
